<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 21:11:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Feb. 26, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	US Gives Colombia Drug Ally Status  
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- The United States on Friday fully  
certified Colombia -- by far the world's No. 1 cocaine producer -- as 
an ally in the war on drugs. The decision is a crucial vote of 
confidence in President Andres Pastrana's young government, his 
foreign minister said. Guillermo Fernandez de Soto said the nation 
would not fail in its efforts to fight drug trafficking ``so that 
Colombia can never again be treated by the community of nations as 
if it were a pariah.'' President Clinton also certified Mexico 
Friday as a fully cooperating partner with U.S. counternarcotics 
efforts. 

</P>
<P>
	Gains Cited in Drug War  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States and allied countries made  
``solid gains'' in efforts to control narcotics trafficking in 
1998, the State Department said Friday, citing progress in crop 
reduction, drug interdiction and other areas. In its annual report 
on the illicit drug trade worldwide, the department said the most 
encouraging development in 1998 was the continued downward trend in 
illicit coca cultivation. The State Department study said overall 
coca cultivation in the Andean countries fell 17 percent to 471,000 
acres last year. The most dramatic decline was in Peru, once the 
world's largest coca producer, the report said. 

</P>
<P>
	Serb Border Police Detain Monitors  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Serb border police detained  
diplomatic observers and forcibly searched their cars in an 
incident the chief monitor called ``ominous.'' Police told the 
monitors they were ``suspicious'' about the contents of the 
vehicles. William Walker, head of Kosovo monitors for the 
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, said a 
cease-fire between Yugoslav and ethnic Albanian forces was 
``non-existent'' despite NATO warnings for both sides to abstain 
from violence during a 2 1/2-week suspension of peace talks. 

</P>
<P>
	Iraq Contacts U.N. Weapons Panel  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Iraq has contacted an expert panel that is  
exploring ways to restart U.N. weapons inspections, the panel's 
chairman said Friday. The Iraqi government invited the chairman, 
Brazilian U.N. Ambassador Celso Amorim, to visit Baghdad. The 
disarmament panel is holding its first meeting this week and will 
initially assess the state of the eight-year U.N. effort to rid 
Iraq of its nuclear, chemical and biological weapons and long-range 
missiles. 

</P>
<P>
	Libya Suspect Deadline Extended  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The United States and Britain gave Libya  
one more month to turn over two suspects for trial in the 1988 Pan 
Am Lockerbie bombing. British Ambassador Jeremy Greenstock said 
London and Washington were willing to allow another month for the 
handover because Secretary-General Kofi Annan had expressed 
``cautious optimism'' that his diplomatic efforts might succeed. 

</P>
<P>
	China Criticized on Human Rights  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- China's human rights record deteriorated  
sharply late last year with a crackdown on political dissent that 
reversed recent signs of improvement, the Clinton administration 
said Friday. The administration's critical assessment of China's 
human rights performance came on the eve of Secretary of State 
Madeleine Albright's departure for Beijing and a day after the 
Senate urged the administration to push for a resolution condemning 
China at the U.N. Human Rights Commission's meeting next month in 
Geneva. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Down 59.76  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices fell for the fourth day in a row.  
The Dow Jones industrial average ended down 59.76 at 9,306.58. On 
the NYSE, losers led gainers 1,511-1,458. The Nasdaq composite 
index fell 38.81 to 2,288.01. 

</P>
<P>
	Pistons Edge Heat 95-93  
</P>
<P>
	AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Bison Dele's dunk with 2.7 seconds  
gave the Detroit Pistons a 95-93 victory over Miami on Friday 
night, ending the Heat's seven-game winning streak. Dele rolled off 
a screen, took a pass from Grant Hill and drove for the open dunk. 
Miami rushed back down the court, but Terry Porter's 25-footer 
bounced off the rim at the buzzer. Miami hadn't lost since falling 
108-101 in Boston on Feb. 9. Hill led Detroit with 22 points and 10 
rebounds, while Joe Dumars added 21. Alonzo Mourning led the Heat 
with 29 points. 

</P>
<P>
	Rodman Makes His Debut With Lakers  
</P>
<P>
	INGLEWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- Dennis Rodman, the purple and gold in  
his hair complementing his Los Angeles Lakers new outfit, got a 
brief standing ovation when he entered Friday night's game against 
the Los Angeles Clippers at the Forum. He replaced Travis Knight at 
forward midway through the first quarter. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by STEPHANIE GASKELL  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
