<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 06:03:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 4th Day of Violence in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMBON, Indonesia (AP) -- Soldiers fired in the air today to  
disperse rioters who were burning houses in a fourth day of 
religious violence in an Indonesian town. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 24 people have died in the violence between Christian  
and Muslim gangs this week in and around the city of Ambon, the 
capital of Maluku province, and thousands of refugees have fled on 
boats. 
</P>
<P>
	Christian mobs threw stones at the homes of Muslim government  
officials today and set fire to several houses. Police dispersed 
the crowd with volleys of gunfire into the air. 
</P>
<P>
	In another part of Ambon, about 1,000 people protested  
peacefully outside the police headquarters to protest officers' 
shooting of gang members. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 3,500 Muslims took shelter in a city mosque after their  
homes were burned down or wrecked in the riots. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have nothing now,'' said one refugee, Rahma Suli, 37.  
</P>
<P>
	At the height of the Ambon fighting this week, mobs battled each  
other with swords, bows and arrows and gasoline bombs. Soldiers 
fired on the rioters repeatedly in an attempt to disperse them. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 150 people have died in rioting on several Maluku  
islands this year. In riots last month, more than 3,300 houses and 
two dozen churches and mosques were burned. 
</P>
<P>
	A U.S.-based human rights group warned that the violence could  
increase ``polarization'' ahead of June parliamentary elections in 
the predominantly Muslim nation of 210 million people. 
</P>
<P>
	The deepening divisions could result in ``channeling political  
debate into communal issues,'' Human Rights Watch said in a 
statement Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The elections are expected to be the fairest in more than four  
decades, and follow the ouster last year of authoritarian President 
Suharto. However, there are fears of violence between rival 
political factions. 
</P>
<P>
	Ambon is 1,400 miles east of Jakarta, the Indonesian capital.  
</P>
<P>
	The Indonesian-controlled territory of East Timor, meanwhile,  
continues to see tensions between pro-independence factions and 
their opponents. Some 500 East Timorese marched with anti-violence 
banners today in Dili, 1,250 miles east of Jakarta, as they buried 
a pro-independence activist killed by Indonesian soldiers on 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Another separatist and a soldier were killed the same day, all  
in separate incidents in tensions that have swelled since Indonesia 
said it could give independence to the territory, held since 1975. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
