<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gretzky To Miss First Game in 223 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Wayne Gretzky will be sidelined for two weeks  
with a neck injury, breaking a 223-game consecutive game streak. 
</P>
<P>
	The 38-year-old Gretzky has not missed a game in his three  
seasons with the New York Rangers. He first complained about neck 
pains after a January game in Washington and was later knocked to 
the ice against Carolina and complained about his back. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, he missed practice, saying he was unable to grip  
his stick because of pains in his arms. 
</P>
<P>
	He underwent an MRI Thursday and the Rangers announced Friday  
that he will miss two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Gretzky leads the team in scoring with 8 goals and 49 assists  
for 57 points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990226.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 15:25:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Salt Lake To Tone Down IOC Perks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The city that gave the Olympics ski vacations,  
knee replacements, college scholarships and pocketfuls of cash 
wants to tone down the perks IOC members get during the games. 
</P>
<P>
	The Salt Lake Organizing Committee is prepared to renegotiate  
the millions of dollars it spends on ``pomp and ceremony'' 
surrounding International Olympic Committee delegates when they 
come in 2002, SLOC chairman Robert Garff said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Garff would not identify areas where SLOC might try to cut back  
and said ``cultural exchanges'' such as the opening and closing 
ceremonies would not be touched. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said that, in light of the Olympic bribery scandal that  
erupted from Salt Lake's winning bid for the 2002 Winter Games, it 
was proper that the public expect some changes in the often lavish 
treatment of IOC members. 
</P>
<P>
	``Salt Lake City in general is a very conservative community,''  
Garff said. ``We have a lot of wealthy people driving Chevrolets. 
We don't wear our wealth on our sleeves. That's just part of who we 
are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like all Olympic cities, Salt Lake signed a contract with the  
IOC that, among other things, promises certain standards of 
hospitality for the committee's 100-plus members during their stay 
at the games, including quality hotel rooms and transportation. 
</P>
<P>
	While that contract is secret, SLOC board member Ken Bullock has  
estimated that the pricetag for keeping the committee comfortable 
comes to $10 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Garff, speaking after addressing the International Radio and  
Television Society Foundation, said SLOC recognized its obligation 
to the IOC but would not hesitate to try to cut costs. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are the franchisee, they are the franchisor,'' he said.  
``We do have a budget with relation to protocol. But that budget is 
a living document that changes with time. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are in the process of talking with them about a number of  
things that we believe will help return the spotlight to sports and 
the athletes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garff said the opening ceremonies, which attract an  
international television audience of some 3 billion, and similar 
cultural showcases should not be touched. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are a big part of the Olympic moment,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Salt Lake's Olympic moment for the last three months has focused  
on the worst corruption case in games history. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine IOC members have resigned or been expeled, and a Salt Lake  
ethics panel said 24 delegates benefited from $1.2 million in cash, 
scholarships, travel, medical expenses and other improper 
inducements from Utah bidders. 
</P>
<P>
	``When it came to that vote, the bid managers decided they  
weren't going to lose this one,'' Garff told the society's monthly 
``Newsmaker'' luncheon. ``They became overzealous and, while the 
board had given them approval to use Plan A, they instituted Plan 
B. There needed to be better oversight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garff, SLOC's new chief executive Mitt Romney and senior vice  
president of communications Shelley Thomas said the committee had 
acted quickly and strongly to deal with the scandal and get back on 
the road to the games. 
</P>
<P>
	``The process of selecting Olympic cities needs changing,''  
Garff said. ``We hope we will be a catalyst for change.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
