<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990226.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 13:26:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Feb. 26, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Sen. Kerry Won't Run for President  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Sen. John Kerry of Massachusetts announced today  
he will skip the 2000 presidential race. The three-term Democratic 
senator cited fund-raising concerns and party unity as major 
factors in his decision not to run. ``I have concluded that to 
raise the necessary amount of money with only 10 months to do so, 
compounded by the newly accelerated primary schedule, is simply 
impossible at this time,'' he said. Kerry also said that pulling 
out of the race could help Vice President Al Gore win the 
Democratic nomination and ``may be more helpful to our party's 
efforts.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Outlines Foreign Policy  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- President Clinton today outlined a foreign  
policy of active involvement overseas -- from China to Kosovo -- for 
the final two years of his administration, saying Americans ``must 
embrace the inexorable logic of globalization.'' He also offered a 
defense of China on the same day that the State Department reported 
a sharp erosion of human rights in that country. Aides billed the 
president's speech to California business and policy leaders as a 
major address laying out his goals for the remainder of his term. 
The president has faced criticism over the continued standoff with 
Iraq and the peace talks on Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton OKs Mexico on Drugs  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- President Clinton said today that he is  
certifying Mexico as a fully cooperating partner in the fight 
against drug trafficking. ``Mexico is cooperating with us in the 
battle for our lives,'' Clinton said. The announcement set up a 
potential battle with Republicans in Congress who cite Mexico's 
drop in narcotics seizures and disappointing record of extraditions 
in arguing for sanctions against America's southern neighbor. But 
in a foreign policy address to California business leaders, Clinton 
credited Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo, saying he was ``working 
hard to tackle the corruption traffickers headlong.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Marine Jet Pilot Testifies  
</P>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- Marine Capt. Richard Ashby testified  
today at his court-martial about how his jet struck an Italian ski 
gondola cable, killing 20 people. ``Mistakes were made on this 
flight -- and any flight, any mission you fly, mistakes are made,'' 
he said. ``We never intentionally did anything outside the scope of 
this mission, which was to try to maintain 1,000 feet'' and use 
terrain features to practice avoiding enemy radar. The Mount Cermis 
ski lift accident occurred Feb. 3, 1998. 

</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavs Block Kosovo Monitors  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Western peace monitors were blocked  
from entering Kosovo today by Yugoslav border police. The 
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe said 21 
monitors were kept out for a second-straight day until their cars 
and luggage were searched. The monitors refused to be searched, 
invoking diplomatic immunity. It's the latest confrontation 
involving the monitors, whom Serbs accuse of supporting ethnic 
Albanian rebels fighting for the independence of Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	GDP Grows at 6.1 Pct. Rate  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite the global financial crisis, the U.S.  
economy grew at a sizzling 6.1 percent annual rate in the final 
three months of 1998, the fastest pace in nearly 15 years. The 
Commerce Department reported today on the gross domestic product, 
the nation's total output of goods and services. On Wall Street, 
investors worried that unless there is a slowdown soon, the Federal 
Reserve will start raising interest rates to keep inflation at bay. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Lower; Dow Off 24.72  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell today. Just before the close, the  
Dow industrials were at 9,341.62, down 24.72. On the NYSE, losers 
led gainers 1,540-1,387. Just before the hour, the Nasdaq Composite 
Index was at 2289.11, down 37.71. 

</P>
<P>
	HHS Recommends Cigar Warning Labels  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Cigars, which scientists say are just as  
deadly as cigarettes, should carry similar health warning labels, 
the Department of Health and Human Services recommended today. The 
inspector general also released a report today from a series of 
focus groups with young people about cigar use. It found more than 
a third of the teen-agers in the groups admitted having smoked a 
cigar in the past month. 

</P>
<P>
	No. 2 Lady Vols Beat Florida  
</P>
<P>
	CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) -- Tamika Catchings scored a career-high  
38 points and Chamique Holdsclaw added 19 as No. 2 Tennessee 
rebounded from its second loss this season by routing Florida 92-80 
today in the Southeastern Conference tournament. Tennessee (26-2) 
will play the winner of No. 23 Auburn and 24th-ranked Alabama in 
tomorrow's semifinals. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
