<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> John Sargent's Drawings on Display </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- John Singer Sargent was just under 5 years old  
when he did his first recorded portrait. He went on to do hundreds 
of them and become the most famous American portraitist of the 
1800s. 
</P>
<P>
	``While I was engaged in writing to you,'' Dr. FitzWilliam  
Sargent said in a letter shortly before his son's birthday, ``John 
has had the impertinence to take my portrait, which I enclose, 
thinking you will prize it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sixty-six of Sargent's drawings and two watercolors are now  
gathered in a show called ``Sketch Everything and Keep Your 
Curiosity Fresh.'' That first sketch as a boy is not included -- 
curators would like to show it, but say they don't know where to 
find it. 
</P>
<P>
	The title of the exhibit, which opened this month at the  
Corcoran Gallery of Art, is a bit of advice from the artist. The 
exhibit of sketches is running roughly at the same time as a major 
exhibit of Sargent's work at the National Gallery of Art -- 
including many of his most famous portraits. 
</P>
<P>
	Sargent did many watercolors and especially liked scenes in  
Venice, one of which is in the Corcoran show. A biographer has 
counted more than 600 portraits he did in his career, but more than 
2,500 other pictures -- landscapes, still lifes, cityscapes and 
canalscapes. 
</P>
<P>
	The last 30 years of his life were devoted in large part to  
murals for the Boston Public Library, the Boston Museum of Fine 
Arts and the Widener Memorial Library at Harvard University. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the drawings in the Corcoran exhibit are studies for  
these murals, which are less known than his portraits. But Sargent 
was quoted as saying that his work in the public library -- the 
``Triumph of Religion'' -- was his most significant. Bostonians 
sometimes call these murals, now due for cleaning and restoration, 
``the Sistine Chapel of the West.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990226.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 05:28:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brits May Help BMW With Assistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MUNICH, Germany (AP) -- Bayerische Motoren Werke AG is in talks  
with the British government for financial assistance to revive its 
Rover division, but declined to comment on a report its is seeking 
at least $240 million. 
</P>
<P>
	BMW spokesman Uwe Mahla said Friday the talks are intense and  
that aid will be crucial in deciding whether BMW will relocate 
Rover production outside Britain. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, BMW said it was eyeing Hungary as an  
alternative location. 
</P>
<P>
	The Financial Times reported Friday that BMW is seeking public  
aid of between $240 million and $320 million to keep the troubled 
Rover plant at Longbridge, near Birmingham, in operation. 
</P>
<P>
	The London-based newspaper also said BMW is expected to announce  
at the Geneva Motor Show in early March a $2.7 billion project to 
replace Rover's 200 and 400 models. 
</P>
<P>
	Mahla declined to comment on the report and repeated previous  
company statements that it is still considering whether to build a 
medium-sized car to compete with the Volkswagen Golf. 
</P>
<P>
	Mahla said, however, that the Longbridge plant has priority if  
the company decides to build a new Rover, stressing again that the 
decision depends on subsidies from the British government. 
</P>
<P>
	He also denied that BMW would take another auto company in as a  
partner for such a project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990226.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 11:24:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stanley Front-Runner After Mo Vaughn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT MYERS, Fla. (AP) -- It's Opening Day and Boston's new first  
baseman trots to the position once owned by Mo Vaughn. Chances are 
it will be Mike Stanley. 
</P>
<P>
	The ex-catcher, as thoughtful with his comments as Vaughn was  
emotional, downplays the comparisons. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not here to replace Mo,'' says Stanley, who has inherited  
Vaughn's locker at the Red Sox spring training complex. ``I was on 
the team last year at the end of the year. I wasn't signed in the 
offseason to replace him. In a way, that's good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After hitting .337, his fifth straight season at .300 or better,  
and leading the team with 40 homers, Vaughn signed with Anaheim. 
Other free agent first basemen Rafael Palmeiro and Will Clark 
didn't sign with the Red Sox, and Boston's interest in Chicago's 
Frank Thomas hasn't resulted in a trade. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Sox have two other first base candidates, but Jose  
Offerman was Kansas City's second baseman the past two seasons and 
could play there or designated hitter, and Reggie Jefferson is 
returning from back problems and can't field as well as Stanley. 
</P>
<P>
	While manager Jimy Williams remains noncommittal, Stanley,  
entering his 14th major-league season, has the inside track on 
Vaughn's job. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just because I'm playing the position that he was playing last  
year that doesn't mean I've got to do what he does,'' Stanley said. 
``This team went to the playoffs last year. If we could each push 
each other to drive in 10 or 15 more runs apiece or hit five more 
home runs, we'll be able to make up for what Mo did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Defensively, the Red Sox might not lose much.  
</P>
<P>
	``He made the transition from being a catcher to a very, very  
good first baseman,'' Williams said of Stanley. ``He has good 
hands.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 35 games at first base last year with Toronto and Boston,  
Stanley made one error in 298 chances, a fielding percentage of 
.997. In 142 games, Vaughn made 12 errors in 1,277 chances, a .991 
percentage. 
</P>
<P>
	Stanley spent spring training last year preparing to be  
Toronto's first baseman in place of the injured Carlos Delgado. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was really enjoying the idea of playing there quite a bit  
because Carlos wasn't supposed to come back until June,'' Stanley 
said. ``Then it was May. Next thing you know, it was two weeks into 
April, so it was hard to let that go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While he's not the hitting threat Vaughn is, Stanley has power.  
In 145 games last season, he had a career-high 29 homers with 79 
RBIs and hit .256. After being obtained from Toronto on July 30, he 
had seven homers, 32 RBIs and a .288 average in 47 games with 
Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	In six years as a part-time player with Texas and one with the  
New York Yankees, Stanley was a mediocre hitter. After hitting .249 
for three consecutive seasons, he hit. 305 with 26 homers in 1993 
for the Yankees. He followed that in 1994 with 17 homers and a .300 
average. 
</P>
<P>
	In 218 games with Boston in 1996 and 1997, he hit 37 homers  
before being traded back to New York. He's hit .280 over the last 
six seasons with an average of 22 homers and thinks he can improve. 
</P>
<P>
	``I drove in 79 last year. I think I can drive in more runs than  
that,'' Stanley said. ``Nobody in here had tremendous years, other 
than Nomar (Garciaparra) and Mo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Sox might miss Vaughn's leadership as much as his bat,  
but the 35-year-old Stanley can fill some of the void, although his 
style is different. 
</P>
<P>
	``He brings quiet leadership,'' Williams said. ``There are times  
when he'll stand up and make some statements. Because he's not 
trying to make those statements all the time, when he does, I think 
an awful lot of people, myself included, take notice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stanley likes the low-key approach.  
</P>
<P>
	``I have no problem saying something but I'm not as vocal as  
Mo,'' Stanley said. ``I wouldn't yell and scream and rant and rave 
like he did to get the players' attention.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No, Stanley just wants to slip quietly into the position  
occupied by Vaughn for the last eight seasons. Besides, he's used 
to being touted as a replacement for an outstanding player. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last year, when I signed with Toronto, I was supposed to take  
Joe Carter's place,'' Stanley said. ``I said, `Wait a minute, this 
guy's a World Series hero.' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of unfair to a player to say you've got to do what  
this guy did.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990226.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 13:35:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Stocks End Down; Dow Off 59.76 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock indexes fell today, led by a selloff in  
technology shares, after Compaq Computer's warning of soft sales 
raised concerns of slowdown in the computer market. 
</P>
<P>
	At the close of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was down 59.76 at 9,306.58, expanding Thursday's 
33.33-point decline. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were lower as well.  
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 declined 6.69 to 1,238.33, and the  
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index fell 38.81 to 2.288.01. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by 1,511 to 1,458 on the  
New York Stock Exchange, with 566 unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	NYSE volume totaled 762.85 million shares as of 4 p.m., vs.  
737.17 million in the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index fell 0.97 to 586.46, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index fell 4.82 to 698.29. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 0.33 to 392.36.  
</P>
<P>
	Compaq Computer, the world's biggest maker of personal  
computers, warned analysts that sales in its small- and medium- 
business market have slowed this quarter. That prompted Merrill 
Lynch and Credit Suisse First Boston to cut its first-quarter 
earnings projection for Compaq, whose shares were down nearly 6 
points on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Other computer-makers, including IBM, Gateway and Dell Computer,  
also fell sharply today on concerns that their sales may also slow 
in coming months. 
</P>
<P>
	Also lower in the technology sector was Intel, which fell  
sharply after PC Data reported that Advanced Micro Devices AMD-K6 
processor-based computers outsold all Intel-based desktop PCs in 
the U.S. retail market. It was the first time that Intel fell out 
of the top spot. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel was down more than 8 points in Nasdaq trading.  
</P>
<P>
	The stock market also came under pressure today after the  
Commerce Department reported that the U.S. economy grew at a 
faster-than-expected 6.1 percent annual rate in the final three 
months of 1998, the quickest pace in nearly 15 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Growth in gross domestic product, the nation's total output of  
goods and services, had been originally reported at 5.6 percent for 
the fourth quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	While the report showed the economy growing at a faster pace  
than expected, it also showed that inflation rose just 1 percent 
last year, the slowest pace since a 0.9 percent rise in 1949. 
</P>
<P>
	That boosted bond prices, which have tumbled the last three days  
on worries that the Fed might boost interest rates to keep 
inflation in check. The benchmark 30-year Treasury bond was up a 
little more than $10 for every $1,000 valuation. Its yield, which 
moves opposite the price, fell to 5.58 percent from 5.65 percent 
late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bond market and stock market are watching different parts  
of the report,'' said Sung Won Sohn, chief economist at Norwest 
Corp. in Minneapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	``The stock market is looking at strong economic growth and  
thinking there may be rising interest rates,'' he said. ``Bonds are 
looking at the low inflation.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
