<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Ups Aid to Okla. Bombing Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department awarded an additional  
$342,086 Friday to assist victims and survivors of the 1995 
Oklahoma City federal building bombing, the most deadly terrorist 
attack in this country. 
</P>
<P>
	``The emotional and psychological impact of this horrendous  
crime has affected many people,'' Attorney General Janet Reno said. 
``The effects of such a crime can last long after the last piece of 
rubble has been hauled away and a jury has sentenced a defendant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The department's Office for Victims of Crime has now awarded a  
total of $841,000 to Project Heartland, which has been the 
principal mental health care provider for survivors and relatives 
of victims of the truck-bomb attack that killed 168 people and 
injured hundreds of others. 
</P>
<P>
	Project Heartland, which was created by the Oklahoma Department  
of Mental Health and Substance Abuse Services, ``has greatly 
contributed to the process of healing,'' Reno said. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds have been used to pay for crisis counseling at  
the Safe Haven facilities in Oklahoma City and 650 miles away in 
Denver, where Timothy McVeigh and Terry Nichols were tried and 
convicted in the bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal money also paid for travel and training for staff  
workers and volunteers working with the victims. Some family 
members of the victims traveled to Denver for the trial. 
</P>
<P>
	``The importance of programs, such as Project Heartland, are  
immeasurable,'' said Kathryn Turman, acting director of the victims 
of crime office. ``The tireless efforts of those individuals who 
are involved in these programs provide victims of crime with needed 
support at a most vulnerable time in their lives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The federal office was established in 1984 to fund state victim  
assistance and compensation programs. The Crime Victims Fund, which 
is the source of the funds for Project Heartland, comes solely from 
fines and penalties assessed on federal criminal offenders, not 
from taxpayers. It supports 3,000 victim services agencies, 
including domestic violence shelters and programs to assist victims 
of child abuse and sexual assault and survivors of homicide 
victims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
