<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nonprofit Will Sell Ventura Goods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- The company selling Jesse Ventura  
merchandise apparently will be allowed to operate as a private 
corporation instead of a political committee, meaning it won't have 
to report how it earns or spends money. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Campaign Finance and Public Disclosure Board plans to  
make a formal ruling next month after Friday's preliminary decision 
involving Ventura for Minnesota Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're basically blazing a new trail here,'' said company vice  
president David Olsen, who is also the Minnesota governor's 
personal attorney. 
</P>
<P>
	Olsen said the nonprofit corporation was formed to protect the  
rights to Jesse Ventura's likeness and trademarked moniker ``The 
Body,'' and to raise money for educational and civic programs. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, the company has contracts for Ventura action figures,  
pants, T-shirts, baseball caps, key chains and refrigerator 
magnets. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura's campaign committee will continue to sell merchandise,  
too, with profits that could be used for a future political run. 
The committee is expected to buy from the nonprofit company. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a very strange thing. Nobody's ever seen anything  
quite like this,'' said Doug Freidline, president of Ventura for 
Minnesota Inc. and also the manager of the campaign committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Campaign disclosure board members said they were convinced that  
the company would not operate as a political committee. 
</P>
<P>
	David Schultz, president of Common Cause Minnesota, said he  
wants to make sure that the nonpolitical purpose is enforced. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the general firewall they are trying to draw is a good  
one,'' Schultz said. ``If this money is going to go to charity and 
not for political purposes, then it sounds like a good decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura didn't seem to be clear on that when he spoke earlier  
this week to the National Press Club in Washington, D.C., about the 
corporation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of the money will be donated to charitable cause. And  
we're hoping to get a ruling from ethics that we can use the rest 
of the money to finance a campaign,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Olsen said he didn't know what Ventura was talking about, but  
that the company will not be able to contribute to any political 
campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	A Ventura action figure debuted earlier this month at the  
American International Toy Fair in New York. A Ventura doll was 
first seen in his campaign commercials last year, banging his fist 
on a desk and dismissing ``Evil Special Interest Man.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More than 60,000 of the action figures have been ordered. The  
dolls are expected to be in stores in April, priced at $15 to $20. 
</P>
<P>
	Freidline said some of the money collected through the company  
may be used for public service announcements using the action 
figures to teach children about politics. Other money will be used 
to run the business and the rest will be donated to educational and 
civic programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
