<HEADLINE> Independent Counsel Law Reviewed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Robert Bennett, one of President Clinton's  
attorneys, will lead testimony at a Senate hearing Wednesday into 
whether Congress should renew the act that gave Independent Counsel 
Kenneth Starr his job. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be Bennett's first appearance before a congressional  
panel on an issue connected to the Monica Lewinsky matter, and the 
Senate Governmental Affairs Committee's second hearing into whether 
to renew the law, revise it or let it expire June 30. 
</P>
<P>
	The 21-year-old law is widely disliked by members of both  
parties after independent counsel investigations of Republican and 
Democratic presidents. If Congress lets the law expire, as it did 
in 1992 before renewing it 18 months later, dozens of high-ranking 
government officials who now could be subject to an independent 
counsel probe would be investigated instead by the Justice 
Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Also set to testify Wednesday before panel chaired by Sen. Fred  
Thompson, R-Tenn., is Theodore Olson, an assistant attorney general 
during the Reagan administration who was the target of an 
independent counsel; Nathan Lewin, former counsel to Attorney 
General Edwin Meese; Henry Ruth, leader of the Watergate special 
prosecution force; and Robert Fiske, former special prosecutor for 
the Whitewater investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney General Janet Reno is to testify before the committee  
in mid-March. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the House Subcommittee on Commercial and  
Administrative Law is set to open its own hearings on the law. The 
Justice Department has announced that Deputy Attorney General Eric 
Holder will testify there and may map out at least part of the 
administration's position. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
