<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Phillies Come Down With Flu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) -- Call it the Philly flu.  
</P>
<P>
	It's painful, it moves fast and it swept through the  
Philadelphia Phillies clubhouse faster than a Curt Schilling trade 
rumor. Nearly a third of the 59 players in camp Friday were 
stricken, including starters Scott Rolen, Rico Brogna, Mike 
Lieberthal and No. 1 draft pick Pat Burrell. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I got here at 5:30 in the morning, I found Burrell and  
(Steve) Carver asleep on a table,'' said manager Terry Francona, 
who had managed to ward off the stomach virus -- at least for the 
day. ``They were not looking ready for any extra work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A few players were too sick to even show up at Jack Russell  
Stadium Friday morning. Others came in anyway and were sent home. 
And a few, like Carver, didn't feel anything until after they 
showed up. 
</P>
<P>
	Right-hander Wayne Gomes sat at his locker with his head in his  
hands and a grim look on his face, but insisted on doing his 
scheduled throwing anyway. He went home as soon as he was finished. 
</P>
<P>
	Center fielder Doug Glanville had a fever, worked out briefly  
and was sent home. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got a fever, but he hasn't thrown up yet,'' said  
spokesman Larry Shenk, in his new role as head of the Clearwater 
MASH unit. 
</P>
<P>
	When the team returned from its workout at the Carpenter Complex  
-- about 4 miles from the stadium -- pitching coach Galen Cisco had 
succumbed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm fine, I think,'' Francona said.  
</P>
<P>
	The first one to get sick was left-hander Paul Spoljaric, who  
missed the first day of workouts last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``Spoljaric infects clubhouse,'' lefty Jim Poole joked as the  
now-healthy Spoljaric walked past his locker. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had nothing to do with it,'' Spoljaric said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
