<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 15:34:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Eli Lilly Is Sued Over Evista </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- British drug maker Zeneca Inc. has sued rival  
Eli Lilly &AMP; Co., accusing the company of improperly selling its 
osteoporosis drug Evista as a medication to prevent breast cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Evista is not approved as a breast cancer drug in the United  
States, though early tests look promising. 
</P>
<P>
	Zeneca makes Nolvadex, which in October became the first drug  
approved by the Food and Drug Administration to reduce the risk of 
breast cancer in healthy women. Nolvadex is Zeneca's brand name for 
tamoxifen, which has been used to as a treatment for advanced 
breast cancer for 20 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit filed Thursday in federal court in New York contends  
Lilly has reduced demand for Nolvadex with its marketing of Evista. 
Lilly has allowed its sales staff to claim during meetings with 
doctors that Evista is proven to prevent breast cancer, the lawsuit 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal law bars drug companies from promoting drugs for uses  
not approved by the Food and Drug Administration, although doctors 
are permitted to prescribe drugs for any use they see fit. 
</P>
<P>
	Lilly denied the suit's allegations. ``We feel our promotion of  
Evista is 100 percent appropriate,'' said spokesman Jeff Newton. 
``We're promoting this product for its labeled indication, which is 
osteoporosis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lilly, though, has hopes that Evista will eventually be used to  
prevent breast cancer. Early studies show Evista may work just as 
well as Nolvadex, though large-scale human tests have yet to be 
completed. 
</P>
<P>
	Zeneca said one market study found physicians have begun  
prescribing Evista at least as frequently as Nolvadex to reduce the 
risk of breast cancer. This, the company said, ``poses a grave 
public health risk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Many women have already begun to use Evista instead of  
Nolvadex in the mistaken belief that the drug has been proven to 
reduce their chances of developing breast cancer,'' Zeneca said in 
the suit. 
</P>
<P>
	Lilly, whose biggest-selling drug antidepressant Prozac is  
expected to lose patent protection in 2004, launched Evista early 
in 1998. Lilly targeted a market of women eager for a substitute 
for the hormone estrogen in fighting bone deterioration after 
menopause. However, last year's $138 million in U.S. sales were 
disappointing. 
</P>
<P>
	In comparison, Nolvadex had $369 million in U.S. sales last  
year. Since October, the number of U.S. prescriptions written for 
Nolvadex has been flat at about 66,000 per month, according to 
market data firm IMS Health. In the same period, the number of 
prescriptions for Evista rose from 220,000 in October to 261,000 in 
December, IMS said. 
</P>
<P>
	In trading Friday on the New York Stock Exchange, Lilly was up  
$1.25 at $94.50, while Zeneca's U.S. shares were down $1 at $41.06 1/4 
a share. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990226.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 16:32:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dodgers Want Pitching Depth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VERO BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Los Angeles Dodgers manager Davey  
Johnson wants to keep six veteran starters competing for five spots 
in the rotation. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said Friday he isn't considering a six-man rotation --  
something the New York Mets tried last season -- but he would like a 
sixth starter with major league experience on the roster as 
insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	``You need to have that depth,'' Johnson said. ``You end up  
having injuries, so the depth is important. That's what the Yankees 
had last year by keeping six or seven starters around. Atlanta's 
pretty much the same way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dodger officials say they aren't close to making any decisions  
about Kevin Brown, Chan Ho Park, Ismael Valdes, Carlos Perez, 
Darren Dreifort and Dave Mlicki. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Mlicki has been mentioned in trade rumors this spring.  
</P>
<P>
	General manager Kevin Malone said at the beginning of camp that  
he probably would attempt to trade whichever starter didn't crack 
the rotation. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dodgers could use an extra left-handed reliever and an  
experienced backup catcher. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Dodgers leave Mlicki out of the rotation, they still  
could keep him in the bullpen or use him as a spot starter. 
</P>
<P>
	Mlicki said he enjoys pitching in Los Angeles and might consider  
a move to the bullpen if it allowed him to remain with the team. 
But he prefers to start. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I've proved myself as a starter and I prefer that  
role,'' Mlicki said. ``I'm more of a routine-type guy. I like 
knowing what I'm going to do every day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mlicki went 1-4 with a 5.68 ERA for the New York Mets last year,  
then went 7-3 with a 4.05 ERA after coming to Los Angeles in the 
trade that sent Hideo Nomo to New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``All six of them deserve to be in a rotation somewhere,''  
Malone said. ``We just have to figure out which five are best for 
us. There's no clear-cut odd man out.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
