<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Fall Further / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) --Grain and soybean futures extended their slide  
Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid a fundamentally weak 
supply-and-demand picture. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans and wheat posted new lows amid expectations of large  
deliveries of grain to satisfy contracts expiring in March. Futures 
prices have been pressured by expectations U.S. inventories will 
remain sharply higher this year amid weak demand from Asia and huge 
harvests in South America. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans also were pressured by plunging soybean oil prices.  
Soybean oil fell to 11-year lows amid concern China, one of the 
largest buyers of U.S. exports, will cancel orders. India and 
Pakistan recently canceled their orders as a 20 percent decline in 
prices prompted them to move to the sidelines and wait for a 
bottom. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures fell mostly in sympathy with wheat and soybeans.  
Corn inventories are expected to fall slightly as demand remains 
fairly steady for the crop in feed and other uses. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for March delivery fell 1 1/2 cents to $2.37 1/4 a bushel; March  
corn fell 2 1/4 cents to $2.04 1/2 a bushel; March oats rose 4 1/4 cents to 
$1.04 3/4 a bushel; March soybeans fell 4 3/4 cents to $4.49 3/4 a bushel; 
March soybean oil fell 0.37 cent to 17.62 cents a pound. 
</P>
<P>
	Pork futures fell sharply on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange as  
slaughterhouses appeared content to wait for lower prices. Beef 
futures also retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	April live cattle fell 0.68 cent to 68.02 cents a pound; March  
feeder cattle fell 0.30 cent to 74.17 cents a pound; April lean 
hogs fell 1.15 cents to 43 cents a pound; March pork bellies fell 
1.05 cents to 49.50 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
