<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orie Tries To Hang On With Marlins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MELBOURNE, Fla. (AP) -- Thirty minutes after the day's final  
spring training drill, Kevin Orie still has a bat in his hand and 
perspiration on his brow. His job is in jeopardy, and that's enough 
to make anyone sweat. 
</P>
<P>
	Once touted as the Chicago Cubs' best third baseman since Ron  
Santo, Orie was bust at Wrigley Field. Now he's trying to hang on 
with the Florida Marlins, baseball's worst team last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've hardened a good bit,'' said Orie, 26. ``I guess it's my  
turn to experience the ups and downs of the game. But I've had 
enough for a while. Let me rest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A month ago, Orie figured a spot in the Marlins' lineup was his.  
Then they acquired top prospect Mike Lowell from the New York 
Yankees to compete for the job at third. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, just before spring training started, Lowell was  
diagnosed with testicular cancer. Following surgery and brief 
radiation treatment, he's expected to join the team, although the 
timetable is uncertain. 
</P>
<P>
	``When Mike comes back, there will be competition at third  
base,'' manager John Boles said. 
</P>
<P>
	The difficult situation has left Orie rooting for Lowell, 25.  
</P>
<P>
	``I just hope he feels better,'' Orie said. ``My grandfather  
died of cancer. When something like this happens, it puts 
everything into perspective. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully good things will happen for both of us. I know this  
is his best chance too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The stakes are high because only one of the two will make the  
Marlins' 25-man roster. 
</P>
<P>
	Orie hit .263 with six homers in 48 games last year after the  
Cubs traded him and two young pitchers to the Marlins for reliever 
Felix Heredia. His career average is .246 with 16 homers in 226 
games over two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowell spent almost all of the past two years in the minors,  
hitting .309 with 56 homers and 191 RBIs. The Marlins traded three 
pitching prospects to get him. 
</P>
<P>
	``People say, `You have to be leaning toward keeping Lowell  
because you traded a lot to get him,' '' Boles said. ``Well, we 
traded a lot to get Kevin Orie, too. Felix Heredia is no slouch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A native of suburban Pittsburgh, Orie ranked among the National  
League rookie leaders in 1997 with eight homers and 44 RBIs. He hit 
.275 in 114 games and ranked second in fielding percentage among NL 
third basemen. 
</P>
<P>
	But last year he was hitting just .179 when demoted to Triple-A  
in late May. He rejoined the Cubs a month later but couldn't regain 
the starting job and was traded to Florida on July 31. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got a new life coming over here, something I needed,'' he  
said. ``As far as I'm concerned, the job is still mine to lose. 
Worrying about it doesn't do any good.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
