<DOCNO> APW19990226.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 13:16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Evista Maker Sues Eli Lilly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- British drug maker Zeneca Inc. has sued rival  
Eli Lilly &AMP; Co., accusing the company of improperly selling its 
osteoporosis drug Evista as a medication to prevent breast cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Evista is not approved as a breast cancer drug in the United  
States, though early tests look promising. 
</P>
<P>
	Zeneca makes Nolvadex, which in October became the first drug  
approved by the Food and Drug Administration to reduce the risk of 
breast cancer in healthy women. Nolvadex is Zeneca's brand name for 
tamoxifen, which has been used as a treatment for advanced breast 
cancer for 20 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit filed Thursday in federal court in New York contends  
Lilly has reduced demand for Nolvadex with its marketing of Evista. 
Lilly has allowed its sales staff to claim during meetings with 
doctors that Evista is proven to prevent breast cancer, the lawsuit 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal law bars drug companies from promoting drugs for uses  
not approved by the Food and Drug Administration, although doctors 
are permitted to prescribe drugs for any use they see fit. 
</P>
<P>
	Lilly denied the suit's allegations. ``We feel our promotion of  
Evista is 100 percent appropriate,'' said spokesman Jeff Newton. 
``We're promoting this product for its labeled indication, which is 
osteoporosis''. 
</P>
<P>
	Lilly, though, has hopes that Evista will eventually be used to  
prevent breast cancer. Early studies show Evista may work just as 
well as Nolvadex, though large-scale human tests have yet to be 
completed. 
</P>
<P>
	Zeneca said one market study found physicians have begun  
prescribing Evista at least as frequently as Nolvadex to reduce the 
risk of breast cancer. This, the company said, ``poses a grave 
public health risk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Many women have already begun to use Evista instead of  
Nolvadex in the mistaken belief that the drug has been proven to 
reduce their chances of developing breast cancer,'' Zeneca said in 
the suit. 
</P>
<P>
	Lilly, whose biggest-selling drug antidepressant Prozac is  
expected to lose patent protection in 2004, launched Evista early 
in 1998. Lilly targeted a market of women eager for a substitute 
for the hormone estrogen in fighting bone deterioration after 
menopause. However, last year's $138 million in U.S. sales were 
disappointing. 
</P>
<P>
	In comparison, Nolvadex had $369 million in U.S. sales last  
year. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990226.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 14:56:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Big Mac Getting the Star Treatment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JUPITER, Fla. (AP) -- At 5:30 a.m. Friday, the lights were  
burning at the St. Louis Cardinals' spring training complex. 
</P>
<P>
	It's never too early in the day for the spotlights to shine on  
Mark McGwire. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, it was ABC's ``Good Morning America,'' yet another  
one of the TV shows clamoring to interview baseball's new home run 
king. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire chatted with host Charles Gibson about his 15-second  
visit with Pope John Paul II, discussed his boyhood hero (his 
father) and on a question relayed from Diane Sawyer, answered that 
yes, he gets sore early in spring training. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire said he gets through it by dunking himself daily in an  
ice tank. 
</P>
<P>
	``It gets better as each day goes along,'' McGwire said.  
</P>
<P>
	During the offseason, McGwire appeared on NBC's ``Today'' show,  
``Late Show'' with David Letterman and Rosie O'Donnell's talk show. 
He made his acting debut on ``Mad About You.'' 
</P>
<P>
	```The `Today' Show was great, the Rosie show was great, they  
were all great,'' McGwire said. 
</P>
<P>
	After drawing nearly 3.2 million during the 1998 regular season  
-- a team record -- the Cardinals already have sold 2,215,000 tickets 
for home game this year, up 433,000 from this point last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Their season-ticket base is up 2,100 to 20,300 despite a 12  
percent hike in prices. McGwire, who gets $1 for every home ticket 
sold above 2.8 million, figures to collect on that again. The bonus 
earned him $395,021 last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know Mark is not resting on his laurels, and our fans aren't  
resting on their laurels, either,'' Cardinals managing partner Bill 
DeWitt said. ``He's really taken it to a new level.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Outside the playing field, McGwire is increasing his charitable  
efforts beyond the $1 million he annually donates to his foundation 
for sexually abused children. He's working on a web site called 
``McGwire's Kids'' to debut in June or July, with information on 
various types of abuse and interviews with psychologists. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be exciting,'' McGwire said. ``I was like blown  
away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His preference for Starbucks coffee also led to a foundation  
that donates $5,000 to the local literacy program for each homer he 
hits, in the city where he hits it. 
</P>
<P>
	He also might assume a more vocal role in the players'  
association. Earlier this week, McGwire said he would walk away 
from the game if there was another labor stoppage after the current 
labor agreement expires, probably after the 2001 season. He's 
urging both sides to start talking now. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess the only role I can take is to express my opinion,''  
McGwire said. ``I don't care if you're a player or an owner, you 
have to understand we're not heading toward a good thing. Common 
sense says yes, it needs to be done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He's changed his mind about writing a book -- but won't do it  
until after he retires. He said last fall he'd never write a book, 
but that was because wannabe authors were ``hounding'' him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to do it when I'm still playing, because there's  
still things unveiling,'' McGwire said. ``If I write a book now, 
how do I know that's what it's really going to mean to me five 
years or 10 years down the line? So, I think waiting is the best 
thing.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990226.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 14:56:01 </DATE_TIME>
