<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 15:18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Chinese Diving Star Returns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- She's back and, her coach says, diving better  
than ever. 
</P>
<P>
	Fu Mingxia riveted the Olympics when she became a champion at  
all of 13. She won gold medals in 1992 and 1996, then retired at 
19, tired of diving and ready for college. Now she's aiming for the 
Sydney Games next year. 
</P>
<P>
	From the 12-year-old who became the youngest diving world  
champion in 1991, Fu has grown into a confident 21-year-old with a 
ready laugh and twinkling coffee-brown eyes. She's also added gold 
tints to her black hair. 
</P>
<P>
	Although she resumed training only last July after two years  
without a single dive, Fu shows little sign of rust. 
</P>
<P>
	During practice this week, Fu somersaulted, twisted and splashed  
cleanly off the platform, the event in which she won her first 
Olympic gold in Barcelona in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	On the springboard, she was all compact, controlled, muscular  
grace. Fu won the springboard and platform at the Atlanta Olympics 
in 1996, the first woman in 36 years to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	She likened her return to diving to learning how to bicycle.  
</P>
<P>
	``When you first start, you're all wobbly, but the more you  
ride, the smoother you become. That's the feeling,'' Fu said with a 
giggle. 
</P>
<P>
	Spotted at age 10 and brought to Beijing from her home in  
central Hubei province, Fu endured eight or nine hours of training 
a day. Such regimens are typical of China's state-sponsored sports 
machine, which tries to mold its top young athletes into champions. 
</P>
<P>
	When Fu retired after Atlanta, she said she was exhausted and --  
at age 19 -- too old. She enrolled at Beijing's prestigious Qinghua 
University and gained so much weight ``I didn't want to put on a 
swimming costume,'' she said. ``I didn't really miss it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last summer, Fu had second thoughts. She had shed some pounds,  
and Qinghua had set up a diving team. ``I thought I'd come along 
and give it a try, to see if it was still possible for me to be 
good,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ahead of her first platform dive, ``I really was a little  
scared, but I had to pretend I wasn't,'' she said. ``I wasn't very 
good. My splashes were very big.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, ``I've recovered very quickly, better than my coach  
and others expected. I can more or less do everything. I haven't 
forgotten.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now, as part of Qinghua's team, Fu trains more than four hours a  
day, with weekends off. Techno-music thumped from a boom box by the 
pool as Fu scaled the platform and dived off, over and over again. 
She laughed at fluffed dives. She looked relaxed. 
</P>
<P>
	Yu Fen, her longtime coach, said Fu is enjoying her diving and  
is more motivated than when she was younger. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's turned this -- how should I put it? -- into a job, a  
profession, a thing to pursue, a challenge, something she feels she 
has to do. It's not like in the past when everyone made her to do 
it,'' Yu said. ``Now she feels `I have to do this, and I have to do 
this well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fu is not yet as fit as she was when she retired, but  
technically she's ``even better in some areas than she was 
before,'' Yu said. 
</P>
<P>
	Fu's first test comes in March at a national competition. If all  
goes well, Olympic qualifiers are next. If she competes in Sydney, 
and again aims for the platform-springboard double, Fu could become 
the first diver to take five Olympic golds. 
</P>
<P>
	``Her goal, of course, is to pursue Olympic gold. An athlete who  
doesn't pursue Olympic gold is, I think, not a good athlete,'' Yu 
said. ``But this is not her only goal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By studying economics management in the morning and training in  
the afternoon, Fu could challenge a belief in China that top-level 
sports and studies don't mix. She could also prove that athletes, 
many of whom retire young in China, can come back. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are all explorations. If these explorations succeed it  
will play a good promotional role for sport in our country, 
including sports people of the future,'' Yu said. ``What Fu Mingxia 
is doing is very significant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fu and Yu both add, however, that lots of hard work lies ahead.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm starting from zero,'' Fu said. ``I stepped down, so now I  
have to climb back up one step at a time.'' 
</P>
