<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> John Lewis Conducts Duke Ellington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Arts and Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Music that Duke Ellington composed for his band  
during the Blanton-Webster years --1940 to 1942 -- floated on the air 
again when John Lewis conducted the Lincoln Center Jazz Orchestra. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis, musical director of the Modern Jazz Quartet, was a  
teen-ager when he first heard the Ellington Band. That dance 
concert, in 1939 in Albuquerque, N.M., has stayed with him all his 
life. He called the compositions by Ellington and Billy Strayhorn 
``the most beautiful music I know. And it's ours. America's.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis played piano for ``Bojangles,'' Ellington's musical  
portrait of dancer Bill Robinson, and an encore, ``Duke's Place.'' 
Wynton Marsalis played trumpet twice, on a rocking ``Perdido'' and 
on ``Concerto for Cootie,'' composed for trumpeter Cootie Williams. 
He played an exquisite section not used when the piece, with 
lyrics, became ``Do Nothing Till You Hear From Me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Over the years, Ellington changed arrangements. But Thursday  
night, at Alice Tully Hall, the arrangement matched those of the 
early '40s when bassist Jimmy Blanton and tenor saxophonist Ben 
Webster charged the band. 
</P>
<P>
	Strayhorn's ``Chelsea Bridge'' was thrillingly beautiful.  
Ellington's ``Warm Valley'' and ``Ko Ko'' flowed like honey. 
</P>
<P>
	The evening began with sounds of instruments swirling in ``Sepia  
Panorama,'' in a way Ellington enjoyed. The music was bright and 
sharp, though not driving. Ellington's evocative ballad, ``All Too 
Soon,'' conjured thoughts of a romantic woman in chiffon and high 
heels. 
</P>
<P>
	Ellington wrote ``Jack the Bear'' for Blanton, who introduced a  
melodic way to play bass beyond keeping rhythm. Webster 
collaborated with Ellington on ``Cottontail,'' a rouser driven by a 
saxophone that closed the concert. 
</P>
<P>
	The concert, part of the ``Ellington Centennial,'' celebrates  
Ellington's music during the 100th anniversary year of his birth. 
He died at 75 in 1974. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990226.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 20:12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fire Destroys Restaurant Ski Resort </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TRUCKEE, Calif. (AP) -- An early morning fire broke out at an  
empty ski resort near Lake Tahoe on Friday, destroying a 
mountaintop restaurant and causing at least $1.5 million damage. 
</P>
<P>
	Nobody was injured in the fire that destroyed the Summit Deck  
and Grill at the top of the Northstar Ski Resort on Mount Pluto. 
</P>
<P>
	Firefighters climbed the mountain in all-terrain snow cats after  
a worker grooming the slopes reported the flames at 3:51 a.m. They 
ended up letting the fire burn itself out. 
</P>
<P>
	The cause remained under investigation. Arson was not suspected.  
</P>
<P>
	``The one nice thing was the timing. Nobody was here. Nobody was  
hurt,'' said Kelli Twomey, a spokeswoman for the resort. 
</P>
<P>
	Two chair lifts were closed until about 10:30 a.m., but  
otherwise things were back to normal by midday at the Sierra Nevada 
resort between Truckee and Tahoe City, Twomey said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
