<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 13:54:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Phillies' Jordan Knows His Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) -- It's a lonely life for bench players  
like Kevin Jordan. 
</P>
<P>
	Their idols are not Willie Mays, Joe DiMaggio or Hank Aaron,  
because they can relate much better to Jim Eisenreich and Rusty 
Staub. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan, who led the Philadelphia Phillies in pinch-hits for the  
second straight year in 1998, leads a group of role players who are 
among the best and most versatile in the National League. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone wants to play every day,'' said Jordan, third in the  
NL with 15 pinch hits last season. ``I don't think anyone when 
they're coming through the minors, one of their goals is to come up 
and be a pinch hitter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan, valuable not only for his bat but for his versatility as  
a backup infielder, learned from pinch-hitter extraordinaire Jim 
Eisenreich when the left-handed specialist played in Philadelphia. 
Getting 200 at-bats a year isn't what Jordan dreamed of when he was 
playing DiMaggio League baseball and in Little League. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's my role, but it can change day to day,'' Jordan said of  
his pinch-hitting duties. ``We have to be ready, because we might 
be called upon to start every day for a week and we might have to 
sit down every day for a week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The life of a part-time major leaguer isn't always glamorous.  
Phillies manager Terry Francona knows, because he did it for 10 
years. Told that he would never start again after Montreal released 
him in 1985, Francona reached 100 at-bats only once in his last 
five seasons with four teams -- the Cubs, Cincinnati, Cleveland and 
Milwaukee. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was the hardest thing that I ever did,'' Francona said.  
``That was harder for me than quitting baseball. My wife said for 
two years, she thought I was a caged animal. When I retired -- or, I 
like to say, when they retired me -- I didn't miss baseball anymore. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ever heard of a young kid who said it was his dream to be the  
lefty off the bench?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe Francona handles his bench so well because he's been  
there. The 39-year-old manager makes sure there's always a coach 
working with the reserves, and he makes Jordan, Kevin Sefcik and 
Arias feel as though they're a big part of the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know, maybe it's because he was a backup guy,'' Jordan  
said. ``He's the kind of guy that you want to play hard for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Francona said Arias, the backup shortstop behind Desi Relaford,  
will probably pinch-hit more than last year. Jordan, 15-for-54 
(.278) as a pinch-hitter with two homers and 10 RBIs last year, 
remains the top option off the bench. 
</P>
<P>
	``He gives you a quality at-bat against any pitcher,'' Francona  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sefcik, who backs up Doug Glanville in center field, is solid  
defensively and batted .314 last year in a part-time role. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who outworks Sefcik?'' Francona asked. ``Nobody.''  
</P>
<P>
	While this bench brigade won't make as much in their careers as  
Kevin Brown gets in his new $100 million contract, the Phillies 
tried to give them some security. Sefcik and Arias signed two-year 
contracts after last season. Jordan was offered a similar contract, 
but opted for one year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's something that we discussed, I just didn't take one,''  
Jordan said. ``In the future, it's something that, yeah, I'd like 
to stay in Philadelphia. It was the Phillies that gave me a chance 
to play in the major leagues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even if it's only a part-time job.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990226.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 14:56:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Yankees Pull Fast One on Clemens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Roger Clemens was actually smiling on the  
mound Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The five-time Cy Young winner was facing minor league catcher  
Jaime Torres during his first live batting practice stint with the 
New York Yankees when new teammates Derek Jeter and Chuck Knoblauch 
appeared in full catcher's gear. 
</P>
<P>
	The gag went unnoticed by Clemens, who was locked in on pitching  
to Torres, until Knoblauch entered the cage. That prompted a smile, 
a tip of the cap and pitch softly throw behind the second baseman's 
back. 
</P>
<P>
	``He threw his normal pitch up ... a pitch Jeter and I have seen  
before,'' Knoblauch said. ``We were having a good time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens worked on all his pitches during a 10-minute bullpen  
stint and threw 58 pitches during the 13-minute session. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew eventually something would be up ... I think it was a  
good move by them, actually,'' Clemens joked. ``So to make them 
feel right at home, I went ahead and threw those ones behind 
them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jeter and Knoblauch both were hit by Clemens pitches in the past  
and vowed to get even when the Yankees obtained him from Toronto 
last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``The past is over with,'' Jeter said. ``He's part of the team.  
We know it ... he knows it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When informed that Knoblauch had said ``it will take us a while  
to catch up,'' Clemens replied he will ask pitching coach Mel 
Stottlemyre to have the pair assigned to his batting practice group 
if things get out of hand. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, that figures. I didn't think I would get off that  
easy,'' Clemens said. ``They better be careful, because sometimes I 
don't miss.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yankees manager Joe Torre said Clemens will likely start either  
March 6 against Boston or March 7 against Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	Other starters throwing batting practice Friday were David Cone,  
Hideki Irabu and Orlando Hernandez. All three reported no problems 
following their workouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Andy Pettitte is scheduled to throw off a bullpen mound on  
Saturday. The left-hander missed his BP session Wednesday because 
of elbow tenderness. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel fine, said Pettitte, who played catch Friday. ``I'm  
trying to talk them into letting me throw batting practice.'' 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* The Jimmy Key watch is over. Torre said the left-hander has  
decided not to change his decision to retire. Although not ruling 
out a trade, the Yankees will look closely at filling from within 
the bullpen spot vacated by the trade of Graeme Lloyd to Toronto. 
``I think we have to find out what we have here and if we can get 
the job done,'' Torre said. ... Torre, who was traded from Atlanta 
to St. Louis for Orlando Cepeda in 1969, would love to see the 
veterans' committee select Cepeda on Tuesday for Hall of Fame 
induction. ... Clemens and Yankees owner George Steinbrenner talked 
briefly in the outfield. It was their first meeting since last 
week's trade. ``I think it's neat to have him show up when you're 
working out,'' Clemens said. ... Yankees general manager Brian 
Cashman said there is no news regarding contract negotiations with 
Ramiro Mendoza and Jorge Posada. Both can renewed by the team next 
month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
