<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Yankees Pull Fast One on Clemens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Roger Clemens was actually smiling on the  
mound Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The five-time Cy Young winner was facing minor league catcher  
Jaime Torres during his first live batting practice stint with the 
New York Yankees when new teammates Derek Jeter and Chuck Knoblauch 
appeared in full catcher's gear. 
</P>
<P>
	The gag went unnoticed by Clemens, who was locked in on pitching  
to Torres, until Knoblauch entered the cage. That prompted a smile, 
a tip of the cap and pitch softly throw behind the second baseman's 
back. 
</P>
<P>
	``He threw his normal pitch up ... a pitch Jeter and I have seen  
before,'' Knoblauch said. ``We were having a good time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens worked on all his pitches during a 10-minute bullpen  
stint and threw 58 pitches during the 13-minute session. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew eventually something would be up ... I think it was a  
good move by them, actually,'' Clemens joked. ``So to make them 
feel right at home, I went ahead and threw those ones behind 
them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jeter and Knoblauch both were hit by Clemens pitches in the past  
and vowed to get even when the Yankees obtained him from Toronto 
last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``The past is over with,'' Jeter said. ``He's part of the team.  
We know it ... he knows it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When informed that Knoblauch had said ``it will take us a while  
to catch up,'' Clemens replied he will ask pitching coach Mel 
Stottlemyre to have the pair assigned to his batting practice group 
if things get out of hand. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, that figures. I didn't think I would get off that  
easy,'' Clemens said. ``They better be careful, because sometimes I 
don't miss.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yankees manager Joe Torre said Clemens will likely start either  
March 6 against Boston or March 7 against Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	Other starters throwing batting practice Friday were David Cone,  
Hideki Irabu and Orlando Hernandez. All three reported no problems 
following their workouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Andy Pettitte is scheduled to throw off a bullpen mound on  
Saturday. The left-hander missed his BP session Wednesday because 
of elbow tenderness. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel fine, said Pettitte, who played catch Friday. ``I'm  
trying to talk them into letting me throw batting practice.'' 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* The Jimmy Key watch is over. Torre said the left-hander has  
decided not to change his decision to retire. Although not ruling 
out a trade, the Yankees will look closely at filling from within 
the bullpen spot vacated by the trade of Graeme Lloyd to Toronto. 
``I think we have to find out what we have here and if we can get 
the job done,'' Torre said. ... Torre, who was traded from Atlanta 
to St. Louis for Orlando Cepeda in 1969, would love to see the 
veterans' committee select Cepeda on Tuesday for Hall of Fame 
induction. ... Clemens and Yankees owner George Steinbrenner talked 
briefly in the outfield. It was their first meeting since last 
week's trade. ``I think it's neat to have him show up when you're 
working out,'' Clemens said. ... Yankees general manager Brian 
Cashman said there is no news regarding contract negotiations with 
Ramiro Mendoza and Jorge Posada. Both can renewed by the team next 
month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
