<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Washington Traffic Is Getting Worse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Your typical bureaucrat has trouble getting  
from here to there. 
</P>
<P>
	Unfortunately, so does everyone else who must drive around the  
nation's capital. And things are about to get much worse. 
</P>
<P>
	Tourists flocking to see the monuments, museums and government  
institutions already face traffic so bad the city is second only to 
the gridlock capital of the country, Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Truckers running goods up and down the East Coast on Interstate  
95 also try desperately to hit the capital when traffic is less; it 
is almost never really light. 
</P>
<P>
	Area residents cope with commutes timed around carpool-lane  
restrictions, while government motorcades throw another roadblock 
into motorists' progress. 
</P>
<P>
	Often, to speed their journey, people stop by informal ``slug  
lines'' on routes out of the city to fill their cars with strangers 
waiting for a lift; that qualifies the vehicle for express lanes. 
</P>
<P>
	A recent study by the Texas Transportation Institute concluded  
that District of Columbia commuters waste the equivalent of two 
full work weeks each year sitting in traffic. 
</P>
<P>
	As bad as the traffic is, two road projects are about to make it  
worse for the locals and visitors alike. 
</P>
<P>
	Virginia is preparing to rebuild the massive I-95/I-395/I-495  
interchange just southwest of the capital. Much like Chicago's 
highway ``Spaghetti Bowl,'' the multilane jumble connects traffic 
running in and out of Washington with the famed Capital Beltway 
encircling the city. 
</P>
<P>
	Reworking what is called the ``Mixing Bowl'' will cost $350  
million and take eight years. During that time, planners say, the 
construction could add up to a half-hour each way for commuters 
unless 2,500 motorists can be persuaded to use mass transit or car 
pools. 
</P>
<P>
	Engineers also are completing a $1.8 billion plan to replace the  
Woodrow Wilson Bridge. Part of the I-95 portion of the Beltway, it 
spans the Potomac River and connects Virginia, Washington and 
Maryland just upstream from George Washington's old home, Mount 
Vernon. 
</P>
<P>
	The metal-grid drawbridge was designed to carry 75,000 cars per  
day. It is crumbling under the weight of 190,000 vehicles every day 
and has become the region's Achilles heel. 
</P>
<P>
	Late last year, gridlock tied up roads within a 25-mile radius  
of the Wilson Bridge when police shut it down because a man was 
threatening to jump. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though there was a life at stake, and police thought the  
man had a firearm, travelers complained vigorously about the 
inconvenience. The bridge replacement is expected to take six 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Either one of them alone would be enough to cause an enormous  
impact. Together, I can't even guess how horrible it's going to 
be,'' said Ron Shaffer, a commuting columnist for The Washington 
Post known affectionately as ``Dr. Gridlock.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Area road experts say the region and all who travel through it  
suffer from poor road planning, Washington's popularity as a 
tourist destination and the simple abundance of vehicles found in 
urban areas. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the '50s and '60s, planners said we would need three  
beltways. We built one and did away with the other two, and now we 
have the second worst gridlock in the nation,'' said Lon Anderson, 
spokesman for AAA's Potomac club. 
</P>
<P>
	Relieving the congestion creates a Hobson's choice: ``If we  
don't do this, we're in horrible shape; if we do it, we're in 
horrible shape,'' Anderson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Traffic is such a part of capital life that the city's primary  
all-news radio station broadcasts traffic reports every 10 minutes, 
24 hours a day, 365 days a year, as is done in other major cities. 
</P>
<P>
	Like their counterparts in other congested areas, Washington  
commuters also have come up with novel solutions for coping with 
traffic. 
</P>
<P>
	Some pick up strangers from the ``slug lines'' at the Pentagon  
so they can qualify for three-person carpool lanes running out of 
the city in the afternoon. Others pull over into the breakdown lane 
at the entrance to the carpool lanes, waiting for the stroke of 6 
p.m., when the three-person limit is dropped. 
</P>
<P>
	Shaffer said he is amazed by the shortcuts people devise.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's like water that seeks the point of least common  
resistance,'' he said. ``They will find that leak in the foundation 
and slip through it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The other way the locals cope is by beginning their commute very  
early or very late -- an option not available to others traveling 
through the area. 
</P>
<P>
	John Wack, a computer furniture salesman, starts his 65-mile  
drive from Fredericksburg, Va., to Bethesda, Md., either by 5:15 
a.m. or after 9 a.m. If he wants to make it home for dinner, he 
must leave the office by 3 p.m. or else wait for 7 p.m. and brace 
himself for leftovers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would compare Washington to what San Francisco was like  
after the earthquake -- when many of the roads had collapsed,'' Wack 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
