<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 16:12:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ericsson Building Dallas Complex </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Ericsson, maker of mobile phones and other  
telecommunications equipment, is moving more than half of its 3,000 
Dallas-area workers from the ``Telecom Corridor'' to another 
suburb. 
</P>
<P>
	The Swedish company announced Friday it will build a  
500,000-square-foot office complex in Plano just south of J.C. 
Penney's corporate headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	Ericsson joins several other major employer in the Telecom  
Corridor of Richardson, Texas, that are planning to relocate 
operations to Plano. 
</P>
<P>
	Alcatel USA announced in November that it would move its U.S.  
headquarters and 1,500 workers. More recently, Fujitsu said it will 
move 250 jobs and a divisional headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	Ericsson officials said they have signed a letter of intent to  
acquire a 35-acre plot with an option to buy up to 110 acres more. 
About 1,700 Ericsson employees will work in the new facility. The 
move is expected to be completed by mid-2001. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990226.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 17:51:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Olympic Gold Medalist Lewis Shines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Three years ago, Steve Lewis had a cyst on his  
lower back that was ``as big as a sausage,'' and if he didn't have 
surgery he might not have been able to walk again. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, Lewis, winner of three Olympic gold medals and one silver  
medal, again appears to be among the world's fastest 
quarter-milers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not finished making history yet,'' Lewis said Friday after  
winning his section of the 400 meters in 46.38 seconds in the USA 
Indoor Track and Field Championships at the Georgia Dome. 
</P>
<P>
	By winning, the 29-year-old Lewis advanced to Saturday's final  
against a field that will include Milt Campbell, who qualified in 
45.75, the fastest by an American this year, and Angelo Taylor 
(45.91), the 1998 NCAA 400-meter hurdles champion from Georgia 
Tech. Derek Mills, the 1997 USA indoor champion, won his heat but 
didn't advance because his time of 46.70 wasn't among the six 
fastest. 
</P>
<P>
	While Campbell, Taylor and Mills have been running without much  
interruption in recent years, Lewis' career was in jeopardy. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Saturday, he ran his first indoor race in five years and  
ran under control, winning a low-key event in 46.48. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, there was a lot more at stake -- and Lewis was ready.  
</P>
<P>
	``It felt good,'' he said, after easing up at the finish.  
</P>
<P>
	His two performances within a week are a testament to his strong  
determination. He thought about quitting running before his 
operation because ``I was so weak,'' he said, ``I couldn't even 
work out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought I had a virus,'' Lewis said. ``Then, I had an MRI.''  
</P>
<P>
	The test showed the huge cyst that was affecting nerves in his  
body and legs, weakening him completely. Because of the way it was 
situated, Lewis said he could not feel the cyst. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was embedded in my spine, and it was expanding,'' he said.  
``I couldn't even jog a mile because I was in such pain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The operation was performed in April 1996 and Lewis was  
incapacitated for a year, unable to work out, train or exercise. He 
resumed training in April 1997, competed sporadically that year and 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Now he is pain free and coming back full time in a quest to  
regain the stature he held in 1988 when he won gold medals in the 
400 and 1,600 relay, and in 1992, when he was the silver medalist 
in the 400 and earned another relay gold. 
</P>
<P>
	If he wins or finishes second in Saturday's final, he would earn  
a place on the U.S. team for next week's World Indoor Championships 
at Maebashi, Japan. His last international team appearance was at 
the 1992 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis said that if hadn't been injured, he might have quit after  
a possible third Olympics in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``But I don't feel I've reached my potential,'' he said. ``I  
don't feel too old to accomplish things. I feel I have a lot more 
in me. I feel I still have it. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you're a runner, it's hard to stop because of injuries.''  
</P>
<P>
	Right now, there's no quit in Lewis.  
</P>
<P>
	``The key is to find the old Steve Lewis,'' he said. ``That will  
save the day. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's still there.''  
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the trials in the men's 400, trials were held in  
the women's 400 and the men's and women's 200 and 800. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevin Little, the 1997 world champion in the men's 200, won his  
heat comfortably in 20.59. Tyree Washington, the 1997 world outdoor 
bronze medalist in the 400, also qualified for Saturday's final in 
the 200, finishing second in his heat in 20.68. 
</P>
<P>
	Jearl Miles-Clark, the defending world champion in the women's  
400, easily won her heat in 53.12 and advanced to Saturday's final. 
</P>
<P>
	Her sister-in-law, Joetta Clark, the defending U.S. champion in  
the women's 800, and Meredith Valmon, the 1991 national champion, 
won their heats. Clark was timed in 2:05.15 and Valmon in 2:06.45. 
</P>
<P>
	While Valmon was running, her 19-month-old son Travis was asleep  
in the stands with his father. 
</P>
<P>
	``He gets a little distressed when I run,'' Valmon said,  
``especially when he can see that I'm tired. He doesn't always like 
it. So it's better that he slept through it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rich Kenah, the 1997 world indoor and outdoor bronze medalist in  
the men's 800, also qualified for Saturday's final, finishing 
second in his heat in 1:49.44. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-nine championship finals will be held Saturday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990226.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 17:51:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Olympic Gold Medalist Lewis Shines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Three years ago, Steve Lewis had a cyst on his  
lower back that was ``as big as a sausage,'' and if he didn't have 
surgery he might not have been able to walk again. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, Lewis, winner of three Olympic gold medals and one silver  
