<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> P&AMP;G Says Diaper Prevents Rash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Procter &AMP; Gamble believes parents will be  
willing to pay 50 percent more for a diaper the company says has 
been medically proven to prevent and treat diaper rash. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pampers Rash Guard diaper, which started arriving in stores  
last week, contains strips treated with petrolatum, found in 
petroleum jelly, and stearate, a skin conditioner. The new diaper 
can still absorb waste because not all areas are treated with the 
conditioners. 
</P>
<P>
	Diaper rash is caused partly by wetness, which causes irritation  
and abrasion of the baby's skin, leading sometimes to sores that 
require medical attention. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our consumer research has shown us not only that diaper rash  
is a painful and common ailment for children, but it causes a 
genuine misery for parents, who feel guilty over not being able to 
prevent their children's suffering,'' company spokesman Scott 
Stewart said Friday. ``This is a way to help both.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A jumbo package of 36 treated diapers costs about $13.25, the  
same as the average price of a package of 56 of the company's basic 
diapers. That works out to about 37 cents for each Rash Guard 
diaper compared with 24 cents for the standard product. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would be willing to try anything I thought would help, but  
the added expense may keep some people from trying it,'' said Dena 
Smith, the mother of a 6-month-old girl and an aide at Hope Early 
Childhood Center in Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	One doctor who has three children, including an 8-month-old,  
isn't ready to recommend Rash Guard. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a skeptic. My first impression is that I'm not sure I  
would be willing to pay the price for the product,'' said Dr. Anita 
Sheth, director of pediatric dermatology at Children's Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	``The primary thing for prevention is really good hygiene and  
changing diapers frequently,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kimberly-Clark Corp., the maker of Huggies, the nation's most  
popular diapers, said it is monitoring the impact of the new diaper 
on the market. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is nothing difficult about coating a diaper with  
petrolatum and stearate, but we welcome competitiveness,'' said 
company spokeswoman Wendy Strong. 

</P>
</TEXT>
