<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Joy Overcomes Hate in Jasper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JASPER, Texas (AP) -- One family was vindicated, another  
destroyed. 
</P>
<P>
	But the trial and death sentence of racist John King united the  
families of the black victim and the white killer in one important 
way: Both agree it's time for the hate to end. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all are human beings, black and white. We all are children  
of God,'' King's ailing father, Ronald King, said in a written 
statement after his son was sentenced to die for dragging James 
Byrd Jr. to death last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must learn to love one another,'' he said, ``and not  
hate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Byrd's sister, Mary Verrett, said she hoped the death sentence  
would send ``a message throughout the world that hate crimes must 
stop.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But, she added, her heart goes out to King's father.  
</P>
<P>
	``We can understand his loss,'' she said. ``But what we have to  
realize is that it was his son that made the choice to bring this 
pain upon his father.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like the Kings and the Byrds, not all in this rural east Texas  
community agreed on King's punishment, but most were grateful for a 
resolution. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't ask the Lord to give him the death penalty,'' said  
the Rev. Bobby Hudson, a Baptist who opposes capital punishment. 
``We're going to get on with life, regardless. You can't show in 
the Bible where one man or one incident stopped people from getting 
on with life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ethel Parks, who celebrated the sentence by exchanging a  
high-five with another woman on the courthouse lawn, said she 
usually opposes the death penalty. ``But in this case I can make an 
exception,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	For some, King's sentencing is only the first stitch in an open  
wound. Two more suspects, Shawn Berry and Lawrence Brewer, are 
still to be tried for Byrd's slaying. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've still got a lot to go through,'' said Jasper resident  
Jim Saari. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite having to endure two more trials, Byrd's sister, Clara  
Taylor, said some good already has come out of her brother's death 
and King's trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Blacks and whites are beginning to talk, and the problem of race  
is no longer taboo. Perhaps, she said, the wound can be healed 
after all. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we all work together in our own communities, we can  
hopefully prevent other John Kings from carrying out their hateful 
acts toward other individuals,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
