<HEADLINE> Man Pleads Guilty to HIV Exposure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MAYVILLE, N.Y. (AP) -- A man accused of exposing more than a  
dozen young women in upstate New York to the virus that causes AIDS 
has pleaded guilty to statutory rape of a 13-year-old and having 
unprotected sex. 
</P>
<P>
	Nushawn Williams, 21, faces up to 12 years in prison after  
pleading guilty Friday in Chautauqua County to two counts of 
second-degree rape and a charge of reckless endangerment. 
Sentencing was set for April 5. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams already has pleaded guilty to reckless endangerment for  
having unprotected sex with a New York City high school student. He 
could get up to seven years in prison when he is sentenced on that 
charge April 8. 
</P>
<P>
	The state's confidentiality laws prevent people who are HIV  
positive from being identified. But in October 1997, concerned 
health officials took the extraordinary step of identifying 
Williams in a poster campaign aimed at warning his sex partners 
that he may have given them the virus that causes AIDS. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chautauqua County health department was being besieged with  
calls from worried residents. Authorities there have said Williams 
infected nine of at least 28 sex partners with the HIV virus, six 
of them knowingly. 
</P>
<P>
	State Health Department officials said a sweeping HIV-reporting  
and partner notification program is expected to begin in the spring 
in response to the Williams case. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams is currently serving a one- to three-year prison  
sentence for selling cocaine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
