<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rockies' Lansing Overcomes Palsy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- Mike Lansing's first year with the Colorado  
Rockies left him little reason to smile. Shortly after the season 
ended, he literally became incapable of mustering any kind of grin. 
</P>
<P>
	``I couldn't smile,'' Lansing said Friday, describing his bout  
with Bell's palsy. ``This (left) side would smile and this (right) 
side would go down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bell's palsy is a temporary facial paralysis that has no warning  
signs and affects one in 5,000 Americans. Lansing learned about it 
in November after he began having trouble moving his mouth while 
brushing his teeth. 
</P>
<P>
	``I bit my lip an awful lot,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The paralysis lasted nearly a month, and Lansing said he is just  
about fully recovered. In about 80 percent of all cases, Bell's 
palsy patients have complete, spontaneous recovery within four 
months, according to medical research. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you didn't know I had it, you wouldn't know at all,''  
Lansing said. ``It doesn't give me any problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The onset of Bell's palsy came following a disappointing season  
with the Rockies. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first year of a $23.25 million, four-year contract,  
Lansing got off to a slow start before finishing the year with a 
.276 average with 12 homers and 66 RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	Though he said it was unrelated to his sub-par season, Lansing  
underwent corrective eye surgery on Nov. 16. 
</P>
<P>
	A contact lens wearer since the ninth grade, the 31-year-old  
Lansing said he wanted to have the laser surgery partly because he 
got frustrated with constantly administering eyedrops between 
innings. 
</P>
<P>
	``San Francisco's a prime example. It's the worst.'' Lansing  
said of the Bay area's renowned winds. ``If you get some dirt in 
there, you can't see and then your contacts dry out so quick that 
you could be trying to blink and you miss a pitch, or you're on 
defense and you miss something.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With surgery, Lansing's vision went from 20/200 to about 20/20 --  
a result that he says was worth the risk of the increasingly 
popular, but still unproven, procedure. 
</P>
<P>
	To help put his mind at ease, Lansing did his own research and  
specifically requested Englewood, Colo., Dr. Lawrence Spivack. 
</P>
<P>
	``From what I'd heard and looked into, he's considered one of  
the best in the country because he's been doing it for so long,'' 
Lansing said. ``He knew that I played baseball and he knew what my 
worries were and he was very sympathetic to that and reassured me. 
That made me feel a lot better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lansing joins a growing list of baseball players and managers  
who have had laser eye surgery. The group includes San Diego's 
Wally Joyner and his manager Bruce Bochy. Both went under the laser 
this offseason. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was thinking, I've got a couple more years to play. I've  
played with these bad eyes all my career,'' Joyner said last week. 
``If there's a possibility of getting better eyesight, let's see if 
it helps.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even if it doesn't improve Lansing's batting average this  
season, the eye surgery -- which can cost anywhere from $2,000 to 
$4,000 -- won't be a total loss. 
</P>
<P>
	``The best thing is to wake up in the middle of the night and  
look over and I can see the alarm clock without going, `What time 
is it?''' Lansing said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
