<DOCNO> APW19990226.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 12:33:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AlliedSignal Can Vote on Tyco Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- AlliedSignal Inc., rejected in its hostile  
bid to acquire AMP Inc., will get to vote on Tyco International 
Ltd.'s $11.3 billion agreement to buy the maker of electrical 
components, a federal appeals court has ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	AlliedSignal already owns 200 million shares, or 9.1 percent, of  
AMP, that it purchased before making a $10 billion bid for 
Harrisburg, Pa.-based company. 
</P>
<P>
	The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reversed a ruling that  
AlliedSignal could not vote as a shareholder because of a 1990 
state anti-takeover law. 
</P>
<P>
	The law says purchasers of more than 20 percent of a company's  
stock cannot vote the stock without getting the approval of the 
remaining shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	Though AlliedSignal bought less than 20 percent, U.S. District  
Judge James T. Giles had ruled that its shares were ``control 
shares'' because they were bought with intent to make an 
acquisition. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the appeals court ruled on Feb. 18 that the law  
requires ``actual acquisition of at least 20 percent of the 
outstanding shares.'' 
</P>
<P>
	AMP officials did not return calls Friday for comment on the  
likely impact of the ruling when AMP shareholders meet April 1 to 
vote on the Tyco bid. 
</P>
<P>
	AlliedSignal has not decided how it will vote, said Mark  
Greenberg, a spokesman for the Morristown, N.J.,-based maker of 
aerospace and automotive products, chemicals and high-tech 
materials. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are pleased with ruling,'' said Greenberg, though he would  
not predict whether it would change anything. ``We only own nine 
percent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	AMP agreed in November to accept the $11.3 billion bid by Tyco  
International, a Bermuda-based provider of electronic security 
services and a manufacturer of flow control valves. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990226.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 00:13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jurors Say King Posed Future Danger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JASPER, Texas (AP) -- The photographs of James Byrd Jr.'s  
mutilated body were appalling and almost too much for juror Lequeta 
Flowers to bear. 
</P>
<P>
	She and 11 other jurors spent days listening to brutal racist  
language and looking at horrifying crime scene photos. The 
41-year-old school teacher said she found strength to endure the 
evidence in the words of prosecutor Guy James Gray. 
</P>
<P>
	``I kept remembering what Mr. Gray said, `This is hard, but you  
can do it.' I kept telling myself that because I was thinking I 
can't turn this page,'' Flowers said, referring to an evidence 
booklet containing dozens of photos. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury deliberated less than three hours Thursday before  
sentencing John King to die by injection rather than spend life in 
prison for the June 7 dragging death of Byrd. 
</P>
<P>
	The jurors had to find that King intended to kill Byrd, that  
King was a future danger to society and that no mitigating 
circumstances warranted a lighter sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Collins, the lone black juror and the one elected to lead  
the panel in its deliberations, said jurors honored their 
responsibilities. 
</P>
<P>
	``Each of us believes that justice has been served,'' said  
Collins, a guard at a private prison in nearby Newton. 
</P>
<P>
	Byrd, 49, was killed after he was chained to a truck and dragged  
for nearly three miles. His head and right arm were severed in what 
prosecutors said was a killing designed to launch a new racial hate 
group in Jasper. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just feel that nobody should be tortured that way,'' said  
Collins, who called the crime scene pictures ``terrifying.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Flowers said the jury searched for evidence to avoid a death  
sentence, but searched in vain. 
</P>
<P>
	``We looked for ways to not have to do what we did today, and  
they were not there,'' she said. ``You just can't have this. 
Society cannot accept this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Flowers said she found King's prison letters and other  
writings persuasive proof of his guilt. The 24-year-old laborer had 
outlined plans for a new hate group and his desire to die as some 
sort of martyr for white America. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were very compelling to me,'' Ms. Flowers said. ``I felt  
like he didn't show any remorse for his actions after the deed was 
done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other evidence that swayed jurors included the victim's blood  
found on King's shoes, King's lighter inscribed with a Ku Klux Klan 
symbol and King's DNA found at the scene where Byrd was chained to 
the truck. 
</P>
<P>
	King was the first of three white suspects to go to trial for  
Byrd's murder. Trial dates for the other two -- Shawn Berry, 24, and 
Lawrence Brewer, 31, -- have not been scheduled. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Flowers and Collins said jurors rejected a defense argument  
that King, who spent two years in prison for a burglary conviction, 
became a racist in order to protect himself from attacks by black 
inmates. 
</P>
<P>
	``As sad as it is, whether he is a victim of his environment, as  
humans we still have a mind and heart to make our judgment,'' Ms. 
Flowers said. ``Mr. King chose poorly.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
