<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AMD Chips Knock Intel From Top Spot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                           *BY RACHEL BECK   	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Tarnishing the launch of Intel's newest Pentium  
chips, a report Friday revealed that consumers bought more 
computers in January with semiconductors made by Advanced Micro 
Devices -- knocking Intel from the No. 1 spot for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Intel slid $8, or more than 6 percent, to $119 on Wall  
Street amid news that 43.9 percent of all desktop PCs sold in 
January were equipped with AMD-K6 processors, according to the 
research firm PC Data. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel's chips powered 40.3 percent of the machines sold, while  
National Semiconductor's Cyrix chips came in third at 15.8 percent, 
the monthly report said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a major milestone for AMD,'' said Stephen Baker, the  
senior hardware analyst at PC Data, which bases its figures on unit 
sales, not dollar volume. ``This is the first time that a processor 
family, other than one manufactured by Intel, led the U.S. retail 
market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The report came as Intel unveiled the Pentium III, a new line of  
microprocessors with graphic and video capabilities that are far 
faster and clearer than anything else available to consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	But like its predecessors, the Pentium III is also far more  
pricey than most chips, and it was clear from Friday's report that 
Intel has been hurt by its limited exposure to the sub-$1,000 PC 
market -- which accounted for a record 65.6 percent January's retail 
sales, up from 51 percent in December. 
</P>
<P>
	Notably, the average selling price of a PC fell to $953 in  
January, a 6 percent decline from December, said PC Data, which is 
based in Reston, Va. By contrast, computers powered with the 
Pentium III are selling for about $2,000. 
</P>
<P>
	In the sub-$1,000 market, AMD-powered machines captured more  
than 50 percent of the sales -- doubling Intel's 25.4 percent share. 
Of those selling below $800, AMD chips were in 45.1 percent of the 
computers, while Intel chips were in 14.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel, however, maintained its leadership in the above-$1,000  
market, with its chips powering more than two-thirds of the 
machines sold. 
</P>
<P>
	``Intel is taking us to a new power level with its new line  
processors,'' namely the Pentium III, said Tim Bajarin, president 
of Creative Strategies Research International in San Jose, Calif. 
``But they aren't as aggressive in the low end of the market where 
they need to compete.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Having recognized the boom in the sub-$1,000 market, Intel is  
spending $300 million on marketing to entice consumers to buy 
pricier, Penium-powered computers. 
</P>
<P>
	While Intel has lost market share at the retail level, it's  
important to note that its microprocessors still power more than 80 
percent of the world's personal computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Likewise, Intel's profits remain quite healthy, although much of  
that strength actually comes from the company's most expensive 
chips -- like the Xeon -- which are used as the brainpower in desktop 
machines bought by businesses. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
