<HEADLINE> Koufax Visits Mets' Spring Training </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. (AP) -- Sandy Koufax made what's becoming an  
annual appearance at the New York Mets spring training camp Friday, 
viewing batting practice and speaking with pitchers and coaches. 
</P>
<P>
	The Brooklyn Dodgers Hall of Famer, who also visited last year,  
again took interest in Al Leiter, a fellow left-hander. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know, not only to see Sandy Koufax, but to hear him, he's  
so succinct,'' Mets manager Bobby Valentine said. ``Seems like the 
world doesn't spin as fast when Sandy's looking at it. He sees 
things very clearly, and it's really good to have him around and 
slowing things down a little.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Koufax, who resides in Vero Beach, 20 miles north of the Mets  
camp, worked with Leiter last year when he made his first visit, 
talking about mechanics. 
</P>
<P>
	``He definitely cares and he's not here for show,'' Valentine  
said. ``He'd rather come here when the lights were turned off and 
have his own little corner so he could do his work there. Not that 
he's working, because he's not getting paid, but he is making a 
contribution and he likes to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Koufax is a friend of Dave Wallace, a senior advisor to general  
manager Steve Phillips. 
</P>
<P>
	Another Mets pitcher also got some advice, but it came from a  
different corner. Bobby Bonilla told Armando Benitez the reliever 
was tipping his pitches during batting practice Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had a good conversation with Armando about the grips of  
different pitches,'' Valentine said. ``He had a conversation with 
him about changing his glove position. Armando came out today and 
felt real good about the change.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Benitez came to the Mets from the Baltimore Orioles.  
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes with a new organization there will be a little bit  
of resistance,'' Valentine said. ``There wasn't any, he felt good 
about it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
