<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 15:34:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Austria Wins at Nordic Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RAMSAU, Austria (AP) -- With the tip of his right ski, Christian  
Hoffmann made cross-country history in his native Austria, and 
Japanese ski jumpers swept the medals Friday for the first time 
since the Olympic Games at home in 1972. 
</P>
<P>
	Kazuyoshi Funaki, the Olympic champion last year in Nagano, won  
the 90K gold in the Nordic Ski World Championship, followed by 
Hideharu Miyahira in second and Masahiko Harada, the Olympic bronze 
medalist, in third again. 
</P>
<P>
	Funaki soared 96 and 94 meters and earned 255 points to lead the  
first ski jumping sweep in a major championship since the Japanese 
did it in Sapporo. 
</P>
<P>
	``The team carried me, because we all jumped well,'' Funaki  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Miyahira, bronze medalist on the large hill, had 253.5 points  
for jumps of 95.5 and 93.5 meters. Harada went 98 meters in the 
first series and 94 in the second, but his style was not as clean 
and he took the bronze with 252 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoffmann lunged forward in a desperate final burst to beat  
Norway's favorite Thomas Alsgaard at the finish line of the men's 
4x10-kilometer relay and give Austria its first cross-county gold 
medal in a major competition. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's incredible,'' Hoffmann said. ``I've practiced that finish  
so often but it wasn't easy to beat Alsgaard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The thrilling finish turned the ski stadium into a sea of waving  
red-and-white Austrian flags in a jubilation scene more frequently 
associated with Hermann Maier and the nation's other Alpine stars. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today, the whole nation stood behind us,'' said Hoffmann, the  
Olympic 50K bronze medalist. 
</P>
<P>
	Markus Gandler, the 10K Olympic silver medalist, and Alois  
Stadlober, who was second here in the 10K, had given Austria a 
solid lead after the first two classical style legs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Austrians were nearly 30 seconds ahead of the Norwegians  
when Mikhail Botwinov fell, allowing Norway's star Bjorn Daehlie to 
slash the deficit in the third leg. 
</P>
<P>
	Botwinov, a Russian-born naturalized Austrian citizen, fell in a  
downhill section of the course, losing a pole and damaging his ski 
boot, which nearly came undone. He got up, threw away his goggles, 
grabbed another pole and again charged ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to increase our margin, but I was tired and both of  
my skis went into the same grove and they crossed,'' Botwinov said. 
``A team official threw me another pole but it was too short.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If we had lost the gold it would have been my fault,''  
Botwinov said. 
</P>
<P>
	By the time Botwinov tagged Hoffmann for the final leg, Daehlie  
was only 5.5 seconds behind and handed over to Alsgaard, a powerful 
finisher with a long stride who had confirmed his 15K Olympic gold 
with another close victory here in the pursuit Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Both racers stayed close at a slow pace and eyed one other. Both  
were saving their strength for the decisive finish, with Alsgaard 
passing up several invitations to move into the lead. Homestretch 
sprints are Alsgaard's trademark. 
</P>
<P>
	But it was Alsgaard who miscalculated in the neck-to-neck finish  
as Hoffmann never lost the pace and pushed his ski forward to win 
by .02 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of us took the victory for granted and when you take  
everything for granted it doesn't always turn out the best way for 
you,'' Daehlie said. 
</P>
<P>
	Austria's combined time of 1 hour, 35 minutes, 7.5 seconds  
snapped Norway's relay winning streak stretching back four world 
championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Norway used three skiers who were also on the gold medal team in  
the Olympics last year in Nagano. Espen Bjervig was the newcomer, 
joining Erling Jevne in the two classical legs. 
</P>
<P>
	The silver gave Daehlie, a record eight-time Winter Olympics  
champion, 17 world championship medals, tying him on the career 
list with Elena Vaelbe, the retired Russian star. 
</P>
<P>
	But Daehlie was still disappointed, comparing the loss to  
Norway's defeat by Italy at the 1994 Olympics at home in 
Lillehammer. 
</P>
<P>
	Italy took the bronze this time, using three racers from the  
team that won the Olympic silver in Nagano. Giorgio di Centa joined 
the Olympic trio of Fulvio Valbusa, Fabio Maj and Silvio Fauner. 
Fauner was also on the victorious team in Lillehammer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
