<DOCNO> APW19990226.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 00:13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man's Torture Shocks N.J. Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KEANSBURG, N.J. (AP) -- They came looking for him at McDonald's,  
just before he got off work. They invited him to come to a party, 
where he could meet a pretty girl. 
</P>
<P>
	Clutching the stuffed whale he carried with him everywhere, the  
23-year-old retarded man eagerly followed, happy to be included in 
a circle of people he wanted to call his friends. 
</P>
<P>
	It was all a cruel trick, authorities say. At least 14 people  
were waiting for him at a Keansburg apartment. As he walked in the 
door, they grabbed him in a choke hold, cut off his McDonald's tie 
and ripped his beloved toy to shreds. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors allege Eric Krochmaluk's attackers then taped him to  
a lawn chair and tossed lighted cigarettes into his mouth -- and 
kept on torturing him for three hours. 
</P>
<P>
	A week after nine men and women were charged in the attack,  
people in this blue-collar Jersey Shore town speak of the 
aimlessness of its young people, underage drinkers who raise havoc 
in a wooded area called ``The Pit,'' and the lack of recreational 
opportunities for young adults. 
</P>
<P>
	But no one can fathom the rage and cruelty that led to this.  
</P>
<P>
	``I just don't think that they know what to do with themselves  
and they don't care what they do,'' 69-year-old Ellen Park said as 
she bought lottery tickets at a convenience store. ``I'm sure you 
can find better things to do than go around torturing people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Jan. 30 attack is drawing comparisons to the 1989 gang rape  
in Glen Ridge of a retarded teen-ager by popular athletes who 
sexually assaulted her with a broomstick and baseball bat. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are people out there that prey on the vulnerable,'' said  
Tom Baffuto, director of the Arc of New Jersey, an advocacy group 
for the mentally handicapped. ``This is the dark side of society.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although Krochmaluk graduated from a vocational-technical school  
with honors, family members describe him as having the emotional 
and mental capacity of a 15-year-old. He is deaf in one ear and has 
a heart murmur. 
</P>
<P>
	But he enjoys the same heavy-metal music as his alleged  
attackers, some of whom he knew from his Middletown High School 
days, and he attended some of their parties. One suspect, 
22-year-old Marni Solomon, is a former girlfriend, Monmouth County 
prosecutors say. 
</P>
<P>
	The young man may have offended the tough, tight-knit group by  
spilling a drink on someone at a New Year's Eve party. 
</P>
<P>
	Two weeks later, authorities contend, some of the suspects  
grabbed him at another party and forced him to wear a bra. 
Krochmaluk called his father, who persuaded them to let his son go. 
No one called police. 
</P>
<P>
	On Jan. 30, Solomon and Michael Finlay, 37, showed up at a  
Tinton Falls McDonald's where Krochmaluk worked as a cook. They 
invited him to a party at an apartment shared by Jennifer Dowell, 
21 -- a special education aide at Krochmaluk's old school -- and 
Brandon Cruz, 23. 
</P>
<P>
	When Krochmaluk arrived, he was stripped to his underwear and  
tied down, prosecutors said. The group put out cigarettes on his 
teeth and tossed some into his mouth. They made him lick a spilled 
drink off the floor, dressed him in a bra and skirt and used 
plastic razors and electric clippers to shave his head and 
eyebrows. His head was then set afire with hair spray. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors are investigating whether a string of plastic beads  
used to whip Krochmaluk may have been used to sexually assault him 
as well. 
</P>
<P>
	After about two hours, the group put a pillow case over  
Krochmaluk's head and dragged him to ``The Pit,'' where they beat 
him in the woods before leaving him there, prosecutor Robert 
Honecker Jr. said. 
</P>
<P>
	One eye swollen shut, Krochmaluk eventually staggered to a  
security guard's booth at a nearby factory. He was treated at a 
hospital and released. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors are considering charging the nine under New Jersey's  
bias crime law, which would double their penalties. The suspects -- 
most in their early 20s -- face charges ranging from theft to 
kidnapping and aggravated assault. 
</P>
<P>
	Cruz and Dowell, who face the most serious charges, remain in  
jail, while seven are free on bail. Attempts to reach them were 
unsuccessful; most have not retained lawyers. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents were horrified by the attack, though many said that  
Keansburg -- where a boardwalk, amusement park and well-kept condos 
clash with empty storefronts -- isn't to blame. 
</P>
<P>
	Some said the torture shows that mentally retarded people  
sometimes trust people they shouldn't because they are so desperate 
to belong. 
</P>
<P>
	``The sad part is, this young man was looking for companionship  
and friendship and he looked to these people,'' said Police Chief 
Raymond O'Hare. ``They took advantage of that.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
