<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dozen GOP Govs. Publicly Back Bush </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush has the support of  
12 fellow Republican governors for a presidential run even though 
he has not formally announced his intention to seek the GOP 
nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	The governors on Friday declared their backing for Bush, and  
seven more governors may follow. 
</P>
<P>
	Govs. Paul Cellucci of Massachusetts and Marc Racicot of Montana  
began collecting names at last weekend's National Governors' 
Association meeting here. 
</P>
<P>
	The two divided a list of Republican governors -- 30, not  
including Bush -- to contact and on Friday released 12 names. 
Michigan Gov. John Engler, Bush's unofficial point man with the 
governors, also kept busy reaching out to leaders to gauge support 
for Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Three more governors have committed themselves to endorsing  
Bush, but will not make public statements until they inform party 
members in their states, said Andrew Malcolm, Racicot's executive 
assistant. Malcolm said four others are expected to announce their 
backing soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, eldest son of former President George Bush, said Friday he  
intends to reveal more about his plans next week. 
</P>
<P>
	``Next week I'll discuss it with you as to whether or not I want  
to take this process a step further,'' Bush said. ``The decision is 
yes, I'm going to run; no, I'm not going to run, or I might run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But advisers to Bush say he will form an exploratory campaign  
committee in the next month, which would allow him to raise and 
spend money while testing his potential support. 
</P>
<P>
	The governors said they hope their coalition will encourage Bush  
to run. 
</P>
<P>
	``The ideological and geographical breadth of support among  
Governor Bush's peers demonstrates just how strong a candidate he 
would be,'' Cellucci said. 
</P>
<P>
	Calling Bush a ``proven winner,'' Racicot praised the Texas  
governor's pragmatic reforms and family-oriented administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Other governors listed as Bush supporters, including his  
brother, Jeb, the governor of Florida, are: Engler, John Rowland of 
Connecticut, Frank Keating of Oklahoma, Dirk Kempthorne of Idaho, 
Bill Graves of Kansas, Mike Foster of Louisiana, Kenny Guinn of 
Nevada, Lincoln Almond of Rhode Island and Bill Owens of Colorado. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
