<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Raise Nuke Plant Concerns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Concerned that some workers at nuclear power  
plants are putting in too many hours, lawmakers asked the U.S. 
Nuclear Regulatory Commission to examine whether plant safety is 
being jeopardized. 
</P>
<P>
	Three Democrats, Reps. Edward Markey of Massachusetts, John  
Dingell of Michigan and Ron Klink of Pennsylvania, wrote to NRC 
Chairwoman Shirley Ann Jackson to request an investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are writing in concern that low staffing levels and  
excessive staff overtime may present a serious safety hazard at 
some commercial nuclear plants in the United States,'' they said in 
a letter sent Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawmakers are worried that fatigue caused by too few workers  
putting in too many hours could lead to operating errors. They did 
not identify plants where they thought safety could be threatened. 
</P>
<P>
	Citing an NRC document, they said fatigue ``can degrade an  
operator's ability to rapidly process complex information such as 
that presented by off normal plant conditions. In addition, fatigue 
may jeopardize the ability to respond in a timely fashion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The lawmakers heard of possible problems with staff overtime and  
shift staffing from whistleblowers. The issue of staffing and 
safety at the Byron nuclear plant in Illinois was also raised in a 
February article in Inside N.R.C., a trade publication. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Gilliland, an NRC spokesman, said the agency had no  
immediate comment. ``We will respond to their letter,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson was asked to launch a broad investigation into the  
prevalence of overtime at the nation's 104 federally licensed 
plants and its safety significance. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other points, the lawmakers want to know whether the NRC  
could attribute any examples of errors in performing safety-related 
functions in the past five years to operator fatigue, staffing 
levels or staffing overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency was also asked about its rules, including whether it  
has enforceable regulations on overtime and staffing, and why there 
is no explicit ban on excessive overtime, as there is for airline 
pilots and truck drivers. 
</P>
<P>
	A 1982 NRC policy statement, which is not enforceable, states  
that plants should employ enough operating personnel to adequately 
cover shifts without ``routine heavy use of overtime.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It sets out guidelines for using overtime on a temporary basis  
and states that deviations from guidelines in ``very unusual 
circumstances'' should be authorized by plant managers and 
documented for possible NRC review. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawmakers also said they were worried that overtime and  
staffing problems could get worse if the commercial nuclear 
industry tried to cut costs due to increased competition in 
electricity markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Kerekes, spokesman for the Nuclear Energy Institute, the  
main industry trade group, said the best-run nuclear plants also 
tend to be the most economical. It makes little sense to hurt 
operations, and risk federal penalties, by cutting costs too much, 
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
