<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Salt Lake Preparing for Drug Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The chief medical officer for the Winter  
Olympics said the groundwork is being laid now for a drug testing 
program that will ensure no doped-up athletes compete in 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	Whether Salt Lake also tests for growth hormones and drugs that  
enhance oxygen capacity -- requiring more invasive blood sampling -- 
is an open question, said Charles Rich, a Salt Lake neurosurgeon. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just simply don't know,'' Rich said Friday during a  
briefing for reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Testing for growth hormones, the latest wave of  
performance-enhancing substances, will depend on the ability of the 
world's Olympic and political leaders to fund technology 
development and resolve the thorny issue of privacy, Rich said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The science is getting there,'' said Douglas Rollins, a  
pharmacologist and toxicologist who began work as the medical 
director for doping control last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Rollins works for the Salt Lake Organizing Committee while  
remaining as director of the Center for Human Toxicology at the 
University of Utah. In 2001, he will go to work full-time for the 
SLOC. 
</P>
<P>
	His hiring is one of the reasons Rich believes Salt Lake's  
doping control will be as good as possible. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know that they've ever had anyone as qualified,'' Rich  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The SLOC also has contracted with The Indiana University  
Athletic Drug Testing and Toxicology Laboratory to do the actual 
testing during the games and Paralympic Winter Games that follow. 
</P>
<P>
	It is one of only two labs accredited by the International  
Olympic Committee in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Space will be leased for the lab, possibly at the University of  
Utah's Research Park, Rollins said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rollins said that he and the new doping control program manager,  
Michele Brown, are learning how the seven winter sports federations 
do their drug testing and will pay close attention to what Sydney 
does right and wrong during the 2000 Summer Games. 
</P>
<P>
	If any new drugs show up there, ``We're going to have to be  
prepared to test for it here,'' Rollins said. 
</P>
<P>
	The details of the doping control program -- down to which urine  
collection cups to use -- will be dictated to the SLOC by the IOC 
and sports federations that govern the sporting competition. 
</P>
<P>
	But it will be the job of the organizers to make sure the  
program runs smoothly and with the best technology for accurate, 
prompt results, the SLOC officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rich, Rollins and Brown all attended the IOC's three-day summit  
in early February, which was an attempt to crack down on drugs in 
sport and harmonize anti-doping sanctions among international 
federations. 
</P>
<P>
	Although there remain many unresolved issues, Rich lauded the  
IOC for bringing together athletes and governmental representatives 
for what turned out to be a raucous forum. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were trying to be honest brokers, trying to get the  
players together,'' Rich said. ``This is extremely complex. This is 
a problem that, if it's going to be solved, it's going to be solved 
in stages.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rollins said he suspects the drugs most likely to show up in  
athletes at the 2002 Winter Games will be anabolic steroids, 
stimulants like amphetamine and beta-blockers. 
</P>
<P>
	Biathletes, for instance, may be tempted to use beta-blockers to  
slow down their heart rates and thus steady their hands for 
shooting rifles, Rollins said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
