<DOCNO> APW19990226.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 06:05:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Steel Crisis Shows Signs of Abating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Key administration officials are warning  
Congress against approving stricter trade sanctions sought by the 
U.S. steel industry to block cheap imports. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky said Thursday that  
the United States must weigh the steelworkers' desire for quotas 
and other relief with the risk of starting a trade war that could 
jeopardize U.S. exports of other products and further weaken 
foreign economies. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do have to be cautious about the way in which we proceed,''  
Barshefsky told a House panel. ``We cannot dismiss out of hand the 
notion that other countries will take retaliatory action or might 
impose mirror legislation. ... We have a broad range of interests, 
economic in particular, that we need to protect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barshefsky spoke as the Commerce Department announced that  
imports continued to drop in January, a signal that the steel 
import crisis is abating. Nevertheless, she did express concerns 
about imports from Japan and South Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department reported that steel imports to the  
United States dropped 6.7 percent last month. While Russian imports 
plunged by 70 percent and Brazilian shipments went down 18 percent, 
imports from Japan decreased only 4 percent. Shipments from South 
Korea went up 26 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Imports reached record levels last year in the wake of the Asian  
economic crisis and have been blamed for thousands of U.S. layoffs 
and three company bankruptcies. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration faces difficult choices about how to respond.  
Labor is a key constituency for Democrats, but the administration 
also is a proponent of free trade and believes that open markets 
abroad is best for U.S. companies with goods to export. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, Barshefsky and Commerce Secretary William Daley  
indicated they would stick with procedures available through 
existing trade laws. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department found evidence earlier this month that  
Japan, Russia and Brazil illegally dumped hot-rolled carbon steel, 
a widely used steel product, in U.S. markets at prices dramatically 
below production costs. 
</P>
<P>
	The department said imports of that product from the three  
countries combined fell by 96 percent since November. South Korea 
was not a party to the complaints filed by the U.S. steel industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``These numbers are encouraging,'' Daley said. ``They show that  
tough enforcement of our trade laws does work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he acknowledged that ``one or two months of good data do not  
make a trend'' in light of record highs last year. The U.S. 
industry says that despite the short-term drops, the levels still 
are too high. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan and Brazil face steel tariffs, but the United States  
announced a deal with Russia on Monday in which Russia would slash 
its shipments of hot-rolled and other steel products by almost 70 
percent to avoid tariffs. 
</P>
<P>
	At a House Ways and Means trade subcommittee hearing on steel,  
Daley raised the possibility of settlement talks with Brazil as 
well, saying Brazilian officials recently expressed interest in a 
deal. No discussions have taken place so far, Daley said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990226.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 17:52:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drs. Charged at Home for Retarded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKLIN, Pa. (AP) -- A two-year investigation of deaths at  
Pennsylvania's largest home for the retarded led to charges Friday 
against six doctors accused of such offenses as manslaughter and 
sewing up patients' wounds without anesthesia. 
</P>
<P>
	``It gives you shivers. I've never heard of anything like  
that,'' said Charles Lakin, who tracks abuse cases nationwide at 
the Institute on Community Living at the University of Minnesota. 
``If that's not the regular treatment for human beings, obviously 
someone's under the perception that these are not human beings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Drs. Cesar Miranda, 68, and Hyunchel Shin, 74, were charged with  
manslaughter in the deaths of three patients from the Polk Center, 
a 101-year-old, state-run facility in western Pennsylvania. 
</P>
<P>
	Miranda did not examine a man with a blocked intestine for hours  
-- until his body temperature had dropped to 82 degrees -- and sent a 
vomiting, feverish woman whose skin had turned blue for an X-ray, 
prosecutors said. Both patients died. Shin allegedly failed to get 
a brain scan of a patient, leading to his brain deterioration and 
death. 
</P>
<P>
	Four other doctors -- former Polk medical director Samir Moussa,  
47; David Byers, 53; Donald Stitt, 84; and Louka Makkar, 50 -- were 
charged with assault and neglect. Among other things, they and 
Miranda were accused of using sutures and surgical staples to close 
wounds without anesthesia. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for all six doctors said their clients are innocent.  
Five of them were arraigned Friday and released on $50,000 bail; 
the sixth, Byers, is expected to surrender Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney General Mike Fisher, whose office began investigating  
in 1997 after the deaths of the three patients, called it ``a very 
sad and disturbing case.'' The center employs about 1,200 people 
and has 565 residents, some of them so severely disabled they 
cannot communicate. 
</P>
<P>
	``These doctors were entrusted with the care of some of our most  
dependent citizens,'' Fisher said. ``Many of these residents could 
not express pain or discomfort to the doctors. However, that's no 
excuse for circumventing normal medical procedures.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Makkar said hospital and state officials were aware that doctors  
at Polk commonly used surgical staples without anesthesia if an 
injury needed immediate treatment. ``You judge which pain is 
worse,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jay Pagni, a spokesman for the state Welfare Department, which  
operates the center, said there is no policy directing doctors to 
treat wounds without anesthesia. He would not comment further on 
Makkar's allegation. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the manslaughter charges against Miranda stems from the  
death of Eugene Rozgonyi, 62, who was mentally retarded because of 
injuries he suffered from surgical instruments at birth. 
</P>
<P>
	Rozgonyi, who lived at Polk for 55 years, became sick on March  
6, 1997, with a blocked intestine that made his belly expand. He 
got worse throughout the day, but Miranda did not examine him until 
midnight, when his body temperature had fallen to 16 degrees below 
normal, investigators said. 
</P>
<P>
	Miranda also allegedly failed to transfer Rozgonyi to a hospital  
until four hours later. He died six hours after being admitted. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had a hard time being born and a hard time dying,'' said  
Rozgonyi's brother, John, 71. 
</P>
<P>
	Mary Ellen Fritz, a spokeswoman for the state welfare agency,  
said the department fixed problems at Polk and drafted stricter 
rules for doctors after the allegations first arose, in 1996. Four 
doctors resigned and three were fired. 
</P>
<P>
	One fired doctor was reinstated after arbitration. It was  
unclear whether that doctor was among the six charged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990226.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 12:54:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bernstein Swipes at Today's Media </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- Carl Bernstein, who helped bring  
down President Nixon, said American journalism is ``disfigured by 
celebrity, gossip and sensationalism.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe it's the role of journalists to challenge people,  
not to just mindlessly amuse them,'' Bernstein said Thursday at a 
Jewish Federation gathering. ``In this culture of journalistic 
titillation, we teach our readers and our viewers that the trivial 
is important.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bernstein's work with Bob Woodward at The Washington Post  
exposed the Watergate scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	He blamed much of the problem on the rise of tabloid journalism.  
</P>
<P>
	``The sleazy standards of the low end of the media are affecting  
the standards of even the high end of our busines,'' Bernstein 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990226.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 10:35:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Kosovo Rebels, Serbs Keep Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Ethnic Albanians fled villages on  
tractor-pulled trailers by the dozens to escape new fighting and a 
buildup of Serb forces today. Western peace monitors, meanwhile, 
were prevented from entering Kosovo by Yugoslav customs agents. 
</P>
<P>
	The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, which  
runs the monitoring mission in Kosovo, said Yugoslav border 
authorities blocked peace monitors from entering the province from 
neighboring Macedonia for a second straight day. 
</P>
<P>
	OSCE spokesmen said the customs officials were demanding to  
search luggage and vehicles of the monitors, violating 
international conventions on border procedures for diplomats. The 
problems began Thursday and by this afternoon 21 staffers were 
stuck at the border, waiting in their cars. 
</P>
<P>
	American diplomat William Walker, the head of the mission, was  
trying to mediate the standoff by telephone. 
</P>
<P>
	Mortar fire and gunshots resounded in northern Kosovo in a  
second day of clashes in the Bukos area between the Yugoslav army 
and rebel forces. 
</P>
<P>
	Serb police blocked roads into the area, but humanitarian aid  
workers said they saw about 30 Yugoslav tanks and armored cars in 
the area. Four tanks were poised at the edge of the village of 
Nevoljane, about 15 miles northwest of the capital Pristina. 
</P>
<P>
	Field workers for the U.N. refugee agency said four civilians  
were wounded by shrapnel and bullets Thursday in the village of 
Ljubovec. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 500 Kosovo Albanian refugees, mainly women and children,  
fled to neighboring Macedonia today, Macedonian state radio 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The Albanians were said to have fled their homes near Kacanik  
after Serbian security forces conducted house-to-house searches in 
the town. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yugoslav army was reported to be beefing up its defenses  
near Kacanik, a border region where NATO forces currently in 
Macedonia would cross into Kosovo if they are deployed in the 
province. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO and Western officials are concerned about the new fighting  
and the massing of Yugoslav and Serb forces and are trying to hold 
both sides to a cease-fire during a 2 1/2-week suspension in peace 
talks. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Defense Department says Yugoslavia has deployed 4,500  
troops on the border of the separatist-minded province in southern 
Serbia, backed by tanks, artillery, and armored personnel carriers. 
</P>
<P>
	``What frightens me and worries me is that these weeks are taken  
advantage of for the purpose of conflict rather than for 
consolidation'' of steps toward a peace deal, NATO 
Secretary-General Javier Solana said today. 
</P>
<P>
	He told Spain's Channel 9 TV that there would be punitive  
airstrikes on Serb targets ``only if absolutely necessary ... and 
always in the service of a political objective.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fighting in Kosovo began almost a year ago when Yugoslav  
President Slobodan Milosevic sent forces to crush a KLA 
insurrection. More than 2,000 people have died and 300,000 others -- 
mostly ethnic Albanians -- have been displaced by the fighting. 
</P>
<P>
	The new fighting came as ethnic Albanian negotiators returned to  
Kosovo from talks in Rambouillet, France, which ended this week 
without substantial agreement on how to bring lasting peace to the 
impoverished province in Serbia, the main republic in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	While the Serbs refused to let NATO troops enforce a peace plan  
-- a key ingredient to any deal -- ethnic Albanians agreed to sign a 
tentative agreement when talks resume March 15 after consulting 
with KLA commanders back in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The top Kosovo Albanian political leader reiterated today that  
his side will make good on its pledge. 
</P>
<P>
	Ibrahim Rugova, the pacifist leader of pro-independence ethnic  
Albanians, expressed approval of the agreement -- broad autonomy as 
an interim solution without formal secession, combined with NATO 
troops as an implementing force. 
</P>
<P>
	While Rugova did not head the Albanian negotiating team in  
France, he remains an influential leader among the 90 percent 
ethnic Albanian majority in Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990226.0093 </DOCNO>
