<DOCNO> APW19990226.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 01:34:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Lower, Japanese Stocks Slip / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Comments by U.S. Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence  
Summers suggesting that Japan needs to take further steps to boost 
the economy helped the dollar recoup much of its early losses 
against the yen. Japanese stocks slipped. 
</P>
<P>
	In late afternoon, the dollar bought 120.32 yen, down 0.30 yen  
from late Thursday in Tokyo but higher than its late New York level 
of 119.63 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 102.91 points,  
or 0.71 percent, closing the week at 14,367.54 points. On Thursday, 
the index closed up 115 points, or 0.80 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar moved as low as 119.07 yen early in the session,  
following the release of a Japanese government report showing that 
Japan's industrial output rose by 0.8 percent in January from the 
previous month. 
</P>
<P>
	But the greenback jumped after Yukihiko Ikeda, a senior official  
in the ruling Liberal Democratic Party, told reporters that Summers 
had urged further action from Japan when they met in the morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Ikeda quoted Summers as telling him: ``The Bank of Japan's  
monetary steps so far may not be enough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The comments raised speculation that the Bank of Japan, or BOJ,  
might ease monetary policy further, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Summers' words to Ikeda showed that the U.S.... is not  
satisfied with the monetary easing steps taken so far by the BOJ,'' 
said Tetsu Aikawa, a senior trader at Sanwa Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	In a news conference later today in Tokyo, Summers urged Japan  
to take a policy of creating a ``strong domestic demand-led 
growth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Japan should be careful not to rely too much on export sales to  
drive growth, Summers said at the end of a weeklong tour of Asia 
that included stops in Singapore, Indonesia, China and South Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar rose as high as 121.05 yen during the day but shed  
some of the gains after Summers said he wouldn't make specific 
``recommendations'' to the central bank on monetary policy. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 132.35 yen, down  
from 132.78 yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, share prices drifted lower in midway today  
as market players became cautious about exchange rate and interest 
rate movements. An overnight fall on Wall Street also was another 
factor. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 33.33  
points at 9,366.34. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the exchange's first section was estimated at 469  
million shares, up marginally from Thursday's 463 million shares. 
Decliners outnumbered advancers 684 to 481, with 140 issues. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 4.10 points, or 0.36 percent, to 1,120.03 
points. The TOPIX rose 3.84 points, or 0.34 percent, the previous 
day. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese government  
bond fell to 1.885 percent from today's finish of 1.915 percent, 
driving its price up to 99.32 yen from 99.09 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
