<DOCNO> APW19990226.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 11:44:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> $11 Million Award in Gun Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- A judge has ordered an Italian gunmaker to  
pay $10.8 million to a man paralyzed in 1992 when he dropped his 
pistol and was shot in the neck. 
</P>
<P>
	Fratelli Tanfoglio S.R.L. manufactured the .25-caliber pistol  
with a firing pin that was too long, U.S. District Judge Mary Ann 
Vial Lemmon ruled in a lawsuit brought by 52-year-old Arnold 
Jackson. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gun manufacturers have an obligation to reasonably anticipate  
that owners of guns, will, at some point, unexpectedly drop them,'' 
Lemmon said. ``The manufacture of the pistol with a defective 
firing pin made it virtually certain that the gun would fire if 
dropped or bumped on its hammer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The gunmaker did not defend itself in the case, and court papers  
listed no lawyer for the company. The judge's ruling was filed Dec. 
31, and the 30-day appeal period passed without an appeal being 
filed. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Feldman, executive director of the American Shooting  
Sports Council, an organization of gunmakers, said the company 
won't have to pay unless Jackson sues in Italy and wins. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
