<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Malinina Wins Four Continents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HALIFAX, Nova Scotia (AP) -- Tatiana Malinina of Uzbekistan won  
the biggest title of her career Thursday, edging three Americans at 
the Four Continents figure skating championships Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The 26-year-old Malinina, who trains in the United States, won  
the short program the previous night, then added a victory in the 
free skate. She beat out Amber Corwin, Angela Nikodinov and Erin 
Pearl. 
</P>
<P>
	Malinina, winner of the NHK Trophy in December in Japan, took  
the inaugural Four Continents gold medal by landing four clean 
triple jumps in a routine to ``Aladdin.'' It was the first medal in 
an International Skating Union event for Uzbekistan and was a long 
time in coming for Malinina. 
</P>
<P>
	``Age has no meaning whatsoever,'' she said. ``Some skaters  
become champions at 15, others achieve this later on. There is no 
age limit for competitions and I can skate until I'm 40 if I want 
to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She will skate in the Grand Prix finals next week in St.  
Petersburg, Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	Corwin, 20, of Hermosa Beach, Calif., nailed a triple  
loop-triple loop combination. She also hit three other triples, two 
in combination in one of the strongest performances of her career. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very excited because nationals were a very depressing few  
days for me,'' said Corwin, who was sixth at the U.S. championships 
earlier this month. ``Tonight, I started off strong, but I got a 
little weak, then I pulled it off in the end.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Four Continents event is for skaters outside of Europe,  
which holds an annual continental championship for its skaters. 
</P>
<P>
	Canadian couples dominated the ice dance, holding down three of  
the top four spots after the original dance. 
</P>
<P>
	Shae-Lynne Bourne and Victor Kraatz were first, even though  
Bourne is competing with torn cartilage in her left knee. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have been keeping my knee injury quiet up until this point  
and are just trying to deal with it,'' said Bourne, who was hurt a 
few weeks before she and Kraatz won their seventh Canadian 
championship last month. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-time world bronze medalists will decide after the Four  
Continents whether they will skate at the Grand Prix final. 
</P>
<P>
	Bourne didn't show any outward signs of knee problems during the  
waltz in the original dance. But she admitted she is feeling pain. 
</P>
<P>
	Chantal Lefebvre and Michel Brunet moved up a notch from third  
to second after the original dance. Compatriots Megan Wing and 
Aaron Lowe moved up from sixth to fourth. 
</P>
<P>
	American champions Naomi Lang and Peter Tchernyshev dropped to  
third heading into the free dance Friday night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990226.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 20:51:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Outlines Foreign Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- In a sweeping review of world problems,  
President Clinton warned Friday that NATO is ``prepared to act'' in 
Kosovo, pledged to redouble his efforts for peace in the Middle 
East and offered encouragement to Russia and China in their 
struggle for prosperous stability. 
</P>
<P>
	Laying out his foreign policy hopes for the final two years of  
his presidency, Clinton said, ``For our nation to be strong, we 
must maintain a consensus that seemingly distant problems can come 
home if they are not addressed and addressed promptly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Americans should resist the temptation for ``minding our own  
business'' just because there is no overriding threat to U.S. 
security, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, flanked by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and  
National Security Adviser Sandy Berger, spoke before an audience of 
foreign policy specialists. He used the occasion to announce he was 
certifying Mexico as a reliable ally in the war against drugs -- 
even though Mexico has ``a serious drug problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president also said he was lifting sanctions imposed on  
Nigeria for its alleged role in drug trafficking. It was a reward 
to Nigeria's transition government for guiding the country toward 
democracy after long years of military rule. Presidential elections 
are set for Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Under his policy change, Clinton lifted a requirement that the  
United States vote against loan requests by Nigeria in 
international lending institutions. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside the hotel where Clinton spoke, hundreds of protesters  
demonstrated about a variety of causes. One person carried a sign: 
``Clinton -- king of corruption in the reign of raunch.'' Another 
sign said: ``No NAFTA for Africa.'' Clinton flew to Los Angeles 
later for a $200,000 political fund-raiser. 
</P>
<P>
	``America is on the right path to the future and moving in the  
right direction,'' Clinton told cheering Democrats. ``We've come a 
long way in the last six years. We've had a good time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the nation must ``take advantage of these good times to  
deal with the big, long-term challenges we face.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Berger described Clinton's speech as the foreign policy  
equivalent of his State of the Union address. It was intended to 
respond to critics who say ``there is no big threat out there'' and 
``we ought to tend to our own knitting,'' Berger said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said the fighting in Kosovo poses ``the biggest  
remaining danger'' to peace in the Balkans. Kosovo ``is not an easy 
problem. But if we don't stop the conflict now, it clearly will 
spread,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Serbs and ethnic Albanians are to return to the negotiating  
table March 15, and Clinton warned Yugoslav President Slobodan 
Milosevic to refrain from violence, saying: ``President Milosevic 
should understand this is a time for restraint, not repression. And 
if he does not, NATO is prepared to act.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Berger expressed concern about Serb troops massing on the border  
of Kosovo. He said the United States and most of its allies believe 
NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana should use his authority to 
act if the Serbs engage in widescale repression. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has pledged to contribute 4,000 American ground troops  
to a NATO peacekeeping force for Kosovo if a peace agreement is 
reached. 
</P>
<P>
	The president said he would make a special effort to pursue  
peace in the Middle East. ``I intend to use the time I have 
remaining in office to push for a comprehensive peace in the Middle 
East, to encourage Israelis and Palestinians to reach a just and 
final settlement, and to stand by our friends for peace,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The people of the Middle East can do it, but time is precious  
and they can't afford to waste any more of it,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Berger said it was unlikely Clinton would undertake any major  
initiative before the Israeli elections in May and a possible 
runoff in June. But he said the president ``intends to put all the 
energy necessary into moving this forward after the elections, 
obviously assuming the parties are prepared to get serious.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Albright joined the president in San Francisco on her way to  
China. In Washington, the State Department said that China's human 
rights record deteriorated sharply late last year with a crackdown 
on political dissent. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said the United States must respond to the challenge of  
bringing ``our former adversaries, Russia and China, into the 
international system as open, prosperous, stable nations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said China had made ``incredible progress in lifting people  
out of poverty and building a new economy.'' But at the same time, 
``They remain unwilling to open up their political system, to give 
people a peaceful outlet for dissent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said China will come to understand that it ``simply cannot  
purchase stability at the expense of freedom.'' He said the United 
States must expand its cooperation ``through principled and 
purposeful engagement with China, its government and its people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Turning to Russia, Clinton said the United States must come to  
the aid of a nation weakened by a legacy of communism. ``The 
dimensions of this problem are truly enormous. Eight years after 
the Soviet collapse, the Russian people are hurting,'' Clinton 
said.	   ``Yet, we have as much of a stake today in Russia in overcoming 
these challenges as we did in checking its expansion during the 
Cold War. This is not a time for complacency or self-fulfilling 
pessimism,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Russian people will decide their own future,'' Clinton  
said. ``But we must work with them for the best possible outcome, 
with realism and with patience. If Russia does what it must to make 
its economy work, I am ready to do everything I can to mobilize 
adequate international support for them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His speech came a day after a rare presidential admission of  
failures in foreign policy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've made no progress, although I've tried, in trying to get  
Greece and Turkey to get along,'' he said late Thursday night at a 
political fund-raising dinner. ``I've made no progress in trying to 
resolve the tensions between India and Pakistan.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990226.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 22:53:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sen. Kerry Won't Run for President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The decision by Sen. John Kerry against  
challenging Vice President Al Gore for the Democratic presidential 
nomination shrinks the contest to a virtual two-man race, according 
to some political observers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Massachusetts Democrat announced Friday that he wouldn't run  
against front-runner Gore, leaving former Sen. Bill Bradley of New 
Jersey as Gore's only declared competitor. 
</P>
<P>
	``My heart loves these issues. My heart said go out and fight  
for these things. My head said the day after I make an announcement 
I have to raise an exorbitant amount of money and do it all in 10 
months,'' Kerry said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other leading Democrats who have decided not to challenge Gore  
include Sens. Bob Kerrey of Nebraska and Paul Wellstone of 
Minnesota, and House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri. 
</P>
<P>
	``Other than Jesse Jackson, who could play a spoiler role and be  
an uncomfortable opponent for Al Gore, I think we have the field. 
This is a two-person field,'' said Washington political consultant 
Stuart Rothenberg. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerry, a three-term senator, had complained about raising more  
than $20 million to campaign. His wife, Teresa Heinz, widow of Sen. 
John Heinz, R-Pa., is a multimillionaire, but Kerry said he and his 
wife had decided it would be ``inappropriate'' to use their own 
money. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerry said the impeachment hearings hindered his ability to  
attract donations, and many key supporters and fund-raisers were 
reportedly already committed to Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the end of the impeachment trial, Kerry has traveled coast  
to coast and re-evaluated the campaign. He concluded that while he 
might have done well in neighboring New Hampshire, the decision by 
California to move its presidential primary from June to March 2000 
-- when New York also holds its primary -- would have required too 
much upfront cash for political ads. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerry, 55, did not rule out a future presidential run and said  
he would endorse one of the Democratic contenders. 
</P>
<P>
	Locals were disappointed but not surprised. ``The enormity of  
the task probably has to put a chill into anyone,'' said state 
Speaker of the House Thomas Finneran, D-Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerry gained national attention in the 1970s as a decorated  
Vietnam veteran who upon his return spoke out against the war. He 
co-founded Vietnam Veterans Against the War and ran unsuccessfully 
for Congress in 1972. 
</P>
<P>
	He worked as a county prosecutor until being elected lieutenant  
governor of Massachusetts. From there, he launched a successful 
campaign for Senate, succeeding the late Paul Tsongas in 1984. He 
survived a challenge by former Gov. William F. Weld in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990226.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 00:32:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Final Witness in Microsoft Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- And then there was one.  
</P>
<P>
	In an important milestone of the government's antitrust case  
against Microsoft Corp., lawyers planned today to begin -- and 
finish -- questioning the last witness during this stage of the 
trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, after an extraordinary recess of at least six weeks,  
Microsoft and the government will present to the judge their 
rebuttal arguments, each using testimony from three more witnesses 
who haven't all been identified. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft's final defense witness was Robert Muglia, a senior  
vice president who refuted earlier testimony that the company 
sought to undermine the rival ``Java'' technology from Sun 
Microsystems Inc., which allows software to run on a variety of 
computer operating systems. 
</P>
<P>
	The allegation is part of the government's theme that Microsoft  
illegally wields its monopoly power to smother potential 
competitors of its lucrative Windows franchise. Microsoft denies 
that it possesses monopoly power. 
</P>
<P>
	Muglia, arguing that Microsoft was competing for ``the hearts  
and minds of software developers,'' said the company tried to 
encourage them to use Windows-only features that effectively 
prevent their Java programs from running under other operating 
systems. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we were right and successfully executed our strategy, then  
Sun's attempts to use Java to establish a new development platform 
to replace Windows would not be successful,'' Muglia said in 
written testimony. ``... Developers can easily choose to use 
Microsoft's programming tools to write 'pure' cross-platform Java 
applications if they wish.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft was expected today to finish briefly questioning its  
next-to-last witness, senior executive Joachim Kempin, who was 
responsible for the company's deals with the nation's computer 
makers. 
</P>
<P>
	Kempin on Thursday defended restrictions that Microsoft puts on  
the sale of its Windows software, saying it doesn't want other 
companies to ``butcher'' its dominant operating system. 
</P>
<P>
	The government's own questioning of Kempin generally lacked the  
courtroom drama that has recently become characteristic of the 
trial. Kempin, in his heavy Germanic accent, forcefully butted 
heads with Justice Department lawyer David Boies in occasionally 
feisty exchanges but neither gave much ground. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point, Kempin complained that he already had answered a  
question from Boies. ``The answer was?'' Boies asked. ``Because 
sometimes your answers change.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft argues that computer makers are free to install  
whatever rival software they want and to offer it as prominently 
Microsoft's. But it won't let companies make material changes to 
Windows, such as removing or hiding Microsoft's browser, called 
Internet Explorer. 
</P>
<P>
	The government alleges that Microsoft's refusal to allow  
companies to make changes to Windows -- such as removing easy access 
to its bundled Internet software -- is designed to hurt rivals 
offering similar software features. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
