<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 15:15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McCain to GOP: Stop Sniping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Sen. John McCain, casting himself as  
the conscience of the GOP presidential field, promised on Friday 
``not to stoop to negative campaigning against fellow Republicans'' 
and challenged his rivals to take a similar pledge. 
</P>
<P>
	``Scorched earth Republican primaries will lead directly to an  
Al Gore presidency,'' the Arizona senator warned in a speech 
prepared for delivery to the California Republican Party. And he 
urged activists to withhold their support from any GOP candidate 
who attacks another. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't let us go down the road of mindlessly destroying each  
other,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The challenge will be put to the test almost immediately. Four  
other GOP presidential prospects addressing the same group Saturday 
have been highly critical of front-runner Texas Gov. George W. 
Bush. They are former Vice President Dan Quayle, businessman Steve 
Forbes, activist Gary Bauer and former Tennessee Gov. Lamar 
Alexander. 
</P>
<P>
	As Bush moves closer to a formal campaign, the attacks are  
likely to step up. Party leaders fear a repeat of the 1996 GOP 
primaries, when eventual nominee Bob Dole was hobbled by internal 
attacks, particularly from Forbes. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican Party Chairman Jim Nicholson promised this week to  
``blow the whistle'' on Republicans who break Ronald Reagan's 11th 
commandment of politics: Speak no ill of a fellow Republican. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain advisers believe his high-road promise will help his  
standing as a maverick candidate unafraid of bucking political 
trends to advance good government. 
</P>
<P>
	They privately acknowledge that McCain can't win the nomination  
without the Texas governor faltering. But his campaign doesn't need 
to attack Bush because other rivals are already doing the dirty 
work. Those foes have attacked Bush's ``compassionate 
conservatism'' slogan, accusing him of using ``weasel words'' and 
``mealy-mouth rhetoric.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even before McCain's arrival, the infighting was evident at the  
California convention. The state party refused to invite GOP 
presidential hopeful John Kasich, because the chairman of the House 
Budget Committee agreed two years ago to raise money for a 
Democratic congressman. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview aboard the commercial flight that brought him to  
California, McCain said he is the best qualified presidential 
candidate. But he said that doesn't give him the right to tear his 
opponents down. 
</P>
<P>
	``I won't say George Bush is not qualified or Elizabeth Dole is  
not qualified. What's the point? I think they are qualified,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The position may strike a chord with Republicans weary of losing  
partisan battles to a more unified Democratic Party -- from the 
government shutdown in 1995 to President Clinton's impeachment. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's great to hear somebody in the Reagan tradition get back  
to the basics of the party -- uplifting and optimistic themes 
instead of all these newfangled side tracks we're on,'' said Mary 
Lu Hamill of Mission Viejo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Democrats stick together,'' said her husband, Rich. ``We sort  
of crumble when we disagree with the Republican next to us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his speech, McCain said, ``I will not engage in personal  
attacks and the politics of division. I will not stoop to negative 
campaigning against my fellow Republicans. I will not run negative 
advertising. I give you my word on it. And I call on the other 
candidates to join me in that pledge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Naming them, McCain said he respects all of his GOP rivals and  
is a friend of Bush, Dole and Quayle. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope the day never comes when for the sake of personal  
ambition I try to destroy people I admire, and with whom I agree on 
most issues,'' McCain said. 
</P>
<P>
	His approach won't spare Gore, whom McCain sternly admonishes  
for the campaign fund-raising practices of the Clinton-Gore 
administration. ``The American people deserve a controlling ethical 
authority as well as controlling legal authority,'' he says at 
every campaign stop, referring to Gore's defense for making 
fund-raising calls from the White House. The vice president said 
there was ``no controlling legal authority'' forbidding his calls. 
</P>
<P>
	If McCain sticks to his pledge, it won't be the first time he  
has stood alone or nearly so. 
</P>
<P>
	He championed campaign finance reform and fought the tobacco  
industry, two ill-fated missions that bucked his party's 
leadership. He says his cede-no-ground approach stems from the 
years he spent in a Vietnamese prisoner of war camp. 
</P>
<P>
	``It gave me a greater sense of confidence,'' he said in the  
interview, squinting into the sun pouring through the plane's tiny 
window. ``I know the difference between right and wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Political infighting is wrong, he said, ``and pretty stupid.''  
</P>
<P>
	Also on Friday, 12 of the nation's GOP governors publicly lent  
their support for a Bush candidacy. 
</P>
<P>
	Govs. Paul Cellucci of Massachusetts and Marc Racicot of Montana  
have led a drive over the past week to collect names of fellow 
Republican governors to back Bush. Those named Friday are: 
Cellucci, Racicot, John Engler of Michigan, John Rowland of 
Connecticut, Frank Keating of Oklahoma, Dirk Kempthorne of Idaho, 
Jeb Bush of Florida, Bill Graves of Kansas, Mike Foster of 
Louisiana, Kenny Guinn of Nevada, Lincoln Almond of Rhode Island 
and Bill Owens of Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	Three others have committed to Bush but will not make public  
statements yet, a Racicot assistant said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
