<HEADLINE> Eagles Reach Pact With Landeta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The Philadelphia Eagles agreed to terms  
Friday on a three-year contract with veteran punter Sean Landeta. 
</P>
<P>
	Landeta, 37, has played in the NFL for 14 years, most recently  
with the Green Bay Packers. He set team single-season records last 
year with a 37.1-yard net punting average and 30 punts inside the 
20-yard line. He ranks 12th on the league's career list with a 
43.6-yard average. 
</P>
<P>
	From 1983 to 1985, Landeta played for the Philadelphia (later  
Baltimore) Stars, who won two United States Football League 
championships. After his tour of duty with the Stars, Landeta 
joined the New York Giants as a free agent. He has also played for 
the Los Angeles and St. Louis Rams and Tampa Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	The Eagles also signed free agent running back Tony Smith, a  
five-year veteran with Atlanta, Carolina, and the CFL. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, 28, played for three years with the Falcons and ranked  
third in the NFL in 1993 with a 24.9-yard average on 38 kickoff 
returns. After his release in 1994, he became one of the first 10 
players to sign with the expansion Carolina Panthers. He missed the 
1995 season with a leg injury and later went to play in Canada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
