<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil OKs New Central Bank Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) -- Brazil took an important step toward  
naming a new central banker Friday as a Senate panel approved the 
nomination of market-savvy economist Arminio Fraga. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking before an often combative panel, Fraga defended his  
ideas for stabilizing Brazil's battered currency and keeping 
inflation under control. He also defended his past, his intentions 
and even his nationality. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil is relying on Fraga, a former associate of billionaire  
financier George Soros, to stabilize the wild swings in the 
country's currency, the real. The government allowed the currency 
to float last month, abandoning costly efforts to defend it on open 
markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Fraga's nomination now heads for a vote before the full Senate,  
where the government holds an ample majority. But Fraga's 
association with Soros caused one opposition senator to compare his 
selection to ``putting the fox in charge of the henhouse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the hearing, Fraga promised measures to stop the slide of the  
real, which has lost 40 percent of its value since mid-January. 
``The preservation of the buying power of the currency should be 
the most important task of the Central Bank,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Fraga said he prefers keeping interest rates high in order to  
protect the value of the real against other currencies. Rates now 
stand at 39 percent, and the government admits they are fueling 
Brazil's budget deficit and pushing the country into recession. 
</P>
<P>
	Finance Minister Pedro Malan says the economy will shrink  
between 3-4 percent this year, and private analysts expect even 
worse. 
</P>
<P>
	But Fraga says the sacrifice is needed to avoid the return of  
four-digit inflation. He predicted inflation will dip to 0.6 
percent a month in the last quarter and to a single digit for all 
of 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The 33 senators on the panel drilled the Princeton-educated  
economist with questions for six hours, often digressing into 
diatribes against financial speculation. 
</P>
<P>
	Fraga, the son of an American mother and a Brazilian father,  
said his dual citizenship did not affect his allegiances or his 
eligibility to run the government's bank. 
</P>
<P>
	He also denied violating insider information norms when he was  
approached for the post late last month, when currency speculators 
forced the real down and nearly caused a run on banks. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside the white marble Congress building, protesters brought  
dozens of chickens to illustrate the fox-in-the-henhouse 
comparison. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never did anything that could have harmed my country,'' he  
said. ``I am here to serve my country as a technocrat and as an 
economist.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fraga said he opposes restrictions on dollars leaving the  
country. ``Capital controls cut off access to foreign funding and 
therefore limit economic growth potential,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He also endorsed a greater independence for the Central Bank and  
said bank officials who quit should be banned for a year from 
working in market-related jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Fraga also praised the International Monetary Fund, which is  
reveiwing an agreement for release of a $41.5 billion aid package. 
The IMF said the accord will be unveiled next week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
