<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 15:53:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Leads Solo Sailing Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- Italian navigator Giovanni  
Soldini took the lead Friday in a solo sailing race around the 
world while his nearest contender inched toward the Falkland 
Islands in the South Atlantic. 
</P>
<P>
	Soldini is expected to reach Punta del Este next Tuesday or  
Wednesday, race director Mark Schrader said by phone from the 
Uruguayan port. 
</P>
<P>
	Fellow competitor Isabelle Autissier of France, whom Soldini  
rescued Feb. 16 when her yacht capsized, was still on the Italian's 
craft. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, former frontunner Marc Thiercelin of France, who  
snapped his mast Thursday in the South Atlantic, held course toward 
the Falklands at 4 or 5 knots and is expected to arrive Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Thiercelin was spotted by a Royal Air Force craft on a training  
flight from the British base on the islands, Schrader said. 
</P>
<P>
	The French navigator, who averted any danger of sinking by  
sawing away the toppled mast and snarled rigging, made a jury rig 
out of bits and pieces on board. 
</P>
<P>
	Thiercelin had commanded an 18-hour lead over Soldini after  
leaving Auckland, New Zealand, on the third leg of the Around Alone 
regatta, a 27,000-nautical mile globe-girdling voyage. 
</P>
<P>
	The race began in September in Charleston, S.C., and is to end  
there in May. 
</P>
<P>
	The Frenchman's shore crew is in Uruguay and studying such  
options as flying a replacement mast to Thiercelin in the 
Falklands' Port Stanley. 
</P>
<P>
	Autissier was plucked unharmed from her overturned yacht in the  
Southern Ocean, about 1,800 miles west of the southernmost tip of 
South America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
