<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast Storm Drops 2 Feet of Snow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A powerful storm that slammed into the Northeast  
slowed significantly early today after piling up nearly 2 feet of 
snow from Rhode Island to Cape Cod and leaving thousands of people 
shivering without electricity. 
</P>
<P>
	Before it spins back out to sea, the storm that has packed  
gale-force gusts could brush coastal New England -- particularly 
eastern Massachusetts -- with even more snow. 
</P>
<P>
	Roaring in amid a relatively balmy winter, the storm hammered  
the Northeast coast before daybreak Thursday, shutting down schools 
and businesses and forcing the cancellation of more than half the 
flights at Boston's Logan International Airport at its peak. 
</P>
<P>
	Logan was open for business this morning, but some flights were  
delayed or canceled. Many schools remained closed today in 
Massachusetts and Rhode Island. 
</P>
<P>
	Major cities, including New York, were spared the storm's worst  
wrath. On Cape Cod, plows couldn't keep up. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruth Rusher, a Hyannis woman old enough to say she knows better  
than to tell her age, thinks it may be the worst storm she's ever 
seen. It was just about more than she could manage to put one foot 
in front of the other to get back from a neighbor's house on Cape 
Cod. 
</P>
<P>
	``Somebody came and plowed my driveway out close to 4:30, and  
there's all of 6 inches back again,'' Rusher said Thursday evening. 
``It's not the usual storm we've had the last few years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At least 15,000 homes were without power through much of the  
night on Cape Cod and islands Martha's Vineyard and Nantucket. The 
Red Cross set up emergency shelters on the Cape. 
</P>
<P>
	About 17 inches fell on Nantucket and 13.5 inches in Plymouth by  
early this morning. Boston got 6 inches in 24 hours. Ferry service 
was expected to resume to Nantucket this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Mary Simeone of East Dennis, Mass., was aghast at the Cape Cod  
snow. 
</P>
<P>
	``I keep looking at it on my deck and I'm horrified,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	The Nor'easter also sent police and firefighters into the cold  
night searching for 9-year-old Cory Anderson, who disappeared as he 
looked for his dog at midday in Norton, northeast of Providence, 
R.I. He didn't come home. 
</P>
<P>
	A neighbor found Cory's dog shortly after the boy went looking  
for it. 
</P>
<P>
	Search crews of police and volunteers battled snowdrifts and  
poor visibility to comb a two-square-mile area of woods, lake and 
cranberry bogs in the south shore town in search of the child. 
Divers and search dogs were to be brought in this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	The storm was expected to lose some of its punch today, with  
sometimes heavy snow tapering to flurries. But 2 to 5 inches of 
fresh new snow could push totals to 2 feet. Partly sunny skies were 
predicted for later today. 
</P>
<P>
	The storm piled snow across New York's eastern Long Island and  
pounded coastal areas of southeastern Connecticut, where sandy 
beaches were buried under a heavy frosting. 
</P>
<P>
	By Thursday afternoon, the Rhode Island cities of Coventry and  
Foster had more than a foot of snow. Westerly and Providence had 10 
inches. Middletown got 7 inches. 
</P>
<P>
	Sessions of both houses of the Rhode Island's General Assembly  
were called off, and legislators went home as utilities geared up 
for a long night. 
</P>
<P>
	At T.F. Green Airport in Warwick, R.I., airline travelers  
scrutinized departures boards with dismay as flight after flight 
was canceled. By 5 p.m. Thursday, the airport had 9 inches of snow. 
</P>
<P>
	Travelers' nightmares were a many a child's delight.  
</P>
<P>
	``I did a little dance when I woke up this morning'' and found  
out school had been called off, said 11-year-old Tommy Kumes, 
dragging a sled up a hill Thursday at a park in Cranston, R.I. 
</P>
<P>
	In city after city along the coast, grownups were warned to stay  
off roads. Some stayed home from work to avoid blizzard-like 
conditions; some were sent home early. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
