<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tyson Out of Solitary After Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROCKVILLE, Md. (AP) -- Mike Tyson won this round.  
</P>
<P>
	The former heavyweight boxer was removed from solitary  
confinement Thursday and on Friday had telephone and other 
privileges restored after he appealed a disciplinary ruling at his 
Maryland jail, said his lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson's punishment for throwing a television set in a recreation  
room at the Montgomery County, Md., jail Feb. 19 ``was reduced to 
time served, and he was restored to regular privileges,'' said his 
lawyer Paul Kemp. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson is back in his regular cell block, which he shares with  
two other prisoners, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jail Director W.L. Smith received Tyson's appeal Wednesday,  
hours after a two-member panel at the jail ordered Tyson to 
solitary confinement for 20 days, said jail spokesman Eric 
Seleznow. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith reviewed the appeal and suspended the remaining sanctions  
against Tyson, Seleznow said. The boxer has been placed on a 30-day 
institutional probation and could have his sentence reimposed if he 
commits further violations. 
</P>
<P>
	Seleznow did not say specifically why Smith granted Tyson's  
appeal, but he did say the director tries to be consistent when 
reviewing all inmate cases. 
</P>
<P>
	Jail officials had accused Tyson of disorderly conduct,  
destruction of property and assaulting a corrections officer who 
was hit by shards of plastic when the TV was thrown. Tyson lost 
telephone, visitor and group activity privileges. 
</P>
<P>
	Kemp has said Tyson was provoked when he was abruptly taken off  
Zoloft -- an antidepressant drug he had been taking for four months 
-- after refusing to see a jail psychiatrist. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson's psychiatrist, Dr. Richard Goldberg, chairman of the  
psychiatry department at Georgetown University Medical Center, met 
with the boxer Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Goldberg is now consulting with the medical director at the  
jail, Dr. Martin Colodzin, and Tyson is receiving the proper dosage 
of Zoloft, Kemp said. 
</P>
<P>
	The boxer began serving a one-year jail term Feb. 5 after  
pleading no contest to charges he assaulted two men following a 
minor traffic accident in Gaithersburg, Md. in August. He has until 
March 7 to appeal the sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	Kemp said he has not yet decided whether to appeal.  
</P>
<P>
	Tyson also is on probation for a 1991 rape conviction in  
Indiana. He was released from prison in March 1995 after serving 
three years. Indiana officials are considering whether to revoke 
his probation based on his legal problems in Maryland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990226.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 13:16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Disney Wants City Hall Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Some City Hall officials think a request  
from Disney to use the newly renovated building as a backdrop for a 
Robin Williams movie could be trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney wants to use the landmark for a few days in April or June  
for filming of ``Bicentennial Man.'' The movie studio is willing to 
pay $5,000 a day for the legislative chambers, plus $300 a day for 
a permit. 
</P>
<P>
	The city film office strongly backs the project, but some  
officials are worried about damage to the stately columns, statues 
and gold embellishments that have made it a favorite spot for 
weddings and parties. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's important to remember that City Hall is a place for doing  
business,'' said Supervisor Michael Yaki, ``not for throwing 
parties.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rory Enke, location manager for the movie, said Disney would  
repair any damage. 
</P>
