<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) -- A judge dismissed discrimination  
charges Friday filed by gays against a priest and a radio show 
host. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling found that Roman Catholic priest Minor Calvo did not  
illegally discriminate against homosexuals in a 1998 radio 
broadcast in which he criticized plans to hold a ``Lesbigay'' 
festival in San Jose. The festival was canceled because of heavy 
opposition. 
</P>
<P>
	The president of the group that planned the festival and filed  
the compliant against Calvo, Francisco Madrigal, called the ruling 
``a setback'' for gay rights. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- A bank president was decapitated  
Friday after her helicopter attempted an emergency landing Friday 
in Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	Banco Rural President Junia Rabello, 45, was decapitated by the  
helicopter's blade while climbing out after the pilot attempted to 
land in Sabrara, said Sonia Leao, a spokeswomen for the bank. 
Sabrara is about 210 miles northwest of Rio de Janeiro. 
</P>
<P>
	The helicopter was taking Rabello from her ranch to the Minas  
Gerais state capital Belo Horizonte, the location of the bank's 
headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	Rabello died instantly. The other passenger, identified only as  
Joao, was hit in the head by the blade and died on the way to the 
hospital, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexican health authorities fired five doctors  
from a state-run hospital Friday for transplanting kidneys from an 
HIV-positive donor into two patients in January. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other doctors received warnings from the state-run Mexican  
Social Security Institute, which operates the hospital. It has 
pledged to cover the costs of treatment for one of the patients, 
who has tested HIV-positive. 
</P>
<P>
	The doctors ``acted in good faith but violated procedures'' by  
not awaiting the results of an HIV test they had requested on the 
donor, Ricardo Cavazos Galvan, regional director of the institute, 
told local media. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the two organ recipients died of complications after the  
operation. The other, a 23-year-old man, has tested positive for 
HIV, the virus that causes AIDS. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- A family of six was shot to death  
while sleeping at their home in a Buenos Aires suburb, police said 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other family members were wounded during the attack at Lomas  
de Zamora, south of the Argentine capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Elva Suarez, 39, a Uruguayan citizen, went to a hospital early  
Friday with a bullet wound in her leg. She told police that three 
men whom she did not know kicked down the door of her house at dawn 
and started firing. 
</P>
<P>
	At the house, police found the bodies of Suarez's mother, her  
sister, a 26-year-old man, a teen-ager and two children, who were 7 
and 12. Another young man was wounded, but still alive. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) -- Thousands of cheering  
supporters greeted 92-year-old former President Joaquin Balaguer as 
he returned home Friday from medical treatment in the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	Balaguer was flown to Houston on Jan. 18 for treatment for  
circulatory problems and a lingering bout of flu. He has been 
recuperating in Miami for the past two weeks after being released 
from the hospital in Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	The former president, who ruled this Caribbean country for 22 of  
the last 32 years, took off his hat and waved to the crowd at the 
airport before walking slowly to a waiting car. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite his age and his numerous health problems, Balaguer is  
the choice of more than 70 percent of the members of his political 
party as candidate for president in the 2000 election. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RAWSON, Argentina (AP) -- Forest fires that have raged  
intermittently through southwestern Argentina since January claimed 
a second victim Friday, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	Volunteer firefighter Roberto Barros, 22, was trapped by flames  
and killed at El Maiten, a ranch belonging to Italian clothes 
manufacturers Benetton in Chubut province, 920 miles south of the 
capital Buenos Aires. 
</P>
<P>
	The fires that broke out Thursday have destroyed nearly 1,000  
acres of native forest and 17,800 acres of grassland in the region, 
the Diarios y Noticias news agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Firefighter Juan Negrete, 24, was killed earlier this week while  
battling the fires at Junin de los Andes, on the foothills of the 
Patagonian Andes. 
</P>
