<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dozen GOP Govs. Publicly Back Bush </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A dozen Republican governors publicly lent  
their support Friday to a presidential candidacy by Texas Gov. 
George W. Bush. Leaders of the drive to collect names say seven 
more gubernatorial Bush supporters are on the way. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Paul Cellucci of Massachusetts and Gov. Marc Racicot of  
Montana began collecting names at last week's National Governors' 
Association meeting here. The pair divvied up a list of GOP 
governors -- 30 not including Bush -- to contact and on Friday 
released 12 names. 
</P>
<P>
	Three more governors have committed themselves to endorsing  
Bush, but will not make public statements until they inform party 
members in their states, said Andrew Malcolm, Racicot's executive 
assistant. Malcolm said another four are expected to announce their 
backing in the near future. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush has not formally declared his candidacy. On Thursday, he  
promised an announcement about his presidential ambitions in two 
weeks. But an adviser to Bush said he will form an exploratory 
campaign committee in the next month, which would allow him to 
raise and spend money while testing his potential support. 
</P>
<P>
	The governors said they hope their coalition will encourage Bush  
to run. 
</P>
<P>
	``The ideological and geographical breadth of support among  
Governor Bush's peers demonstrates just how strong a candidate he 
would be,'' Cellucci said. 
</P>
<P>
	Calling Bush a ``proven winner,'' Racicot praised the Texas  
governor's pragmatic reforms and family-oriented administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Other governors listed as Bush supporters are: John Engler of  
Michigan, John Rowland of Connecticut, Frank Keating of Oklahoma, 
Dirk Kempthorne of Idaho, Jeb Bush of Florida, Bill Graves of 
Kansas, Mike Foster of Louisiana, Kenny Guinn of Nevada, Lincoln 
Almond of Rhode Island and Bill Owens of Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, eldest son of the former president, said Friday he intends  
to reveal more about his plans next week. 
</P>
<P>
	``Next week I'll discuss it with you as to whether or not I want  
to take this process a step further,'' Bush said. ``The decision is 
yes, I'm going to run; no, I'm not going to run, or I might run.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
