<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sen. Kerry Won't Run for President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Conceding that he might damage his party's chances  
to win the presidency if he were to run, Sen. John Kerry said 
Friday he will skip the 2000 presidential race. 
</P>
<P>
	``My heart loves the battle. My heart loves these issues. My  
heart said go out and fight for these things. My head said the day 
after I make an announcement I have to raise an exorbitant amount 
of money and do it all in 10 months,'' the Massachusetts Democrat 
said at a news conference Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision not to challenge front-runner Vice President Al  
Gore for the Democratic nomination leaves former Sen. Bill Bradley 
of New Jersey as Gore's only declared competitor so far. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerry's decision could attract others to the field. Jesse  
Jackson is among those who have expressed interest. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other prominent Democrats who have decided against a run  
are Sens. Bob Kerrey of Nebraska and Paul Wellstone, and House 
Minority Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerry said he will eventually endorse one of the Democrats, but  
declined to do that Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerry, a three-term senator, had complained about raising more  
than $20 million to campaign. His wife, Teresa Heinz, widow of Sen. 
John Heinz, R-Pa., is a multimillionaire, but Kerry said Friday 
that he and his wife had decided it would be ``inappropriate'' to 
use their own money. 
</P>
<P>
	Locals were disappointed but not surprised. ``The enormity of  
the task probably has to put a chill into anyone,'' said state 
Speaker of the House Thomas Finneran, D-Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	His decision evoked memories of the 1980 presidential race, when  
the state's senior senator, Ted Kennedy, ran unsuccessfully and was 
criticized for hurting President Jimmy Carter's chances for 
re-election against Ronald Reagan. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, many key supporters and fund-raisers were reportedly  
already committed to Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerry, 55, gained national attention in the 1970s as a decorated  
Vietnam veteran who upon his return spoke out against the war. He 
co-founded Vietnam Veterans Against the War and ran unsuccessfully 
for Congress in 1972. 
</P>
<P>
	He worked as a county prosecutor until being elected lieutenant  
governor of Massachusetts. From there, he launched a successful 
campaign for Senate, succeeding the late Paul Tsongas in 1984. He 
survived a challenge by former Gov. William F. Weld in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
