<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Lighter Side of Business /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IT'S 2000. ALL THE BUGS ARE GONE. NOW WHAT?: Companies that help  
computer users deal with Year 2000 bugs are hot commodities right 
now, but if they haven't figured out yet what they'll do once all 
the problems are fixed, they could be in trouble, says Individual 
Investor magazine. These companies, specialists in information 
technology, will see their revenue decline sharply next year if 20 
percent or more of their business comes from Y2K contracts, the 
magazine says. The most vulnerable are entrepreneurial concerns 
founded primarily on one idea or product for fixing the bugs. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SHOES THAT PINCH YOUR WALLET TOO: Parents grimace when they see  
the prices for basketball shoes, but the average price for these 
shoes edged downward during 1998, according to the National 
Sporting Goods Association. The trade group found basketball shoes 
averaged $55.48 a pair last year, down 0.2 percent from 1997's 
$55.57. But baseball and softball shoe prices were up a sharp 9 
percent, rising to an average $43.03 a pair from $39.49. Golfers 
wore the most expensive sports shoes, paying an average $56.30 a 
pair -- but that was 6.3 percent less than the previous year's 
$60.11. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	NICKEL-AND-DIMING AND DOLLARING, TOO: If you've ever thought  
about adding up what you spend on day-to-day items and seeing just 
how bad the damage is over the course of a year, how does $26,379 
sound? American Express surveyed more than 800 adults in January 
and came up with that projection for a typical budget in 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	The telephone survey included 803 people nationwide who  
identified themselves as the head of their household. They were 
asked about their expenses for groceries and fast-food, gasoline 
and tolls, utilities, insurance, health care, charitable donations, 
subscriptions, tuition, cable, phone and pager, taxes, home 
furnishings, drug store and beauty items -- but not rent or mortgage 
payments. 
</P>
<P>
	About 15 percent of the respondents lived alone, 35 percent had  
two family members, 19 percent had three family members and 17 
percent had four family members. The others had households of five 
or more people. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	THE PSYCHOLOGY OF TIPPING: If you tip a lot, it may not be  
because you're getting great service. You may just be neurotic. 
Cornell University professor Michael Lynn, quoted in Travel Holiday 
magazine, says his research shows the primary motivation for 
tipping in the United States is social approval. ``You feel you 
have to do what is expected,'' Lynn says. ``And you want the server 
to like you.'' Lynn says he's found that servers in restaurants 
earn bigger tips when they introduce themselves, smile, crouch down 
by the table and draw little smiling faces on the check. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
