<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 16:45:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fla. Study: Garbage Jobs Hazardous </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- James Stephens says collecting garbage for a living  
stinks -- literally. But researchers say the stench is nothing 
compared to hazards that make the job the deadliest in the state. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's always a dirty job. We have gotten people hit by cars and  
bit by dogs,'' said Stephens, 62, a garbage collector in Miami for 
28 years who's suffered bumps and bruises but no serious injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	He's been lucky.  
</P>
<P>
	A new study by University of Miami researchers found the rate of  
on-the-job deaths in Florida at 90 per 100,000 garbage collectors. 
</P>
<P>
	That's almost twice the national average -- 49 deaths per 100,000  
-- and more dangerous than piloting a plane and cutting timber, two 
of the most hazardous jobs in the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers, funded by the Florida Center for Solid and  
Hazardous Waste Management, spent a year watching Florida 
sanitation workers haul heavy bags and dodge cars. They analyzed 
five years of injury reports full of cuts, knee sprains, bruises 
and back spasms. 
</P>
<P>
	The study found the rate of injuries to be five to seven times  
higher than the average for other types of workers. That's 52 
injuries per 100 municipal solid-waste workers a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Lead researcher James Englehardt could not say why Florida's  
rate was so much higher than the national average. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we observed is back-breaking work,'' he said. ``It's  
extremely heavy labor with a potential for serious injuries.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About two-thirds of the garbage collectors who died nationwide  
perished in accidents involving automobiles and other vehicles. The 
UM study found that between 1993 and 1997, five of the 11 workers 
who died in Florida were killed in vehicle-related accidents. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some have slipped off the back of the truck and the truck ran  
over them,'' said Willie Seabrooks, president of the American 
Federation of State and County Municipal Employees for Miami-Dade 
County. ``Another guy ran away from a dog and jumped in the back of 
the truck and he got crushed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cars can be deadly, though injuries more commonly are due to  
bags filled with broken glass, poison ivy and even live animals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990226.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 00:13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Assails INS Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican lawmakers, citing the White House's  
decision not to seek 1,000 new Border Patrol agents next year, 
contend the Clinton administration is not doing enough to combat 
illegal immigration and drug trafficking. 
</P>
<P>
	The chairman of the House Judiciary immigration subcommittee  
also criticized Immigration and Naturalization Service managers for 
considering relieving some of the pressure on the agency's 
overburdened detention system by freeing some criminal aliens 
currently behind bars. 
</P>
<P>
	``The administration's record on release of criminal aliens and  
refusal to fund additional Border Patrol agents should be 
disturbing to everyone in the country,'' the panel's chairman, Rep. 
Lamar Smith, R-Texas, said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	INS Commissioner Doris Meissner testified that the  
administration was committed to border enforcement and said the 
much-criticized plan to release 1,500 nonviolent criminal aliens 
had been shelved. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have not released any aliens who are subject to mandatory  
detention under the 1996 immigration law'' and there are no plans 
to do so, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	After word of the possible releases surfaced earlier this month,  
Smith and Rep. Elton Gallegly, R-Calif., threatened to seek 
Meissner's ouster. She said again Thursday she has no plans to 
resign. 
</P>
<P>
	Passage of a sweeping immigration law in 1996 placed new  
pressures on the INS' detention program, with a requirement that 
the agency detain virtually all noncitizens whose criminal 
convictions have made them deportable. Before the requirement took 
full effect last October, the agency could release criminal aliens 
believed to pose no risk. 
</P>
<P>
	Adding to the pressure, the INS agreed to help the four Central  
American countries ravaged by Hurricane Mitch by temporarily 
delaying the deportations of detainees who otherwise would have 
been returned to their homelands. 
</P>
<P>
	The INS now has 16,400 people in custody -- triple the 5,500 five  
years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Budget constraints also have reduced available bed space,  
Meissner said. Last week, the agency requested an extra $80 million 
to add detention space. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith and Gallegly blamed INS managers for inefficiencies in the  
detention program, accusing them of failing to move quickly enough 
to identify and remove deportable criminal aliens who have 
completed their sentences in local jails and state or federal 
prisons. 
</P>
<P>
	Meissner also came under fire for the administration's decision  
not to seek 1,000 extra Border Patrol agents in its fiscal 2000 
budget. The 1996 immigration law directed the administration to add 
1,000 agents a year through 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	With an estimated 70 percent of all illegal drugs coming across  
the Southwest border, the Border Patrol is ``our only line of 
defense,'' Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration contends the Border Patrol, which has more  
than doubled since 1993, cannot continue to absorb new recruits at 
the current level. Nearly 40 percent of all Border Patrol agents 
have been on the job less than two years. Some worry that the ratio 
of inexperienced agents could pose problems for a force already 
accused at times of brutality. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
