<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> California Republicans Regroup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Fresh off November's losses,  
California Republicans will try to regroup at their convention this 
weekend as six White House hopefuls attempt to unify and rally the 
demoralized troops. 
</P>
<P>
	Abortion looms as a potential stumbling block.  
</P>
<P>
	While one wing of the party supports abortion rights and another  
faction wants to bury the issue, all six of the presidential 
hopefuls oppose abortion. Several have unmistakably made banning 
abortion a central mission of their candidacies, and appear 
unlikely to shy away from it this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the 1860s, Lincoln ended the moral outrage of slavery  
because he knew it was wrong. Abortion is the moral outrage of the 
20th century, and I will end it because it too is wrong,'' Sen. Bob 
Smith of New Hampshire said last week as he announced his 
candidacy. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican moderates cringe at such words, believing that the  
party should soften its opposition and broaden its appeal to women. 
Republican gubernatorial candidate Dan Lungren spoke out against 
abortion in his campaign last year, and drew just 37 percent of 
female voters. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are on the verge of perfecting our circular firing-squad  
formation,'' warned Dan Schnur, a GOP media consultant who advised 
the Lungren campaign. Disputes over abortion and other issues have 
made state GOP conventions acts of ``semiannual self-immolation,'' 
he wrote in a recent opinion column. 
</P>
<P>
	Even some staunch abortion opponents want the issue to go away  
as the party seeks to rebuild four months after voters swept 
Republicans from nearly all statewide offices. Sensing the looming 
battle, they are publicly trying to avoid a bitter leadership 
fight. 
</P>
<P>
	The same day Smith was denouncing abortion in his candidacy  
speech, 23 Republican lawmakers -- several of whom have carried 
anti-abortion legislation -- called on state party activists to 
focus on other issues as they elect a new chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't like all the fights we're getting in the middle of  
over abortion or other things that seem to happen constantly within 
our party,'' said Republican Assemblyman Bruce Thompson, an 
abortion opponent from Temecula. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now the Republican Party is probably in the worst shape  
it's ever been,'' he said. ``We are in disarray, we are lacking in 
leadership at the top of the party.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Silicon Valley entrepreneur John McGraw, currently the state  
party's vice chairman, would ordinarily ascend to chairman with 
little fanfare. But his fiercely anti-abortion views have prompted 
a challenge from Stanislaus County Republican leader Nicholas 
Bavaro, who has said he would, if elected, stress other themes. 
</P>
<P>
	Bavaro and other moderates call themselves the Republican  
Mainstream Team. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our current party leadership is seen by too many voters as  
`extreme,' even `radical,''' the team wrote to convention 
delegates. ``Democrats charge that a `cult of antiabortion zealots' 
run the state party.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jon Fleischman, deputy executive director of the California  
Republican Party, said the GOP must realize it will not settle the 
abortion issue ``at this convention, or frankly any other 
convention.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Republicans have to understand that not everyone is going to  
agree on the platform,'' he said. ``You move forward on the issues 
of common agreement.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
