<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 23:31:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marine Pilot: I Was Looking at Map </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- Apart from a navigational miscue,  
Capt. Richard Ashby said his training mission through the Italian 
Alps last winter felt normal, even comfortable. 
</P>
<P>
	He crested a ridge in the Marine jet and glanced at a map  
strapped to the knee of his navigator to make sure he was in the 
right valley. Then he looked up and saw a gondola cable looming in 
his windscreen. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought we were dead,'' Ashby said. ``I thought this wire  
was going to go through the canopy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his first public comment, Ashby testified Friday about last  
February's accident at the Mount Cermis ski resort that sent 20 
people in the gondola plunging to their deaths and caused an uproar 
in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby, the pilot of the EA-6B Prowler that clipped the cable, is  
being court-martialed on 20 counts of involuntary manslaughter and 
other charges and faces more than 200 years in prison. The trial is 
in recess until Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense lawyers argue he was given a map without the cableway  
marked on it, that he may have suffered an optical illusion and 
that his jet's radar altimeter malfunctioned. Prosecutors contend 
he simply flew too fast -- more than 600 mph -- and much too low. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby, 31, of Mission Viejo, Calif., held a model of the jet as  
he explained to the military jury how he lowered his plane into the 
valley where the ski lift was situated. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't feel high and I didn't feel low,'' he said. ``I felt  
comfortable. It felt right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But after spotting the gondola, Ashby said he instinctively  
ducked and pushed his stick forward, causing the plane to descend. 
</P>
<P>
	``I watched this wire go over the canopy and nothing happened,  
and I started to recover. Then at some point between nothing and 
recovering, there's a thump like that,'' he said, knocking the 
witness box rail. 
</P>
<P>
	The jet's right wing had two gashes in it and its tail fin was  
damaged by the wire. Ashby brought the jet back to the NATO air 
base at Aviano, where he and his three crewmates were stationed for 
possible duty in Bosnia. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby said that at the outset of the flight, he set the radar  
low-altitude alarm to go off at 800 feet -- 200 feet below the 
minimum prescribed altitude and about 430 feet higher than where 
the plane struck the cable. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't want the thing going off continuously,'' he  
testified. ``You want that tone to mean something to you. It means, 
`I've got to do something with the aircraft now or I'm going to 
die.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby said he was trying to maintain a 1,000-foot altitude  
during the flight. He was not asked whether the alarm went off 
before the accident. 
</P>
<P>
	Other witnesses, including the backseat crewmen, have testified  
that the alarm did not sound as it should have after the jet 
descended into the valley. 
</P>
<P>
	Before Ashby testified, a Marine Corps electronics expert said  
the jet's radar altimeter may have misread altitudes because it had 
a broken wire that created interference with the radar signal. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby also said he knew of no speed limit for the mission,  
despite prosecutors' claims that it was 517 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	The navigator on the flight, Capt. Joseph Schweitzer, 31,  
attempted to videotape the early part of the mission through the 
Dolomite Mountains, but had trouble operating the camera and put it 
away. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby said he pocketed the tape after they landed. Later,  
Schweitzer asked for it, and Ashby told jurors that never saw it 
again. Both men are charged with obstruction of justice because 
investigators never found the tape; Schweitzer also faces the 
involuntary manslaughter charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Europeans were outraged over the accident, and Italians demanded  
that U.S. landing rights be revoked at bases in their country. The 
officers' lawyers have argued the aviators were charged because of 
political pressure that went as high as the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby said during cross-examination by the government that he  
realized his actions caused the deaths of 20 people. 
</P>
<P>
	``I accept responsibility, but there's a difference between  
responsibility and criminal responsibility,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't imagine going to jail, can you?'' asked the  
prosecutor. 
</P>
<P>
	``No, I can't,'' Ashby replied.  
</P>
<P>
	Ashby denied being negligent during the flight.  
</P>
<P>
	``Mistakes were made on this flight -- and any flight, any  
mission you fly, mistakes are made,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby said under questioning from his lawyers that he was  
initially trained to fly at 500 feet. Once, while serving in Italy 
in 1996, he was flying at that altitude in the mountains when he 
encountered a paraglider. 
</P>
<P>
	``It scared the hell out of me,'' Ashby said. ``I could see the  
whites of his eyes.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990226.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 17:48:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls Against Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell slightly against the yen Friday,  
turning downward after an early rally that had been lit by a U.S. 
Treasury official's criticism of the Japanese government's economic 
recovery efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar narrowly rose against the euro during a day when the  
yen was the focus. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been quiet on all other fronts. The story is the  
dollar/yen (transactions) getting whipped around,'' said Jay 
Bryson, an international economist at First Union Capital Markets 
in Charlotte, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 119.17  
Japanese yen, down from 119.63 on Thursday. Also in late trading, 
the euro was quoted at $1.1026, down from $1.1032. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders dumped yen and bought dollars, sending the dollar up  
about 2 yen, during the Asian trading session. That followed 
reports concerning Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers' tone 
during meetings with Japanese officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Yukihiko Ikeda, a top official in the ruling Liberal Democratic  
Party, told reporters that Summers had urged Japan to take greater 
action in fighting its worst recession in decades. 
</P>
<P>
	Ikeda said Summers told him that ``the Bank of Japan's monetary  
steps so far may not be enough. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. has been pressuring the Bank of Japan to expand money  
supply. That would push down the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders rode the dollar higher on expectations the Bank of Japan  
would take immediate action in response. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone thought this is the pressure that is going to do  
it,'' Bryson said. But after a while, investors put the dollar into 
a tailspin, sending the U.S. currency and the euro falling by 2 1/2 
yen. 
</P>
<P>
	``There has been a rethink on how quick the bank is going to  
start'' its work, Bryson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the euro ``tried to stage a bounce off the bottom and  
didn't get anywhere,'' said Kathy Jones, a currency analyst at 
Prudential Securities. Investors are expecting that higher interest 
rates in the United States will weaken the euro in comparison to 
the dollar, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4469 Swiss francs, down from  
1.4485, and 1.5101 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4979. The British 
pound fell to $1.6026, down from $1.6033. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the countries participating in the euro no longer  
are traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Friday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.7737 German 
marks, up from 1.7727; 5.9488 French francs, up from 5.9453; and 
Italian lire, 1,757.47, up from 1,754.39. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990226.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 10:34:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Higher; Gold Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar rose against most other major  
currencies in European trading Friday. Gold was mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders were paying 119.30 Japanese yen for each dollar, down  
from late Thursday's 120.15 yen. At midday in New York, the dollar 
was quoted at 119.10 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In other European trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0982, up  
from $1.1042, while the British pound was quoted at $1.6003, down 
from $1.6025. Later in New York, the euro was fetching $1.1005 and 
the pound was quoted at $1.6035. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates compared with late Thursday included 1.4472  
Swiss francs, up from 1.4376; and 1.5095 Canadian dollars, up from 
1.5020 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on euro rates, the dollar was worth 1.7809 German marks,  
up from 1.7713; 5.9730 French francs, up from 5.9406; 2.0067 Dutch 
guilders, up from 1.9958; 1,763.13 Italian lire, up from 1,753.55. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $286.40 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$287.30 on Thursday. In Zurich, the bid price was $287.00, up from 
$286.40. Gold fell 30 cents in Hong Kong to close at $286.95. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.56 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$5.47. 
</P>
</TEXT>
