<HEADLINE> Browns Sign Thierry, Make Him LB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- The Browns are convinced John Thierry has spent  
his entire NFL career playing the wrong position. 
</P>
<P>
	Thierry, a converted defensive end for the Chicago Bears the  
past five years, was signed Friday by Cleveland, which plans to use 
the 27-year-old free agent at linebacker. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thierry has the opportunity to become an important piece of  
our defensive unit with his movement to the linebacker spot,'' said 
Dwight Clark, Cleveland's director of football operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Thierry was capable of wreaking havoc on college quarterbacks at  
Alcorn State. Using his 4.5 speed in the 40 to rush quarterbacks 
from his outside linebacker/standup end position, Thierry earned 
All-American honors. 
</P>
<P>
	But after being drafted by the Bears with the No. 11 pick in the  
first round in 1994, Thierry bulked up from 248 pounds to 265 and 
was moved to right defensive end. He struggled against 300-pound 
offensive tackles and recorded just 12 1/2 sacks in five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of his coaches in Chicago, including Bob Slowik, the Browns  
defensive coordinator, thought Thierry was out of position but 
couldn't convince head coach Dave Wannstedt to make a switch. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's something that I did hear the past five years,'' said  
Thierry's agent, Richard DeLuca. ``He was a coverage guy in 
college. He should have been playing linebacker.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Browns signed Thierry to a one-year contract for $1 million  
with ``a nice incentive package,'' said DeLuca. 
</P>
<P>
	DeLuca said Thierry made only one demand before he began  
negotiating. 
</P>
<P>
	``To get him a 50-something on his back,'' said DeLuca,  
referring to the numbers given to linebackers. ``And that's what I 
did. He'll wear 53 for the Browns.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thierry will be reunited with two former Chicago coaches who are  
now with the Browns, Slowik and defensive line coach Clarence 
Brooks. 
</P>
<P>
	Thierry's signing was the only official announcement this week  
by the Browns, who earlier this week landed quarterback Ty Detmer 
in a trade with the San Francisco 49ers. 
</P>
<P>
	Detmer, who was hunting cougar in Utah with friends when the  
deal was finalized, is expected to sign the waiver to his no-trade 
clause when he visits Cleveland on Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
