<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Group Files Complaint Against Intel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An Internet civil liberties group asked the  
Federal Trade Commission on Friday to prohibit Intel Corp. from 
selling its latest Pentium computer processors because of privacy 
concerns over new technology in the chips. 
</P>
<P>
	The Washington-based Center for Democracy and Technology said  
Intel used ``unfair and deceptive trade practices'' in describing 
the new chip's technology as a security feature but never 
mentioning its privacy ramifications. 
</P>
<P>
	An FTC spokeswoman, Vicki Streitfeld, said the agency will  
``seriously review'' the complaint. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel designed its new Pentium III chips to transmit a unique  
serial number internally -- and to Web sites that request it -- to 
help verify the identity of consumers. It argues that the feature 
will help eliminate online fraud and control access to sensitive 
data. 
</P>
<P>
	Some privacy groups, however, contend that the so-called  
tracking technology will give companies unprecedented ability to 
trace consumers' moves as they navigate the Web. 
</P>
<P>
	The democracy and technology center's formal complaint Friday  
asked the FTC to enjoin Intel from selling its Pentium III chips 
with the tracking technology. It also asked the FTC to prohibit 
computer makers from selling machines with the chips unless the 
technology is turned off ``in a secure manner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The complaint didn't specify what computer makers could do to  
satisfy its concerns. A few companies have already indicated they 
plan to disable the technology in each computer's system settings, 
called its Bios. 
</P>
<P>
	``The manufacturers are in this difficult situation, where Intel  
has thrown this issue in their lap,'' said Ari Schwartz, a policy 
analyst for the center. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel spokesman Tom Waldrop said the complaint appears similar  
to previous appeals to the FTC from other privacy groups. 
</P>
<P>
	``We certainly don't think we've done anything deceptive or  
unfair,'' Waldrop said. ``We really don't see anything new. We have 
talked in the past with (privacy groups) and we realize we have a 
difference of opinion.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
