<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> L.A. Organizing Gives Unions Boost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The biggest union organizing victory in more  
than half a century -- 74,000 Los Angeles County home care workers -- 
could be the start of a national resurgence by organized labor. 
</P>
<P>
	The organizing drive by the Service Employees International  
Union highlights the shift in labor's focus away from high-paid 
manufacturing jobs like autoworkers and toward the low-paying 
service sector, especially health care where just 1 million of 12 
million workers nationally are union members. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an awfully important victory for the symbolism it  
represents. This vote shows labor has huge success in the service 
sector and with women and minorities,'' said Harley Shaiken, a 
University of California, Berkeley, professor specializing in labor 
issues. 
</P>
<P>
	``We live in a world that is an information and service  
economy,'' said Andrew L. Stern, national president of the 1.3 
million-member SEIU. ``Our goal is to make sure workers in the 
service economy have a choice, not only about the quality of their 
own jobs, but the quality of service,'' said Stern whose union is 
the third-largest and fastest growing affiliate of the AFL-CIO. 
</P>
<P>
	Los Angeles County's home care providers -- many earning $5.75 an  
hour to feed and bathe 80,000 elderly and disabled -- voted 16,200 
to 1,925 to unionize, according to the final tally Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	It was labor's biggest organizing victory since 1937 when  
112,000 General Motors employees joined the United Auto Workers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe that the history books will show that their triumph  
today will play as important a role in American history as the mass 
organizing drives in the 1930s,'' said John Sweeney, president of 
the American Federation of Labor and Congress of Industrial 
Organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	The AFL-CIO is the umbrella organization for 72 unions  
representing about 13 million workers, including the SEIU. 
</P>
<P>
	Shaiken, Berkeley's labor specialist, said the impact of the  
California vote extends beyond homecare workers to organizing ``the 
new face of labor'' such as fast-food employees. 
</P>
<P>
	``The future of labor is inextricably tied up with organizing  
women and minority workers. Both are vital to labor's survival and 
growth. This is a campaign that represents a new vitality for 
labor,'' Shaiken said. 
</P>
<P>
	Janitors, hotel workers and now unionized health care workers.  
Who's next for the union? 
</P>
<P>
	``We are seeing the day where unions refocus themselves in a way  
to be attractive to those in historically high-turnover and 
low-wage jobs,'' Stern said. ``In Seattle, we have a major, 
groundbreaking campaign among daycare workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The downside of the movement is the increased cost, said Rick  
Gundling, technical director of the Westchester, Ill.-based 
nonprofit Healthcare Financial Management Association. 
</P>
<P>
	The homecare industry has been under pressure to cut expenses  
and unionizing might threaten its survival, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anything that adds to a more costly system is not to the best  
advantage for health plans and the desire to keep health care costs 
down,'' said Gundling, whose 35,000-member group includes financial 
management professionals employed by managed-care groups, 
hospitals, nursing homes and other organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	Union advocates expect organizing the health field to remain a  
tough battle. The Los Angeles County home care worker campaign 
lasted 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Employers don't want advocates for patients at the bedside.  
They will continue to resist giving health care workers a voice. 
But workers know it's time to be heard in this new health care 
industry,'' Stern said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
