<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990226.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 15:34:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls Against Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell slightly against the yen Friday,  
turning downward after an early rally that had been lit by a U.S. 
Treasury official's criticism of the Japanese government's economic 
recovery efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar narrowly rose against the euro during a day when the  
yen was the focus. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been quiet on all other fronts. The story is the  
dollar/yen (transactions) getting whipped around,'' said Jay 
Bryson, an international economist at First Union Capital Markets 
in Charlotte, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 119.17  
Japanese yen, down from 119.63 on Thursday. Also in late trading, 
the euro was quoted at $1.1026, down from $1.1032. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders dumped yen and bought dollars, sending the dollar up  
about 2 yen, during the Asian trading session. That followed 
reports concerning Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers' tone 
during meetings with Japanese officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Yukihiko Ikeda, a top official in the ruling Liberal Democratic  
Party, told reporters that Summers had urged Japan to take greater 
action in fighting its worst recession in decades. 
</P>
<P>
	Ikeda said Summers told him that ``the Bank of Japan's monetary  
steps so far may not be enough. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. has been pressuring the Bank of Japan to expand money  
supply. That would push down the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders rode the dollar higher on expectations the Bank of Japan  
would take immediate action in response. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone thought this is the pressure that is going to do  
it,'' Bryson said. But after a while, investors put the dollar into 
a tailspin, sending the U.S. currency and the euro falling by 2 1/2 
yen. 
</P>
<P>
	``There has been a rethink on how quick the bank is going to  
start'' its work, Bryson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the euro ``tried to stage a bounce off the bottom and  
didn't get anywhere,'' said Kathy Jones, a currency analyst at 
Prudential Securities. Investors are expecting that higher interest 
rates in the United States will weaken the euro in comparison to 
the dollar, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4469 Swiss francs, down from  
1.4485, and 1.5101 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4979. The British 
pound fell to $1.6026, down from $1.6033. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the countries participating in the euro no longer  
are traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Friday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.7737 German 
marks, up from 1.7727; 5.9488 French francs, up from 5.9453; and 
Italian lire, 1,757.47, up from 1,754.39. 
</P>
</TEXT>
