<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Feb. 26, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	GDP Grows at 6.1 Pct. Annual Rate  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite the global financial crisis, the U.S.  
economy grew at its fastest pace in nearly 15 years in the last 
quarter, closing out a year in which Americans enjoyed the best 
combination of rapid growth, low unemployment and low inflation in 
at least three decades. The nation's gross domestic product, the 
total output of goods and services, shot up at a sizzling annual 
rate of 6.1 percent from October through December, the Commerce 
Department said today. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Down; Dow Off 59.76  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock indexes fell today, led by a selloff in  
technology shares, after Compaq Computer's warning of soft sales 
raised concerns of slowdown in the computer market. The Dow Jones 
industrial average closed down 59.76 at 9,306.58, expanding 
yesterday's 33.33-point decline. Most broader stock indicators were 
lower as well. The Nasdaq composite index with its many tech stocks 
was down 38.81 at 2,288.01. Compaq, the world's biggest maker of 
personal computers, warned analysts that sales in its small- and 
medium- business market have slowed this quarter. That prompted 
Merrill Lynch and Credit Suisse First Boston to cut its 
first-quarter earnings projection for Compaq, whose shares fell 5 
11/16 to 35 5/16 on the New York Stock Exchange. Other 
computer-makers, including IBM, Gateway and Dell, also fell sharply 
today on concerns that their sales may also slow in coming months. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:  
