</P>
<P>
	Feds Still Working On Y2K Bug  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite progress with the year 2000 computer  
problem, serious concerns remain about the ability of the agency 
that handles billions of dollars in Medicare and Medicaid payments 
to be problem-free by Jan. 1, a government auditor said today. The 
Health Care Financing Administration still must perform a 
tremendous amount of testing on its computer systems before the end 
of the year, Joel Willemssen, director of civil agencies 
information systems at the General Accounting Office, the 
investigative arm of Congress, told a House panel. But Nancy-Ann 
DeParle, the agency's administrator, said that while there was 
still a lot of work to be done, its systems would be repaired in 
time. 

</P>
<P>
	AlliedSignal Can Vote on Tyco Deal  
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- AlliedSignal Inc., rejected in its hostile  
bid to acquire AMP Inc., will get to vote on Tyco International 
Ltd.'s $11.3 billion agreement to buy the maker of electrical 
components, a federal appeals court has ruled. AlliedSignal already 
owns 200 million shares, or 9.1 percent, of AMP, that it purchased 
before making a $10 billion bid for Harrisburg, Pa.-based company. 
The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reversed a ruling that 
AlliedSignal could not vote as a shareholder because of a 1990 
state anti-takeover law. 

</P>
<P>
	Kerr McGee-Oryx Energy Merger OK'd  
</P>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Shareholders of Kerr-McGee Corp. and Oryx  
Energy Co. approved the merger of the two energy companies, a deal 
that will mean the loss of about 500 jobs. About 40 percent of the 
combined oil and gas workforce will be reduced as a result of the 
merger, which will create the country's fourth-largest independent 
energy exploration and production company. Debbie Schramm, 
spokeswoman for Kerr-McGee, said the two companies had about 1,300 
employees in oil and gas in November. The count will be reduced to 
between 775 and 800 jobs. 

</P>
<P>
	Eli Lilly Is Sued Over Evista  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- British drug maker Zeneca Inc. has sued rival  
Eli Lilly &AMP; Co., accusing the company of improperly selling its 
osteoporosis drug Evista as a medication to prevent breast cancer. 
Evista is not approved as a breast cancer drug in the United 
States, though early tests look promising. Zeneca makes Nolvadex, 
which in October became the first drug approved by the Food and 
Drug Administration to reduce the risk of breast cancer in healthy 
women. 

</P>
<P>
	Dean Foods Recalls Some Ice Cream  
</P>
<P>
	FRANKLIN PARK, Ill. (AP) -- Dean Foods has recalled two brands of  
cookie dough ice cream that failed to list eggs on the ingredient 
labels. Dean officials said today the recall would amount to less 
than 10,000 gallons of chocolate chip cookie dough ice cream sold 
under the Dean and Reiter brand and produced at the company's plant 
in Belvidere, Ill. The egg ingredient in the cookie dough pieces 
could cause a life threatening reaction in people allergic or 
sensitive to eggs, company officials said. 

</P>
<P>
	Crown Central Considers Sale  
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Crown Central Petroleum is considering a  
possible sale of all or part of the company to appease 
shareholders. The disclosure was included in the Baltimore-based 
company's fourth-quarter and year-end earnings report released 
yesterday, which showed Crown Central finished in the red for the 
seventh time in eight years. Crown, a leading petroleum products 
refiner, has hired Credit Suisse First Boston's Energy Group to 
help evaluate its alternatives. 

</P>
<P>
	Hilton Opens 5-Star Hotel in Hanoi  
</P>
<P>
	HANOI, Vietnam (AP) -- A new Hanoi Hilton opened in Vietnam today  
and this one really is a hotel -- not to be confused with the 
infamous prison where American POWs were kept during the Vietnam 
War. The Hilton Hotel Opera is just a few blocks from the old 
prison, which was mostly destroyed in 1995, leaving only a wing for 
a museum. The $64 million hotel sits adjacent to Hanoi's newly 
renovated Opera House. The opening comes at a time of economic 
crisis for Asia and drooping tourism. High-end hotel occupancy 
rates plunged to about 30 percent last year. 

</P>
<P>
	Hard Rock Cafe, NBA Plan Restaurant  
</P>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- NBA officials and players have broken  
ground on a basketball-oriented restaurant. National Basketball 
Association legends Dolph Schayes, John Havlicek and James Worthy, 
Orlando Magic center Ike Austin and the WNBA's Nykesha Sales were 
on hand for the groundbreaking ceremony for the 17,000-square-foot 
NBA City restaurant at Universal Studio's Citywalk entertainment 
district. Hard Rock Cafe, which operates 99 rock-themed restaurants 
in 35 countries, will build the NBA City restaurant and plans to 
open nine more NBA City restaurants around the globe over the next 
four years. 

</P>
