<DOCNO> APW19990226.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 13:54:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> It's a New Season for Braves' Weiss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KISSIMMEE, Fla. (AP) -- Walt Weiss would like nothing better than  
a nice, normal season. No surprises this time. 
</P>
<P>
	A year ago, Weiss was forced into the leadoff role for the  
Atlanta Braves and wound up playing in his first All-Star game at 
age 34. But he also nursed his son through a potentially fatal 
illness and struggled to run on a sore leg. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a strange year,'' he said, relaxing at his locker prior  
to a spring training workout. 
</P>
<P>
	Brody Weiss, now 4, has recovered from an E. coli infection that  
shut down his kidneys last summer, though his weakened immune 
system still leaves him susceptible to illness. 
</P>
<P>
	Just a couple of weeks ago, his parents rushed the youngster to  
a hospital emergency room when he was stricken with the flu, 
suffering from many of the same symptoms that marked his previous 
illness. 
</P>
<P>
	``We try not to be too paranoid '' his father said. ``He's able  
to do all the things he could before, but there have been times 
when we got nervous. ... There's always a little reminder here and 
there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Weiss, meanwhile, spent the first part of the offseason resting  
his ailing left quadriceps muscle, then began a running program 
that he hopes will prevent the same thing from happening again. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just couldn't run all year,'' Weiss said. ``There was  
probably three weeks where I was running at full speed. It was so 
frustrating to hit balls in the hole to the shortstop -- the guy 
having to dive for them -- and you can't beat it out. It takes a lot 
of the fun out of the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Brody's illness gave his father a new perspective on life.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure I look at things a lot differently,'' Weiss said.  
``When you're out there playing, it doesn't change anything. But 
after the fact, I'm able to turn the page a lot easier. When we got 
beat in the playoffs, it was disappointing. At the same time, it 
was time to get home and take care of my family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Through all the pain and family anguish, Weiss still managed to  
put together one of the best seasons of his 11-year career. With no 
one else to fill the leadoff role, he willingly moved to that spot 
in the order and batted .280 -- 20 points above his career average -- 
with a .386 on-base percentage. 
</P>
<P>
	But Weiss doesn't have the speed that typifies most leadoff  
hitters -- even healthy -- so he likely will move to a lower spot in 
the order now that Otis Nixon is back with the Braves. 
</P>
<P>
	Weiss would prefer to bat second in the lineup, ahead of Chipper  
Jones, but doesn't mind going back to the eighth spot, where he has 
spent most of his career. 
</P>
<P>
	``Eighth is the exact opposite of second. You don't get a lot of  
pitches, especially with a runner in scoring position,'' Weiss 
said. ``The thing I do like about the eighth spot is there is 
always something to think about every at-bat. You have to have a 
game plan, and it changes a lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Weiss' defense has always been a no-brainer. This season, he  
will team with second baseman Bret Boone, acquired in a trade from 
Cincinnati, to give the Braves one of the best double-play duos in 
the league. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I was over on that other field,'' said infield coach  
Glenn Hubbard, pointing to the minor-league complex where he worked 
last year, ``I would tell my guys to watch Walt Weiss. Just watch 
what he does out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The double-play combination no longer includes first baseman  
Andres Galarraga, who is out for the season after being diagnosed 
with cancer. Weiss, who has played with the Big Cat since 1994 -- 
first in Colorado, then in Atlanta -- was especially devastated by 
the news. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was driving around Denver the day before I came down here  
and I heard it on the radio,'' he said. ``Something like that makes 
you realize how fragile we all are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Weiss, sitting beside Galarraga's empty locker, plans to write  
his old friend a letter to express his thoughts. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's so easy to get consumed by this game,'' Weiss said.  
``We've all done it. We need little reminders that it shouldn't be 
that way.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
