<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Saturday, Feb. 27, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	McCain: Avoid Negative Campaigning  
</P>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Casting himself as the conscience of  
the GOP presidential field, Sen. John McCain on Friday promised 
``not to stoop to negative campaigning against fellow Republicans'' 
and challenged his rivals to take a similar pledge. ``Scorched 
earth Republican primaries will lead directly to an Al Gore 
presidency,'' the Arizona senator warned in a speech to the 
California Republican Party. Four other GOP presidential prospects 
addressing the same group Saturday have been highly critical of 
front-runner Texas Gov. George W. Bush. They are former Vice 
President Dan Quayle, businessman Steve Forbes, activist Gary Bauer 
and former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Outlines Foreign Policy  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- In a sweeping review of world problems,  
President Clinton warned Friday that NATO is ``prepared to act'' in 
Kosovo, pledged to redouble his efforts for peace in the Middle 
East and offered encouragement to Russia and China in their 
struggle for prosperous stability. Laying out his foreign policy 
hopes for the final two years of his presidency, Clinton said, 
``For our nation to be strong, we must maintain a consensus that 
seemingly distant problems can come home if they are not addressed 
and addressed promptly.'' 

</P>
<P>
	China Criticized on Human Rights  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- China's human rights record deteriorated  
sharply late last year with a crackdown on political dissent that 
reversed recent signs of improvement, the Clinton administration 
said Friday. The administration's critical assessment of China's 
human rights performance came on the eve of Secretary of State 
Madeleine Albright's departure for Beijing. 

</P>
<P>
	Serb Border Police Detain Monitors  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Serb border police detained  
diplomatic observers and forcibly searched their cars in an 
incident the chief monitor called ``ominous.'' Police told the 
monitors they were ``suspicious'' about the contents of the 
vehicles. William Walker, head of Kosovo monitors for the 
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, said a 
cease-fire between Yugoslav and ethnic Albanian forces was 
``non-existent'' despite NATO warnings for both sides to abstain 
from violence during a 2 1/2-week suspension of peace talks. 

</P>
<P>
	Iraq Contacts U.N. Weapons Panel  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Iraq has contacted an expert panel that is  
exploring ways to restart U.N. weapons inspections, the panel's 
chairman said Friday. The Iraqi government invited the chairman, 
Brazilian U.N. Ambassador Celso Amorim, to visit Baghdad. The 
disarmament panel is holding its first meeting this week and will 
initially assess the state of the eight-year U.N. effort to rid 
Iraq of its nuclear, chemical and biological weapons and long-range 
missiles. 

</P>
<P>
	Group Files Complaint Against Intel  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An Internet civil liberties group asked the  
Federal Trade Commission on Friday to prohibit Intel Corp. from 
selling its latest Pentium computer processors because of privacy 
concerns over new technology in the chips. The Washington-based 
Center for Democracy and Technology said Intel used ``unfair and 
deceptive trade practices'' in describing the new chip's technology 
as a security feature but never mentioning its privacy 
ramifications. An FTC spokeswoman said the agency will ``seriously 
review'' the complaint. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Closes Down 59.76  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices fell for the fourth day in a row.  
The Dow Jones industrial average ended down 59.76 at 9,306.58. On 
the NYSE, losers led gainers 1,511-1,458. The Nasdaq composite 
index fell 38.81 to 2,288.01. 

</P>
<P>
	Warriors Beat Suns 94-90  
</P>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Donyell Marshall scored 15 points,  
including a pair of free throws with 4.6 seconds remaining, as the 
Golden State Warriors beat the Phoenix Suns 94-90 Friday night. 
Golden State ended an eight-game losing streak to the Suns and won 
for the sixth time in seven games to reach .500 (6-6). It's the 
first time the Warriors have been a .500 team this deep into a 
season since they were 8-8 in December 1994. 

</P>
<P>
	Lightning Stun Flyers 4-1  
</P>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Stephane Richer scored two first-period goals  
and goaltender Corey Schwab stopped 36 shots as the Tampa Bay 
Lightning surprised the Philadelphia Flyers 4-1 on Friday night. 
Richer, who ended a 17-game goal-scoring drought, gave the 
Lightning -- the NHL's worst team -- a quick 2-0 lead with goals at 
9:44 and 15:23 of the opening period. The Flyers, who sit atop the 
Atlantic Division, are 2-6-2 in their last 10 games after putting 
together a 16-1-6 run. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  

</P>
