<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> P&AMP;G Says Diaper Prevents Rash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Procter &AMP; Gamble says it has developed the  
first diaper medically proven to prevent and treat rashes, and the 
company figures parents are willing to pay 50 percent more than 
they do for regular Pampers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pampers Rash Guard began arriving at some stores last week.  
They contain strips treated with petrolatum, found in petroleum 
jelly, and stearate, a skin conditioner. The diaper can still 
absorb waste because not all areas are treated with the 
conditioners. 
</P>
<P>
	P&AMP;G hopes the diapers will be good not only for the bottom, but  
for the bottom line. A jumbo package of 36 Rash Guard diapers costs 
about $13.25, the same as the average price of a package of 56 
basic diapers. That works out to about 37 cents for each Rash Guard 
diaper compared with 24 cents for the standard product. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our consumer research has shown us not only that diaper rash  
is a painful and common ailment for children, but it causes a 
genuine misery for parents, who feel guilty over not being able to 
prevent their children's suffering,'' P&AMP;G spokesman Scott Stewart 
said Friday. ``This is a way to help both.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dena Smith, the mother of a 6-month-old girl and an aide at Hope  
Early Childhood Center in Cincinnati, said she is interested, but 
might try to save money by limiting use of the new diapers to 
nights, when changes are less frequent. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would be willing to try anything I thought would help, but  
the added expense may keep some people from trying it,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Anita Sheth, who has three children, including an  
8-month-old, isn't ready to recommend Rash Guard, however. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a skeptic. My first impression is that I'm not sure I  
would be willing to pay the price for the product,'' said Dr. 
Sheth, director of pediatric dermatology at Children's Hospital in 
Cincinnati. ``The primary thing for prevention is really good 
hygiene and changing diapers frequently.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Diaper rash is caused partly by wetness, which causes irritation  
and abrasion of the baby's skin, leading sometimes to sores that 
require medical attention. 
</P>
<P>
	About two out of three babies suffer a rash monthly and at least  
one-third of parents think their babies get the ailment frequently, 
according to Cincinnati-based P&AMP;G. 
</P>
<P>
	Kimberly-Clark Corp., the maker of Huggies, the nation's most  
popular diapers, said it is considering its options and monitoring 
P&AMP;G's product. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is nothing difficult about coating a diaper with  
petrolatum and stearate, but we welcome competitiveness,'' 
spokeswoman Wendy Strong said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
