<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded  
heavily Friday on the New York Stock Exchange, Nasdaq Stock Market, 
and American Stock Exchange. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	
</P>
<P>
	Compaq Computer fell 5 5/8 to 35 3/8.  
</P>
<P>
	Merrill Lynch and Credit Suisse First Boston cut their  
first-quarter earnings estimates on the giant computer maker after 
the company warned that its PC sales in the small- and 
medium-business market have been ``soft'' thus far in the quarter. 

</P>
<P>
	Navistar rose 3 5/8 to 43.  
</P>
<P>
	Swedish business daily Dagens Industri reported today that  
automaker Volvo is expected to soon make an offer for Chicago-based 
truckmaker Navistar International. 

</P>
<P>
                              *NASDAQ   	
</P>
<P>
	Intel fell 7 13/16 to 119 15/16.  
</P>
<P>
	Advanced Micro Devices fell 1/4 to 17 7/8 on the NYSE.  
</P>
<P>
	Advanced Micro Devices' AMD-K6 processor-based computers outsold  
all Intel Corp.-based desktop PCs in the U.S. retail market in 
January, according to PC Data's January Retail Hardware Report. 
AMD's processor accounted for 43.9 percent of sales, while Intel 
had 40.3 percent. It was the first time that Intel fell out of the 
top spot. 

</P>
<P>
	Intuit rose 9 3/8 to 98 15/16.  
</P>
<P>
	The consumer and small-business finance software company  
reported earnings for its fiscal second quarter that topped Wall 
Street analysts' estimates. 

</P>
<P>
	VLSI rose 4 3/4 to 15 1/2.  
</P>
<P>
	Dutch electronics giant Royal Philips Electronics NV offered to  
acquire chip maker VLSI Technology for more than $806 million, or 
$17 a share, in a move that would give it a platform to expand in 
the United States. 

</P>
<P>
	Datum rose 1 11/16 to 8 7/16.  
</P>
<P>
	The Irvine, Calif.-based company beat Wall Street analysts'  
earnings expectations for the fourth quarter. The company is a 
maker of frequency products for telecommunications networks. 

</P>
<P>
	Hytek Microsystems fell 7/8 to 1 1/2.  
</P>
<P>
	The Carson City, Nev.-based microelectronic circuits producer  
said its largest customer, Chesapeake Sciences Corp. of 
Millersville, Md., has placed all open orders on an indefinite 
``hold'' status. 

</P>
</TEXT>
