<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tobacco Executive Charged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- A tobacco company executive was charged  
with helping smugglers scheme to sell nearly $700 million worth of 
cigarettes on the Canadian black market. 
</P>
<P>
	Leslie Thompson, a former R.J. Reynolds executive, was arrested  
this week in Detroit on money laundering charges. He is the first 
tobacco industry executive charged in the federal government's 
investigation into tobacco and alcohol smuggling through the St. 
Regis Mohawk Reservation in northern New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The smugglers told U.S. customs agents that the Canadian  
cigarettes they were carrying were being brought to the United 
States, prior to being exported to Russia. Instead, they were 
shipped to the St. Regis reservation, and smuggled across the St. 
Lawrence River back into Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	The smugglers avoided paying excise taxes to the United States  
and then cheated the Canadian government out of millions of dollars 
more. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant U.S. Attorney Gregory West said Friday that it  
appeared Thompson was preparing to flee the country when arrested. 
Thompson, 51, of Harper Woods, Mich., was ordered held without bail 
and will be returned to Syracuse for prosecution, West said. 
</P>
<P>
	If convicted of money laundering, Thompson could face up to 20  
years in prison. The government also is seeking to seize $87 
million in illicit assets from Thompson, West said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two dozen people have already been convicted in the case and are  
awaiting sentencing. In December, Northern Brands International, an 
R.J. Reynolds subsidiary, admitted helping the smuggling ring and 
paid $15 million in fines and forfeitures. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson was an R.J. Reynolds marketing executive in 1992 when  
he allegedly met Larry V. Miller and Lewis and Robert Tavano of 
Niagara Falls, the men convicted of masterminding the smuggling 
operation. Thompson arranged to have the company's Canadian-brand 
cigarettes, Export A's, exported to the smugglers in the United 
States, the indictment said. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal investigators first linked Thompson to Miller and the  
Tavanos through their meetings at Sonora Island Lodge in British 
Columbia in 1995. A witness, Michael Mangan, a truck driver for the 
smuggling ring, testified about the meetings to a federal grand 
jury in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``We sat around this big fireplace, and there was a big  
discussion about smuggling of the cigarettes, and Les Thompson was 
present at this meeting,'' Mangan testified in April 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for R.J. Reynolds International said the allegations  
against Thompson run ``completely contrary'' to corporate policy. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a serious matter for the company and it's to the  
detriment of the company,'' spokesman Adam Bryan-Brown said. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson was placed on administrative leave after the company  
began an internal investigation into the allegations of Northern 
Brands' complicity with smugglers, said C. Stephen Heard, the 
company 's lawyer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
