<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spy Sentenced to 24 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) -- A former National Security Agency  
intelligence analyst was sentenced Friday to 24 years in prison for 
selling top-secret documents to the Soviet KGB for $60,000. 
</P>
<P>
	David Sheldon Boone, 46, pleaded guilty in federal court in  
December to conspiracy to commit espionage. 
</P>
<P>
	Boone was arrested in a sting operation in which a former FBI  
agent posing as a KGB representative asked him to resume his 
spying, most of which was carried out while he was posted in 
Germany from 1988 to 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	The documents included material on tactical nuclear weapons  
targeting the Soviet bloc and a 300- to 400-page handbook listing 
reconnaissance and intelligence-collection systems used by the U.S. 
military. 
</P>
<P>
	Boone put American pilots' lives in danger by selling the  
documents, prosecutor Thomas Connolly said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I regret the actions I took. They were wrong. They  
overshadowed anything good I've done in my life before and after,'' 
Boone told Judge Albert V. Bryan Jr. ``I'm glad it's over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boone was trained in cryptoanalysis and Russian and had been  
assigned to an Army field station in Augsburg, Germany. The former 
Army sergeant also worked at NSA headquarters at Fort Meade, Md. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
