<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ship Line Accused of Falsification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A federal grand jury has accused Royal  
Caribbean Cruises Ltd. of falsifying oil discharge records on a 
ship that stopped at California ports in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Records for the Nordic Prince were falsified to show that  
pollution prevention equipment was working properly during several 
excursions, according to the indictment returned Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The equipment, designed to separate oil from wastewater being  
dumped into the sea, was inoperative, the indictment charged. It 
does not accuse the cruise line of actually dumping oil. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokeswoman for Miami-based Royal Caribbean said the  
allegations appear to duplicate charges to which the company 
pleaded guilty last year in Miami and Puerto Rico. 
</P>
<P>
	``As far as we're concerned, this has already been acknowledged  
and apologized for -- totally inexcusable -- and we've already paid a 
fine and implemented a compliance plan,'' spokeswoman Lynn 
Martenstein said. 
</P>
<P>
	Royal Caribbean paid $9 million in fines, but the deal did not  
insulate the company from other charges. Prosecutors said Royal 
Caribbean had not cooperated fully, The New York Times reported 
today, and that indictments were also expected in Alaska and New 
York. 
</P>
<P>
	The new indictment stems from Coast Guard inspections of Nordic  
Prince records between January and October of 1994, according to a 
statement issued by the U.S. Attorney's Office. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
