<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soybean Oil at 11-Year Low  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Soybean futures extended a week-long skid on the Chicago Board  
of Trade, this time undercut as soybean oil prices tumbled Friday 
to an 11-year low. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, sugar and orange juice futures also fell  
sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean oil futures fell amid concern that China would join a  
list of countries canceling orders for the food ingredient while 
waiting for the market to settle. China is one of the largest 
customers for U.S. soybean oil. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices of soybean oil and Malaysian palm oil have plunged after  
India and Pakistan recently canceled orders made when prices were 
20 percent higher. Analysts say importing countries, some of whom 
are strapped for cash, now appear content to wait for prices to 
bottom before stepping back into the market. 
</P>
<P>
	With soybean prices at their lowest point in more than two  
decades, traders are concerned there could be a surge in processing 
the crop, something that will increase soybean oil inventories. 
</P>
<P>
	Meantime, Brazil, the world's second-largest grower behind the  
United States, is set to harvest a near-record competing soybean 
crop. It also is in the midst of a currency crisis that is making 
Brazilian commodities cheaper on world markets, helping its sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans for March delivery fell 4 3/4 cents to $4.49 3/4 a bushel;  
March soybean oil fell 0.37 cent to 17.62 cents a pound. 
</P>
<P>
	March sugar futures tumbled nearly 8 percent in heavy selling on  
the Board of Trade of the City of New York as the monthly 
contract's last day of trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Sugar futures have been on the defensive for months, pressured  
by bumper world supplies and fears Brazil, the world's largest 
grower, would export large amounts of its crop to help ease 
economic problems and bring in hard currency. 
</P>
<P>
	March sugar fell 0.53 cent to 6.34 cents a pound.  
</P>
<P>
	Frozen, concentrated orange juice futures retreated on the Board  
of Trade of the City of New York amid concern about weak demand. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders were concerned that with the peak winter consumption  
period winding down, there will be fewer takers of orange juice, in 
which there were record inventories last week, according to the 
USDA. While Florida, the nation's biggest grower, is expected to 
produce a smaller crop this year, ample supplies remain. 
</P>
<P>
	Orange juice inventories are expected to continue to grow even  
further. The U.S. Agriculture Department's recent monthly update on 
supply and demand said the Florida crop will be 2 percent, or 4 
million boxes, larger than an earlier estimate of 194 million 
boxes. 
</P>
<P>
	May orange juice fell 2.35 cents to 80.95 cents a pound.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
