<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Feb. 26, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Certifies Mexico on Drugs  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- President Clinton said today he is  
certifying that Mexico is a fully cooperating partner in the fight 
against drug trafficking. In a foreign policy address, he praised 
Mexican efforts to fight drugs. Clinton praised President Ernesto 
Zedillo of Mexico for ``working hard to tackle the corruption 
traffickers headlong.'' ``He cannot win this battle alone,'' 
Clinton said. ``And neither can we.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Cites World Concerns  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- President Clinton said today Americans  
``must embrace the inexorable logic of globalization.'' Speaking to 
business and policy leaders, he outlined his foreign policy for the 
final two years of his administration. Clinton faced criticism over 
the standoff with Iraq and peace talks on Kosovo. He defended China 
on the same day that the State Department reported a sharp erosion 
of human rights in that country. 

</P>
<P>
	Sen. Kerry Won't Run for President  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Sen. John Kerry of Massachusetts announced today  
he won't enter the 2000 presidential race. The three-term 
Democratic senator said: ``I have concluded that to raise the 
necessary amount of money with only 10 months to do so, compounded 
by the newly accelerated primary schedule, is simply impossible at 
this time.'' Kerry also said that pulling out of the race could 
help Vice President Al Gore win the Democratic nomination, which 
``may be more helpful to our party's efforts.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Marine Jet Pilot Testifies  
</P>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- Marine Capt. Richard Ashby testified  
today about how his jet cut an Italian ski gondola cable, killing 
20 people. At his court martial, Ashby said: ``We never 
intentionally did anything outside the scope of this mission, which 
was to try to maintain 1,000 feet'' and use terrain to practice 
avoiding enemy radar. But he admitted: ``Mistakes were made on this 
flight -- and any flight, any mission you fly, mistakes are made.'' 
The Mount Cermis accident was Feb. 3, 1998. 

</P>
<P>
	Austria Avalanche Bodies Found  
</P>
<P>
	LANDECK, Austria (AP) -- The search for avalanche victims drew  
near a close today in the Austrian Alps, where exhausted rescuers 
found four more bodies, bringing the death toll to 37. A little 
girl was still missing and presumed dead. More than 4,000 tourists 
have now streamed out of ski resorts in the Paznaun valley, where a 
pair of deadly snowslides crushed the villages of Galtuer and 
Valzur earlier this week. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: Israel to Indict U.S. Teen  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- An American teen-ager accused of a killing in  
Maryland is to be indicted for the crime in an Israeli court on 
Monday, Channel 2 television reported today. The Justice Ministry 
had said that by law Samuel Sheinbein must be indicted within five 
days. He will be charged with the slaying of an acquaintance in 
Maryland in 1997. Israel's Supreme Court ruled that Sheinbein has 
Israeli citizenship even though he has never lived here, and that 
he cannot be extradited to the United States 

</P>
<P>
	Cigar Warning Labels Recommended  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Cigars are as deadly as cigarettes yet face  
virtually no federal regulation, government health officials said 
today, recommending a mandatory national warning label for the 
first time. Requiring health warnings on cigarettes and smokeless 
tobacco but not cigars sends the wrong message, Surgeon General 
David Satcher said. 

</P>
<P>
	Nobel-Winner Glenn Seaborg Dies  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Glenn Seaborg, the Nobel Prize-winning  
physicist who discovered 10 atomic elements including plutonium and 
one that now bears his name, has died. He was 86. Seaborg died last 
night at his home in Lafayette, near Berkeley, while convalescing 
from a stroke . 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Economy Is Sizzling  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite the global financial crisis, the U.S.  
economy grew at a sizzling 6.1 percent annual rate in the final 
three months of 1998, the fastest pace in nearly 15 years. The 
Commerce Department reported today on the gross domestic product, 
the nation's total output of goods and services. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Down; Dow Off 59.76  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock indexes fell today, led by a selloff in  
technology shares, after Compaq's warning of soft sales raised 
concerns of a slowdown in the computer market. The Dow Jones 
industrial average ended down 59.76 at 9,306.58. On the NYSE, 
losers led gainers 1,511-1,458. The technology-heavy Nasdaq 
composite index fell 38.81 to 2,288.01. 

</P>
<P>
	D-Backs Get Womack From Bucs  
</P>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- The Arizona Diamondbacks obtained National League  
stolen base leader Tony Womack from the Pittsburgh Pirates today 
for a minor league outfielder and a player to be named. The 
Diamondbacks had been trying for weeks to get Womack, the NL steals 
leader the last two seasons. Arizona will use Womack as its leadoff 
batter. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  
</P>
