<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Wants $153M for Farm Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is asking Congress for $153  
million to make emergency loans to farmers and hire additional 
employees to process requests for disaster assistance. 
</P>
<P>
	His proposal would provide $1.1 billion in direct or guaranteed  
loans for an estimated 10,000 producers who can't get credit from 
private sources. The Agriculture Department is running out of money 
to make loans because of the heavy demand for credit. 
</P>
<P>
	``Economic turmoil in the Pacific Rim countries and around the  
world continue to make it difficult for American farmers and 
ranchers to export their goods overseas,'' Clinton said Friday. 
``More and more farmers need loans to see them through to better 
times.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Because of the gloomy farm economy, many bankers are skittish  
about lending money to marginal farmers unless the government 
guarantees the loans. 
</P>
<P>
	``Without this help many farmers simply would not be able to put  
in their spring crops,'' said Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, USDA officials have come under criticism as they  
struggle to keep up with requests from farmers for $6 billion in 
disaster assistance approved by Congress last fall. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's request earmarks $43 million for hiring temporary  
staff in USDA's county offices. 
</P>
<P>
	``To date the vast majority of farmers haven't been signed up to  
receive relief,'' said House Agriculture Committee Chairman, Larry 
Combest, R-Texas. ``I don't know what's going on down at the 
department, but I do know that our farmers can't wait forever for 
this money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman predicted earlier this week  
that farmers will face another year of lagging exports and low 
prices. 
</P>
<P>
	USDA has lowered farm export projections to $49 billion -- down  
from last year's $53.6 billion. Farm income could fall at least $3 
billion, according to the agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
