<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Rise on Tame Inflation Data / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices rallied Friday, ending a three-day  
slump, after a report of tame inflation eased worries that the 
Federal Reserve might raise interest rates to cool inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 1 3/32  
points, or $10.94 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves 
in the opposite direction, fell to 5.57 percent after climbing to a 
six-month high of 5.65 percent late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The surge came after the Commerce Department reported that  
inflation rose just 1 percent last year -- the slowest pace since a 
0.9 percent rise in 1949 -- despite healthy economic growth. 
</P>
<P>
	The report came as a relief to bond investors who had been  
worried that rapid economic expansion would force the Fed to raise 
interest rates to keep inflation in check. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
were up between 3/32 point and 5/32 point, and intermediate 
maturities were up between 9/32 point to 7/16 point, reported 
Bridge Telerate, a financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lehman Brothers Daily Treasury Bond Index, reflecting price  
movements on bonds with maturities of a year or longer, fell 2.2 
points to 1,281.98 from Thursday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.66 percent as the  
discount rose 0.04 percentage point to 4.55 percent. Six-month 
yields were 4.70 percent, as the discount rose 0.02 percentage 
point to 4.54 percent. One-year yields were 4.84 percent as the 
discount fell 0.01 percentage point fell to 4.63 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, fell to 4.88 percent from 5.00 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds rose 17/32 point to 124 5/8. The average 
yield to maturity fell to 5.17 percent from 5.20 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
