<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	A storm that pounded New England coastal areas with more than a  
foot of snow was easing a bit early today as it headed back toward 
the Atlantic. Unsettled weather was spreading rain and 
thunderstorms into the nation's midsection. 
</P>
<P>
	A few more inches of snow was expected over eastern  
Massachusetts and southern New Hampshire, but heavy snowfall was 
possible in eastern Maine. 
</P>
<P>
	Much quieter weather should return to inland areas of the  
Northeast, with partly cloudy skies likely from the Ohio Valley 
into the Southeast. Gulf Coast thunderstorms were possible. 
</P>
<P>
	A developing storm system threatened to spread rain and isolated  
heavy storms from the eastern Dakotas and western Great Lakes to 
the southern Plains, and then deep into the Mississippi Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	Across the far northern Plains, rain could switch over to light  
snow. 
</P>
<P>
	Snow also was moving toward the Rockies, with accumulations of  
up to 6 inches possible. 
</P>
<P>
	Another storm system was taking aim at the Pacific Northwest.  
Rain and snow was possible from western Washington into 
northwestern California. Locally heavy rainfall over coastal 
Washington and Oregon could produce flooding, and up to a foot of 
Cascades snow was possible. 
</P>
<P>
	Mostly fair conditions should prevail across southern California  
and the desert Southwest. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's hot spot Thursday in the Lower 48 states was  
McAllen, Texas, with a high reading of 82 degrees. The coldest 
place was Clayton Lake, Maine, with a low of 16 below zero. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's temperatures should range from the 30s in New England,  
the far northern Plains and the Great Lakes to the 80s along the 
Gulf Coast, with readings into the 40s in the Northeast and upper 
Midwest; the 50s in the Ohio Valley, Pacific Northwest and central 
Plains; and the 60s and 70s across the South. 
</P>
</TEXT>
