<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cubs' Woods Works Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MESA, Ariz. (AP) -- Kerry Wood's first workout in five days  
wasn't a taxing one. Some long tosses, some stretching, some 
limited running. The NL Rookie of the Year, slowed by illness, 
admitted he has a way to go to get in game shape. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said Friday he'll ready for the start of the season that  
is still five weeks away. 
</P>
<P>
	``No doubt in my mind,'' Wood said.  
</P>
<P>
	He was hospitalized briefly this week for tests for an upper  
respiratory infection, his second of the spring. He was also 
hospitalized a week ago with an intestinal virus, meaning he's been 
feeling poorly for the last month. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm behind a little bit,'' Wood said. ``But I got plenty of  
time to be where I need to be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wood said he lost 14 pounds at one point, gained some back and  
then lost some more. At 6-foot-5, he's now at 233 pounds, about 
where he wants to be. 
</P>
<P>
	Wood was surprised by the attention his illness received.  
</P>
<P>
	``I got sick. Everybody gets sick,'' he said. ``We've got four  
or five guys in the clubhouse with the same thing. That's what is 
going around down here. Unfortunately, I had it for a while and 
couldn't get rid of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cubs general manager Ed Lynch this week said he expects the Cubs  
to have a contract worked out with Wood's agent before the start of 
exhibition games next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Wood said he hadn't given it any thought.  
</P>
<P>
	``I've been too sick to think,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* Outfielder Lance Johnson and catcher Benito Santiago are  
also ill. The Cubs had 48 of their 52 players on the spring 
training roster at the first full-squad workout. Santiago skipped 
the drills, and catcher Pat Cline was excused because of a death in 
the family. Manny Alexander and Sammy Sosa had not arrived at camp. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
