<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Able To Attack Taiwan by 2005 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- By 2005, China will have the capability to  
attack Taiwan with highly effective air and missile strikes and to 
blockade Taiwan's main ports, the Pentagon has concluded. 
</P>
<P>
	In a report to Congress released Friday, the Pentagon did not  
predict a Chinese attack on Taiwan but painted a picture of the 2.5 
million-man People's Liberation Army growing more modern and 
effective even as it shrinks in numbers and struggles with morale 
problems and weaknesses in air transport. 
</P>
<P>
	For a Chinese invasion of Taiwan to succeed it would have to  
conduct a multifaceted campaign involving air assault, amphibious 
landings, a naval blockade, sustained conventional missile strikes 
and other support actions -- a feat it could achieve only with 
``great difficulty'' by 2005, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nevertheless, the campaign likely would succeed,'' it said,  
unless the United States intervened to aid Taiwan. 
</P>
<P>
	The communist government in Beijing views Taiwan as a renegade  
province and insists it not seek international recognition as a 
separate state. It has refused to renounce the option of using 
force against Taiwan and has stated that it might do so under any 
of three circumstances: If Taiwan declared independence, if a 
foreign power intervened to stop reunification or if Taiwan gained 
nuclear arms. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. policy is to view Taiwan as part of China, although it  
sells defensive arms to the island. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon report said China is ``still decades'' away from  
possessing the capability to defeat a modern military force beyond 
China's borders. Its emphasis has been on developing innovative 
ways of using its strengths -- such as advanced cruise missiles and 
ballistic missiles -- to exploit an enemy's weaknesses. 
</P>
<P>
	``This approach potentially will give Beijing the `credible  
intimidation' needed to accomplish political and military goals 
without having to rely on overwhelming force-on-force 
superiority,'' the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	China's main focus now is on improving its ability to fight near  
its borders, including Taiwan and the South China Sea, it said. 
China views its growing force of ballistic missiles as ``a potent 
military and political weapon'' to influence Taiwan's people and 
their leaders, it added. 
</P>
<P>
	The report said that if China were to invade Taiwan it probably  
would begin by blockading ports with mines laid by submarines and 
channeling Taiwan naval vessels into areas where they would be 
vulnerable to anti-ship missiles. Without outside help, Taiwan 
probably would not be able to keep the island's key ports and sea 
lines of communication open. Taiwan's merchant ships and warships 
would be a ``serious risk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	From that point, China likely would follow quickly with  
``massive missile strikes'' and then an invasion. 
</P>
<P>
	By 2005, the People's Liberation Army will have deployed two  
types of shorter-range ballistic missiles and a first-generation 
land-attack cruise missile, the Pentagon predicted. This expanded 
arsenal of missiles targeted against key airfields and 
communications links will constrain Taiwan's military operations. 
</P>
<P>
	China is giving high priority to development of land-attack  
cruise missiles and is aggressively acquiring foreign technology 
for these weapons, particularly from Russia, the report said. The 
first land-attack cruise missile to enter production probably will 
be air-launched and could be operational shortly after the turn of 
the century. 
</P>
<P>
	The emphasis on offensive missiles has given rise to talk of the  
United States developing an anti-missile defense for Taiwan -- an 
idea that has angered China and complicated already strained 
relations with Washington. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is 
visiting Beijing next week. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon report said China is focused on other areas where  
its adversaries might be vulnerable, such as space. It already has 
the capability, for example, to detect and track most satellites. 
Beijing apparently is researching anti-satellite laser weaponry and 
``already may possess the capability to damage, under specific 
conditions, optical sensors'' on certain kinds of satellites, it 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
