<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Red Sox To Settle Harassment Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The Boston Red Sox agreed to settle a harassment  
case brought by a former employee who said he was the victim of 
racially motivated threats. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas Sneed, who worked for the Red Sox for seven years, left  
the organization amid allegations the team failed to thoroughly 
investigate racial harassment against him. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other things, Sneed, who is black, said a photograph of  
himself and his white fiancee was defaced with a racial epithet. 
</P>
<P>
	In another incident, a picture of the woman was covered over  
with one of a nanny whose mutilated body was found near the 
baseball park last year. Sneed said he interpreted that act as a 
threat. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the settlement agreement between Sneed and the team,  
the Massachusetts Commission Against Discrimination withdrew its 
earlier finding that Sneed had probable cause to move forward with 
his complaint against the team. 
</P>
<P>
	In Friday's announcement, club officials reported they have  
hired someone to consult on diversity and discrimination issues, 
but didn't reveal whether there was a financial settlement with 
Sneed. 
</P>
<P>
	Sneed, now with Bell Atlantic Corp., was first hired by the club  
as a part-time security guard while a student at Northeastern 
University. 
</P>
<P>
	He later became sales manager of the team's ``600 Club,''  
managing, he said, annual sales of $10 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Sneed has previously said team officials told him to keep quiet  
about the allegations of harassment, and urged him not to tell his 
fiancee. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Sox denied, however, that their investigation of the  
events was halfhearted. Officials said they hired outside lawyers, 
and a private investigation agency and cooperated with police and 
the telephone company in their inquiries. 
</P>
<P>
	Red Sox officials did not immediately return telephone messages  
left Friday evening at their Boston offices and their spring 
training headquarters in Fort Myers, Fla. 

</P>
</TEXT>
