<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Upholds Nichols' Conviction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- A federal appeals court on Friday upheld Terry  
Nichols' conspiracy conviction and life sentence in the Oklahoma 
City bombing, rejecting a defense claim that the trial judge had 
erred in his instructions to the jury. 
</P>
<P>
	Nichols was sentenced to life and ordered to pay $14.5 million  
in restitution to victims of the April 19, 1995 bombing, which 
killed 168 people and injured 500 others. 
</P>
<P>
	Co-defendant Timothy McVeigh was convicted of first-degree  
murder, conspiracy and weapons-related charges and sentenced to 
death. His lawyers have appealed his sentence and conviction to the 
U.S. Supreme Court. 
</P>
<P>
	Nichols' lawyers argued there were 11 grounds for dismissal of  
his conviction and life sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	The 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals rejected a defense claim  
that U.S. District Judge Richard Matsch should have told the jury 
that Nichols could not be sentenced to life imprisonment unless he 
had ``a specific intent to kill.'' The jury acquitted Nichols on 
charges of first-degree murder and using a weapon of mass 
destruction. 
</P>
<P>
	The court rejected a claim that Matsch should have barred  
testimony from a British forensic expert who testified that a bomb 
in the cargo compartment of a Ryder truck allegedly rented by 
McVeigh was the source of the explosion. The defense claimed she 
exceeded her level of expertise. 
</P>
<P>
	The appeals court also rejected Nichols' claim that he should  
have been allowed to introduce a former FBI agent as an expert 
witness. Dr. Frederick Whitehurst had evidence questioning 
prosecutors' claims that fertilizer crystals found on truck pieces 
could have survived a night in the rain, defense lawyer Michael 
Tigar said. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the court rejected claims that the judge should have  
refused to admit the testimony of informant Michael Fortier, who 
testified in exchange for a plea bargain. 
</P>
<P>
	Fortier pleaded guilty to failing to alert authorities to the  
bomb plot and was sentenced to 12 years in prison. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
