<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FAA Probes Marine Jets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Aviation Administration is looking  
into what caused a pair of Marine Corps fighter jets to diverge 
from their flight pattern and pass within a mile of a commuter 
plane. 
</P>
<P>
	The Washington Post said the incident occurred Thursday when two  
F/A-18 Hornet fighters came too close to a United Express commuter 
plane about 35 miles from its destination -- Dulles International 
Airport outside of Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	The two jets out of Andrews Air Force Base violated regulations  
by coming within 300 feet in altitude and a mile in horizontal 
distance from the plane, FAA spokeswoman Arlene Salac said Friday. 
The aircraft should have been at least 1000 feet apart in vertical 
distance and three miles horizontally, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	A preliminary review attributed the incident to an error by the  
fighter pilots, who had been awaiting approval from air traffic 
controllers to maneuver over Quantico Marine Corps Base. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Rinaldi, president of the Air Traffic Control Association  
at Dulles, said the jets were 20 seconds away from striking the 
commuter plane. 
</P>
<P>
	The Marine Corps said the fighters never endangered the computer  
plane and were on course to pass behind the flight. ``They were 
never on a collision course,'' said Sgt. Jeffrey Foster. 
</P>
</TEXT>
