<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Throws Out Teen Sex Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) -- A judge has thrown out a teen-age sex  
lawsuit, apologizing to jurors as he dismissed a couple's claim 
that another parent was to blame for their daughter's pregnancy. 
</P>
<P>
	``In more than 25 years as a judge, this is one of the weakest,  
if not most frivolous cases I've ever been involved in,'' Lancaster 
County District Judge Jeffre Cheuvront said Thursday. ``I'm 
embarrassed that the jury has been exposed to, in my opinion, 
blatantly mendacious testimony.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Doug and Sharon Detmer of Lincoln had sued Dawn Bixler, alleging  
she was negligent because she knew their daughter and her son were 
having sex and condoned it. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit was believed to be the first of its kind in the  
country. 
</P>
<P>
	Detmer said he and his wife were unaware their daughter, Leanne,  
was having sex with the boy, Dallas Mills, after the two 
16-year-olds began dating in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The girl told them she was pregnant in April 1997 and had an  
abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	Mills refused to comment after the trial, but his mother said  
she was relieved. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just glad that it's over,'' Ms. Bixler said. ``I just wish  
I could have told my side of the story.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Detmers declined to comment. Their lawyer, D. Kirk  
Wolgamott, said he was considering an appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Bixler's lawyer, Susan Strong, maintained from the start  
that the lawsuit was frivolous because the sex was consensual. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wish this would've been thrown out a long time ago,'' she  
said. ``It's too bad these people had to go through this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leanne Detmer testified she that she had sex at her boyfriend's  
house because his mother condoned the activity. 
</P>
<P>
	``I liked being at their house because we could do what we  
wanted. There were no rules over there,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	She also testified there was little her parents could have done  
to stop her from having sex with Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	The Detmers had asked for more than $11,000 in medical expenses  
to pay for the abortion and an unspecified amount of general 
damages. The medical expenses also included cost of the treating 
the girl's depression, which they said was worsened by the 
pregnancy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
