<HEADLINE> Nuggets' LaFrentz Done for Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- The MRI performed Friday on the left knee of  
Denver Nuggets rookie Raef LaFrentz revealed what the team already 
knew -- and more. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nuggets were aware LaFrentz tore the anterior cruciate  
ligament in his left knee on Thursday night against Dallas, and 
knew he would miss the rest of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	The MRI revealed a small tear of the lateral meniscus in the  
same knee. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Steve Traina, the team's orthopedic surgeon, will operate to  
repair the knee, but no date has been set. Traina ruled LaFrentz 
out for the season, but estimated he could return to basketball in 
6-8 months. 
</P>
<P>
	LaFrentz tore the ligament on a drive to the basket in the first  
quarter of Denver's 90-81 loss to Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm disappointed for myself and for the team,'' LaFrentz said  
Friday. ``It is my first major injury. I have to remain positive 
and do the rehab so I can come back strong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	LaFrentz, the third pick in last June's NBA draft, averaged 14.9  
points and 8.1 rebounds in his first 11 games this season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
