<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Child Internet-Sex Charge Dismissed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- Charges against an Eau Claire man have been  
thrown out by the Wisconsin Supreme Court in a ruling that struck 
down part of the state's anti-pornography law. 
</P>
<P>
	The court dismissed two counts of sexual exploitation of a child  
against Joel Zarnke, 59, who was accused of downloading Internet 
pictures of naked boys and distributing them in 1995 and 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	In a 6-1 ruling Friday, the justices struck down the portion of  
a 1987 law used to charge Zarnke, ruling it unconstitutional 
because it requires the defendant to prove his or her lack of 
knowledge of the child's age and violates the First Amendment. 
</P>
<P>
	Zarnke, who is out of jail on bond, will still be prosecuted on  
charges of child enticement and possession of child pornography, 
prosecutor Raymond Pelrine said. A trial has not been scheduled. 
</P>
<P>
	Zarnke has pleaded innocent. If convicted of both charges, he  
faces up to 12 years in prison and a $20,000 fine. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the ruling, it is still against federal law to  
distribute child pornography, said Jim Haney, spokesman for state 
Attorney General James Doyle. 
</P>
<P>
	``The state Legislature needs to repair the state statute,''  
Haney said. ``The most important message is that distribution of 
child pornography remains a crime.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
