<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baby Sitter To Get $1 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- A couple who accused their baby  
sitter of stealing $752 while they cruised the Bahamas in their 
yacht have agreed to pay the woman $1 million for causing her 
emotional distress. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement Thursday ends a seven-year battle between Charles  
and Bonnie Abel and Beth Cunningham, who lived down the street from 
the couple. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Cunningham, 34, was acquitted in 1994 of grand theft for  
allegedly stealing from the couple's bank account with their ATM 
card. She then sued the Abels. 
</P>
<P>
	A jury took only 45 minutes to decide the couple owed Ms.  
Cunningham $787,800 in compensatory damages. The jury was about to 
consider punitive damages when the two sides reached an settlement 
of $1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Ms. Cunningham, the Abels asked her in 1992 to stay  
with their 7-year-old daughter for a week while they went on a 
cruise on their 52-foot yacht and gave her $100 for expenses. Then, 
she said, they called to say they were extending their trip by 
three weeks and gave Ms. Cunningham their ATM number. She withdrew 
$952 from the account. 
</P>
<P>
	After the couple's return, they accused her of stealing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
