<DOCNO> APW19990226.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-26 22:44:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Inmate in Solitary Wins Jury Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- A jury has ordered prison officials to  
pay $660,000 in damages to an inmate who was locked in solitary 
confinement for 23 hours a day for more than four years. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal jury found that David McClary, convicted of killing a  
police officer, was subjected to mental distress and his civil 
rights were violated by state prison officials who kept him 
confined to a small cell from late 1989 through early 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for the state said they will ask U.S. Magistrate  
Jonathan Feldman to set aside the verdict and are considering an 
appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	McClary, 33, is serving 25 years to life for killing an officer  
who was guarding the home of a witness in a drug case in 1988. 
Prison officials said the notoriety of McClary's crime put him at 
risk in the general prison population. 
</P>
<P>
	But after hearing two weeks of testimony, a jury on Tuesday  
night found former state prisons Commissioner Thomas Coughlin III 
and three former superintendents at Attica and Wende prisons in 
western New York liable for damages. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials were within their rights for initially putting McClary  
in a 23-hour-a-day lockup but they violated his rights by his 
continued confinement there, the jury decided. There is no law in 
New York state on how long prisoners can be held in solitary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
